{"title_page": "Kho people", "text_new": "{{short description|Indo-Aryan ethnolinguistic group from northern part of the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{infobox ethnic group\n|group= Kho people \n|native_name= \u06a9\u06be\u0648\n|caption = Wooden untensil use by the Kho tribe in Chitral\n|regions= [[Chitral District|Chitral]] and neighbouring areas\n|region1= {{flag|Pakistan}} \n|pop1= 313,000 (2016)<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\">{{cite web |title=Khowar |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/khw |website=Ethnologue |accessdate=25 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|ref1= \n|total = 332,200<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n|total_year = \n|rels = [[Hanafi]] [[Sunni]] [[Islam]],<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> [[Ismailism|Ismaili]] [[Islam]]<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> <br /> \n|langs = [[Khowar language|Khowar]]\n|related= [[Kalasha people]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Kho''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a}},<ref name=\"O'LearyRensch1992\">{{cite book|last1=O'Leary|first1=Clare F.|last2=Rensch|first2=Calvin Ross|last3=Decker|first3=Sandra J.|title=Sociolinguistic Survey of Northern Pakistan: Languages of Chitral|year=1992|publisher=National Institute of Pakistan Studies at Quaid-i-Azam University|language=English|page=22}}</ref> {{lang-khw|\u06a9\u06be\u0648}}) or '''Chitrali people''' are an [[Indo-Aryan peoples|Indo-Aryan]] [[ethnolinguistic group]] associated with the [[Dardistan region]].<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> They speak Khowar, which is a member of the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] subgroup of the [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] language family.<ref name=\"Olson1998\">{{cite book|last=Olson|first=James Stuart|title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of China|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|language=English|isbn=9780313288531|page=177}}</ref> Many Kho people live in the [[Chitral District|Chitral]], [[Ghizer District|Ghizer]] and [[Gilgit-Baltistan]] districts of [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Kho people are likely descendants of those who migrated to their present location in Chitral from the south.<ref name=\"Cacopardo1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Cacopardo |first1=Alberto |title=The Other Kalasha A Survey of Kalashamun-Speaking People in Southern Chitral: Part I: The Eastern Area |journal=East and West |date=1991 |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=273\u2013310 |publisher=Istituto Italiano per l'Africa e l'Oriente (IsIAO) |language=English |quote=... the language even today, while the rest are Kho people who have moved in from the south.|jstor=29756980 }}</ref> Prior to their Islamisation, the Kho people followed a culture that is described to be of the Peristani-type, and practiced a faith akin to that observed by the Kalash today,<ref name=\"BashirUddin1996\">{{cite book |last1=Bashir |first1=Elena |last2=ud-Din |first2=Israr |title=Proceedings of the Second International Hindukush Cultural Conference |date=1996 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-577571-6 |page=viii |language=English |quote=Before conversion, the Kho people had the same beliefs as the Kalasha have even to this day.}}</ref><ref name=\"CacopardoCacopardo2001\">{{cite book|last1=Cacopardo|first1=Alberto M.|last2=Cacopardo|first2=Augusto S.|title=Gates of Peristan: history, religion and society in the Hindu Kush|year=2001|publisher=[[Istituto Italiano per l'Africa e l'Oriente]]|language=English|page=48}}</ref> which has been classified as a form of Hinduism and likened to the ancient Greek religion.<ref name=\"West2010\">{{cite book|last=West|first=Barbara A.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCiNqFj3MQsC&pg=PA357|title=Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania|date=19 May 2010|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|language=English|isbn=9781438119137|page=357|quote=The Kalasha are a unique people living in just three valleys near Chitral, Pakistan [...] During the mid-20th century a few Kalasha villages in Pakistan were forcibly converted to this dominant religion, but the people fought the conversion and once official pressure was removed the vast majority continued to practice their own religion. Their religion is a form of Hinduism that recognizes many gods and spirits and has been related to the religion of the ancient Greeks [...]  given their Indo-Aryan language, ... the religion of the Kalasha is much more closely aligned to the Hinduism of their Indian neighbors that to the religion of Alexander the Great and his armies.}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2020}} After the arrival of [[Muslim conquests in the Indian subcontinent|Muslim rule in India]], many of the Kho converted to [[Islam]] in the fourthteenth century, though some previous customs continue to persist.<ref name=\"Bashir1996\">{{cite book |last1=Bashir |first1=Elena |title=Proceedings of the Second International Hindukush Cultural Conference |date=1996 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-577571-6 |page=140 |language=English |quote=This was a pre-Islamic custom in Kho society which has continued to exist even after the people converted to Islam in the fourteenth century, even though there is not any room for such beliefs in the religion.}}</ref> With respect to Islam, the Kho are primarily [[Ismaili Muslim]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Olson |first1=James Stuart |title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of China |date=1998 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-28853-1 |language=English |page=177 |quote=In the Upper Chitral region, most Kho are Ismaili Muslims, who the Hanafi Sunnis consider to be an inferior people.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nHistorically the Kho people reside in the [[Dardistan region]]. As such, they are a [[Dardic people|Dardic]] ethnic group located primarily in [[South Asia]]. Many of the Kho people live in the [[Chitral District]] of the Pakistani province of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and a smaller number also live in Ghizer District of Gilgit Baltistan (including the Yasin Valley, Phandar Ishkoman and Gupis). They are also found in few numbers in northern Afghanistan, where the majority of them live in the northern provinces of [[Badakhshan Province|Badakhshan]].<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n\n==Culture==\nKho culture places heavy emphasis on poetry, song and dance. Kho people also have a great respect of law and order. Much of this can be attributed to Chitral being a stable kingdom for most of its history,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalark.net/Pakistan/chitral.htm |title=chitral |publisher=Royalark.net |date=1 June 1937 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> where the rule of law and the will of the ruler came before tribal concepts such as revenge and isolationism. Many Kho believe that their customs and language is much more rich, polite, and sophisticated in comparison to their neighbours.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Human: The Definitive Visual Guide|last=|first=|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2004|isbn=0-7566-0520-2|editor-last=Winston|editor-first=Robert|location=New York|pages=433}}</ref>\n\nPolo is a popular sport and pastime for the Kho people. The polo traditionally played by the Kho has little rules or organisation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDance and music play a large role in Kho society. Common clothing include the ''salwar kameez'' (long tunic and trousers) and headwear includes the [[pakol]] (chitrali hat).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBecause of Chitral's location at the crossroads of [[Central Asia]] and South Asia, the Kho display a wide variety of cultures, largely depending upon their ancestral ethnic group and family history.\n\n==Languages==\nThe Kho people speak the [[Khowar language]], a member of the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] subgroup of the [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language family]]. The ethnologists [[:de:Karl Jettmar|Karl Jettmar]] and Lennart Edelberg noted, with respect to the Khowar language, that: \"Khowar, in many respects [is] the most archaic of all modern Indian languages, retaining a great part of [[Sanskrit]] case inflexion, and retaining many words in a nearly Sanskritic form.\u201d<ref name=\"JettmarEdelberg1974\">{{cite book|last1=Jettmar|first1=Karl|last2=Edelberg|first2=Lennart|title=Cultures of the Hindukush|year=1974|publisher=F. Steiner Verlag|language=English|isbn=9783515012171|page=3}}</ref>\n\nKhowar is spoken by about 247,000 Kho people in northern Pakistan,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thenewstribe.com/2012/01/25/khowar-language/ |title = Khowar Language|date = 25 January 2012}}</ref> Some of the Kho people use [[Urdu]] as a second language.<ref name=\"SimonsFenning2017\">{{cite book|last1=Simons|first1= Gary F. |last2=Fennig|first2=Charles D. |title=Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Twentieth Edition |year=2017|publisher=[[SIL International]]|location= Dallas|language=English}}</ref>\n\n== Genetics ==\nThe western Eurasian haplogroups were observed predominantly and mostly shared in Kho samples with overall frequency of 50%. These include HV8, H19, H57, H24, C and, C4a haplogroups. The South Asian haplogroups and its relevant subgroups including U4, U4c, U6, U5a, and W were also found in Kho samples with overall 37.5% frequency. The haplogroups and haplotypes specify the origin and linkages of an individual and population. The haplogroup analysis eventually demonstrates the western Eurasian ancestral origin of Kho samples. Another South Asian haplogroup, M30 was also identified for Kho samples with frequency of 6.2%. This indicates the genetic affiliation of Kho with the South Asian populations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aziz|first=Shahid|last2=Nawaz|first2=Mehwish|last3=Afridi|first3=Sahib Gul|last4=Khan|first4=Asifullah|date=2019-04-01|title=Genetic structure of Kho population from north-western Pakistan based on mtDNA control region sequences|journal=Genetica|language=en|volume=147|issue=2|pages=177\u2013183|doi=10.1007/s10709-019-00060-8|pmid=30887215|issn=1573-6857}}</ref>\n\n==Folk music==\n{{unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\nFolk singers and reed instrument players have a special respect in the Kho society and are featured in their festivities. The most common instruments are Surnai [[Shehnai]], Sitar, and reed instruments. The Kho sitar is a popular musical instrument in Chitral. It is made out of mulberry wood with five steel strings arranged in three courses, the outer ones have double strings, tuned in unison, while the inner course is single. Popular music of the area includes:\n* ''Shishtoo-war (Sauz)'', a popular folk music played with shehnai on happy occasions, mostly at marriages.\n* ''Shab-daraaz (Dani)'' is a sad tone based on heartbroken love poems.\n* ''Ghalhwar'' is a combination of Dani and Sauz. This is a mixture of fast and classical music played at the starting of a polo match.\n\n== Notable people from Chitral ==\n* [[Saleem Khan (politician)]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Khowar language]]\n* [[Khoshey people]]\n* [[Kashmiri people]]\n* [[Shina people]]\n* [[Brokpa]]s\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://chitraltoday.net/about-chitral/ chitraltoday.net]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Pakistan}}\n{{Ethnic groups in India}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in India]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Dardic peoples]]\n[[Category:Chitral District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indo-Aryan ethnolinguistic group from northern part of the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{infobox ethnic group\n|group= Kho people \n|native_name= \u06a9\u06be\u0648\n|caption = Wooden untensil use by the Kho tribe in Chitral\n|regions= [[Chitral District|Chitral]] and neighbouring areas\n|region1= {{flag|Pakistan}} \n|pop1= 313,000 (2016)<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\">{{cite web |title=Khowar |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/khw |website=Ethnologue |accessdate=25 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|ref1= \n|total = 332,200<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n|total_year = \n|rels = [[Hanafi]] [[Sunni]] [[Islam]],<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> [[Ismailism|Ismaili]] [[Islam]]<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> <br /> \n|langs = [[Khowar language|Khowar]]\n|related= [[Kalasha people]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Kho''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a}},<ref name=\"O'LearyRensch1992\">{{cite book|last1=O'Leary|first1=Clare F.|last2=Rensch|first2=Calvin Ross|last3=Decker|first3=Sandra J.|title=Sociolinguistic Survey of Northern Pakistan: Languages of Chitral|year=1992|publisher=National Institute of Pakistan Studies at Quaid-i-Azam University|language=English|page=22}}</ref> {{lang-khw|\u06a9\u06be\u0648}}) or '''Chitrali people''' are an [[Indo-Aryan peoples|Indo-Aryan]] [[ethnolinguistic group]] associated with the [[Dardistan region]].<ref name=\"Olson1998\"/> They speak Khowar, which is a member of the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] subgroup of the [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] language family.<ref name=\"Olson1998\">{{cite book|last=Olson|first=James Stuart|title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of China|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|language=English|isbn=9780313288531|page=177}}</ref> Many Kho people live in the [[Chitral District|Chitral]], [[Ghizer District|Ghizer]] and [[Gilgit-Baltistan]] districts of [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe Kho people are likely descendants of those who migrated to their present location in Chitral from the south.<ref name=\"Cacopardo1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Cacopardo |first1=Alberto |title=The Other Kalasha A Survey of Kalashamun-Speaking People in Southern Chitral: Part I: The Eastern Area |journal=East and West |date=1991 |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=273\u2013310 |publisher=Istituto Italiano per l'Africa e l'Oriente (IsIAO) |language=English |quote=... the language even today, while the rest are Kho people who have moved in from the south.|jstor=29756980 }}</ref> Prior to their Islamisation, the Kho people followed a culture that is described to be of the Dharmic-type, and practiced a faith akin to that observed by the Kalash today,<ref name=\"BashirUddin1996\">{{cite book |last1=Bashir |first1=Elena |last2=ud-Din |first2=Israr |title=Proceedings of the Second International Hindukush Cultural Conference |date=1996 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-577571-6 |page=viii |language=English |quote=Before conversion, the Kho people had the same beliefs as the Kalasha have even to this day.}}</ref><ref name=\"CacopardoCacopardo2001\">{{cite book|last1=Cacopardo|first1=Alberto M.|last2=Cacopardo|first2=Augusto S.|title=Gates of Peristan: history, religion and society in the Hindu Kush|year=2001|publisher=[[Istituto Italiano per l'Africa e l'Oriente]]|language=English|page=48}}</ref> which has been classified as a form of Hinduism and likened to the ancient Greek religion, however, given their Indo-Aryan language, it is evident that the religion of the Kho people is much more closely aligned to the Hinduism of their Indian neighbors.<ref name=\"West2010\">{{cite book|last=West|first=Barbara A.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCiNqFj3MQsC&pg=PA357|title=Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania|date=19 May 2010|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|language=English|isbn=9781438119137|page=357|quote=The Kalasha are a unique people living in just three valleys near Chitral, Pakistan [...] During the mid-20th century a few Kalasha villages in Pakistan were forcibly converted to this dominant religion, but the people fought the conversion and once official pressure was removed the vast majority continued to practice their own religion. Their religion is a form of Hinduism that recognizes many gods and spirits and has been related to the religion of the ancient Greeks [...]  given their Indo-Aryan language, ... the religion of the Kalasha is much more closely aligned to the Hinduism of their Indian neighbors that to the religion of Alexander the Great and his armies.}}</ref> After the arrival of [[Muslim conquests in the Indian subcontinent|Muslim administration in Northern India]], many of the Kho converted to [[Islam]] in the fourthteenth century, though some previous customs continue to persist.<ref name=\"Bashir1996\">{{cite book |last1=Bashir |first1=Elena |title=Proceedings of the Second International Hindukush Cultural Conference |date=1996 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-577571-6 |page=140 |language=English |quote=This was a pre-Islamic custom in Kho society which has continued to exist even after the people converted to Islam in the fourteenth century, even though there is not any room for such beliefs in the religion.}}</ref> With respect to Islam, the Kho are primarily [[Ismaili Muslim]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Olson |first1=James Stuart |title=An Ethnohistorical Dictionary of China |date=1998 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-28853-1 |language=English |page=177 |quote=In the Upper Chitral region, most Kho are Ismaili Muslims, who the Hanafi Sunnis consider to be an inferior people.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nHistorically the Kho people reside in the [[Dardistan region]]. As such, they are a [[Dardic people|Dardic]] ethnic group located primarily in [[South Asia]]. Many of the Kho people live in the [[Chitral District]] of the Pakistani province of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and a smaller number also live in Ghizer District of Gilgit Baltistan (including the Yasin Valley, Phandar Ishkoman and Gupis). They are also found in few numbers in northern Afghanistan, where the majority of them live in the northern provinces of [[Badakhshan Province|Badakhshan]].<ref name=\"Ethno-Latest\"/>\n\n==Culture==\nKho culture places heavy emphasis on poetry, song and dance. Kho people also have a great respect of law and order. Much of this can be attributed to Chitral being a stable kingdom for most of its history,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalark.net/Pakistan/chitral.htm |title=chitral |publisher=Royalark.net |date=1 June 1937 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> where the rule of law and the will of the ruler came before tribal concepts such as revenge and isolationism. Many Kho believe that their customs and language is much more rich, polite, and sophisticated in comparison to their neighbours.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Human: The Definitive Visual Guide|last=|first=|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2004|isbn=0-7566-0520-2|editor-last=Winston|editor-first=Robert|location=New York|pages=433}}</ref>\n\nPolo is a popular sport and pastime for the Kho people. The polo traditionally played by the Kho has little rules or organisation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDance and music play a large role in Kho society. Common clothing include the ''salwar kameez'' (long tunic and trousers) and headwear includes the [[pakol]] (chitrali hat).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBecause of Chitral's location at the crossroads of [[Central Asia]] and South Asia, the Kho display a wide variety of cultures, largely depending upon their ancestral ethnic group and family history.\n\n==Languages==\nThe Kho people speak the [[Khowar language]], a member of the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] subgroup of the [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language family]]. The ethnologists [[:de:Karl Jettmar|Karl Jettmar]] and Lennart Edelberg noted, with respect to the Khowar language, that: \"Khowar, in many respects [is] the most archaic of all modern Indian languages, retaining a great part of [[Sanskrit]] case inflexion, and retaining many words in a nearly Sanskritic form.\u201d<ref name=\"JettmarEdelberg1974\">{{cite book|last1=Jettmar|first1=Karl|last2=Edelberg|first2=Lennart|title=Cultures of the Hindukush|year=1974|publisher=F. Steiner Verlag|language=English|isbn=9783515012171|page=3}}</ref>\n\nKhowar is spoken by about 247,000 Kho people in northern Pakistan,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thenewstribe.com/2012/01/25/khowar-language/ |title = Khowar Language|date = 25 January 2012}}</ref> Some of the Kho people use [[Urdu]] as a second language.<ref name=\"SimonsFenning2017\">{{cite book|last1=Simons|first1= Gary F. |last2=Fennig|first2=Charles D. |title=Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Twentieth Edition |year=2017|publisher=[[SIL International]]|location= Dallas|language=English}}</ref>\n\n== Genetics ==\nThe western Eurasian haplogroups were observed predominantly and mostly shared in Kho samples with overall frequency of 50%. These include HV8, H19, H57, H24, C and, C4a haplogroups. The South Asian haplogroups and its relevant subgroups including U4, U4c, U6, U5a, and W were also found in Kho samples with overall 37.5% frequency. The haplogroups and haplotypes specify the origin and linkages of an individual and population. The haplogroup analysis eventually demonstrates the western Eurasian ancestral origin of Kho samples. Another South Asian haplogroup, M30 was also identified for Kho samples with frequency of 6.2%. This indicates the genetic affiliation of Kho with the South Asian populations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aziz|first=Shahid|last2=Nawaz|first2=Mehwish|last3=Afridi|first3=Sahib Gul|last4=Khan|first4=Asifullah|date=2019-04-01|title=Genetic structure of Kho population from north-western Pakistan based on mtDNA control region sequences|journal=Genetica|language=en|volume=147|issue=2|pages=177\u2013183|doi=10.1007/s10709-019-00060-8|pmid=30887215|issn=1573-6857}}</ref>\n\n==Folk music==\n{{unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\nFolk singers and reed instrument players have a special respect in the Kho society and are featured in their festivities. The most common instruments are Surnai [[Shehnai]], Sitar, and reed instruments. The Kho sitar is a popular musical instrument in Chitral. It is made out of mulberry wood with five steel strings arranged in three courses, the outer ones have double strings, tuned in unison, while the inner course is single. Popular music of the area includes:\n* ''Shishtoo-war (Sauz)'', a popular folk music played with shehnai on happy occasions, mostly at marriages.\n* ''Shab-daraaz (Dani)'' is a sad tone based on heartbroken love poems.\n* ''Ghalhwar'' is a combination of Dani and Sauz. This is a mixture of fast and classical music played at the starting of a polo match.\n\n== Notable people from Chitral ==\n* [[Saleem Khan (politician)]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Khowar language]]\n* [[Khoshey people]]\n* [[Kashmiri people]]\n* [[Shina people]]\n* [[Brokpa]]s\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://chitraltoday.net/about-chitral/ chitraltoday.net]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Pakistan}}\n{{Ethnic groups in India}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in India]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Dardic peoples]]\n[[Category:Chitral District]]\n", "name_user": "118.107.136.73", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 952432635 byZakaria1978(talk) No improvement)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kho_people"}
{"title_page": "Frode S\u00f8rensen (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish politician}}\n[[File:Frode Sorensen (S) medlem av Nordiska radets naringsutskott.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Frode S\u00f8rensen''' (born 21 January 1946 at [[N\u00f8rre-Rangstrup|Toftlund]]) was a member of the [[Danish parliament]] representing the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]].<ref>[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_efter_1945/Frode_S%C3%B8rensen?highlight=frode%20s%C3%B8rensen Frode S\u00f8rensen Den store Danske]</ref> He was [[Tax Minister of Denmark|Tax Minister]] from 21 December 2000 to 27 November 2001. He was a [[Member of Parliament]] ([[Folketinget]]) from 11 March 1998 - 13 November 2007.<ref>{{ft.dk link}}</ref>\n<!-- He is known as a right-wing social-democrat with strong views on immigrants from non-European countries. -- probably correct, but I cannot immediately source that statement, needs verification /pow -->\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\ntitle=[[List of Tax Ministers of Denmark|Tax Minister of Denmark]]|\nbefore=[[Ole Stavad]]|\nyears=21 December 2000 &ndash; 27 November 2001|\nafter=[[Svend Erik Hovmand]]\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sorensen, Frode}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Folketing]]\n[[Category:Social Democrats (Denmark) politicians]]\n[[Category:Danish Tax Ministers]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00f8nder Municipality]]\n\n{{Denmark-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish politician}}\n[[File:Frode Sorensen (S) medlem av Nordiska radets naringsutskott.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Frode S\u00f8rensen''' (born 21 January 1946 at [[Toftlund]]) was a member of the [[Danish parliament]] representing the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]].<ref>[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_efter_1945/Frode_S%C3%B8rensen?highlight=frode%20s%C3%B8rensen Frode S\u00f8rensen Den store Danske]</ref> He was [[Tax Minister of Denmark|Tax Minister]] from 21 December 2000 to 27 November 2001. He was a [[Member of Parliament]] ([[Folketinget]]) from 11 March 1998 - 13 November 2007.<ref>{{ft.dk link}}</ref>\n<!-- He is known as a right-wing social-democrat with strong views on immigrants from non-European countries. -- probably correct, but I cannot immediately source that statement, needs verification /pow -->\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\ntitle=[[List of Tax Ministers of Denmark|Tax Minister of Denmark]]|\nbefore=[[Ole Stavad]]|\nyears=21 December 2000 &ndash; 27 November 2001|\nafter=[[Svend Erik Hovmand]]\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sorensen, Frode}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Folketing]]\n[[Category:Social Democrats (Denmark) politicians]]\n[[Category:Danish Tax Ministers]]\n[[Category:People from T\u00f8nder Municipality]]\n\n{{Denmark-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "better link for pob", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frode_S%C3%B8rensen_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Sylvie Feucher", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Sylvie Feucher\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| office       = Prefect of Saint-Martin and Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy<ref name=decree>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?dateTexte=&categorieLien=id&cidTexte=JORFTEXT000037078819&fastPos=18&fastReqId=1569137792&oldAction=rechExpTexteJorf|title=D\u00e9cret du 18 juin 2018 portant nomination de la pr\u00e9f\u00e8te d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9e aupr\u00e8s du repr\u00e9sentant de l'Etat dans les collectivit\u00e9s de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy et de Saint-Martin - Mme DANIELO-FEUCHER (Sylvie)|date=18 June 2018|access-date=24 April 2020|language=fr|last=Government of the French Republic|website=legifrance.gouv.fr}}</ref>\n| term_start   = 18 June 2018 <ref name=\"decree\"/>\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Anne Laubi\u00e8s\n| successor    = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1959|2|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brest]], [[France]]\n| siblings     = \n| occupation   =  \n| yearsactive  =  \n| nationality  = {{flagicon|France|1794}} [[France|French]]\n}}\n\n'''Sylvie Feucher''' (ne\u00e9 Dani\u00e9lo born 26 February 1959 in [[Brest]], [[France]])  is a French civil servant and the current [[Prefect (France)|Prefect]] of [[Saint-Martin]] and [[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]].\n\nIn 2004 Feucher was Chief Commissioner of the [[National Police (France)|National Police]] in [[Versailles]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2009/02/21/01016-20090221ARTFIG00158-un-partage-equitable-police-gendarmerie-.php|title=\u00abUn partage \u00e9quitable police-gendarmerie\u00bb |website=Le Figaro|language=fr|access-date=24 April 2020|date=21 February 2009}}</ref> In 2013 Feucher became the Prefect for Equal Opportunities in [[Val-d'Oise]].<ref name=\"prefect\">{{Cite web|url=http://outremers360.com/politique/nomination-sylvie-danielo-feucher-est-nommee-nouvelle-prefete-deleguee-de-saint-martin-et-de-saint-barthelemy/|title=Nomination: Sylvie Danielo-Feucher est nomm\u00e9e nouvelle pr\u00e9f\u00e8te d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9e de Saint-Martin et de Saint-Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my |website=Outre Mers 360|language=fr|access-date=24 April 2020|date=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2018, Feucher was appointed Prefect of Saint-Martin and Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy.<ref name=\"prefect\"/> The islands used to be part of [[Guadeloupe]], but on 7 February 2007 they became an [[Collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer|overseas collectivity]] with a Prefect for both islands to represent the State, but also to handle crises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000465963&dateTexte=&categorieLien=id|title=LOI organique n\u00b0 2007-223 du 21 f\u00e9vrier 2007 portant dispositions statutaires et institutionnelles relatives \u00e0 l'outre-mer|date=21 February 2007|last=Government of the French Republic|website=legifrance.gouv.fr|access-date=24 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref> Sylvie Feucher is therefore in charge of the management of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feucher, Sylvia}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Saint Barth\u00e9lemy politicians]]\n[[Category:Saint Martin politicians]]\n[[Category:French civil servants]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{france-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Sylvie Feucher\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| office       = Prefect of Saint-Martin and Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy<ref name=decree>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?dateTexte=&categorieLien=id&cidTexte=JORFTEXT000037078819&fastPos=18&fastReqId=1569137792&oldAction=rechExpTexteJorf|title=D\u00e9cret du 18 juin 2018 portant nomination de la pr\u00e9f\u00e8te d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9e aupr\u00e8s du repr\u00e9sentant de l'Etat dans les collectivit\u00e9s de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy et de Saint-Martin - Mme DANIELO-FEUCHER (Sylvie)|date=18 June 2018|access-date=24 April 2020|language=fr|last=Government of the French Republic|website=legifrance.gouv.fr}}</ref>\n| term_start   = 18 June 2018 <ref name=\"decree\"/>\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Anne Laubi\u00e8s\n| successor    = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1959|2|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brest]], [[France]]\n| siblings     = \n| occupation   =  \n| yearsactive  =  \n| nationality  = {{flagicon|France|1794}} [[France|French]]\n}}\n\n'''Sylvie Feucher''' (ne\u00e9 Dani\u00e9lo born 26 February 1959 in [[Brest]], [[France]])  is a French civil servant and the current [[Prefect (France)|Prefect]] of [[Saint-Martin]] and [[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]].\n\nIn 2004 Feucher was Chief Commissioner of the [[National Police (France)|National Police]] in [[Versailles]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2009/02/21/01016-20090221ARTFIG00158-un-partage-equitable-police-gendarmerie-.php|title=\u00abUn partage \u00e9quitable police-gendarmerie\u00bb |website=Le Figaro|language=fr|access-date=24 April 2020|date=21 February 2009}}</ref> In 2013 Feucher became the Prefect for Equal Opportunities in [[Val-d'Oise]].<ref name=\"prefect\">{{Cite web|url=http://outremers360.com/politique/nomination-sylvie-danielo-feucher-est-nommee-nouvelle-prefete-deleguee-de-saint-martin-et-de-saint-barthelemy/|title=Nomination: Sylvie Danielo-Feucher est nomm\u00e9e nouvelle pr\u00e9f\u00e8te d\u00e9l\u00e9gu\u00e9e de Saint-Martin et de Saint-Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my |website=Outre Mers 360|language=fr|access-date=24 April 2020|date=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2018, Feucher was appointed Prefect of Saint-Martin and Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy.<ref name=\"prefect\"/> The islands used to be part of [[Guadeloupe]], but on 7 February 2007 they became an [[Collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer|overseas collectivity]] with a Prefect for both islands to represent the State, but also to handle crises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000465963&dateTexte=&categorieLien=id|title=LOI organique n\u00b0 2007-223 du 21 f\u00e9vrier 2007 portant dispositions statutaires et institutionnelles relatives \u00e0 l'outre-mer|date=21 February 2007|last=Government of the French Republic|website=legifrance.gouv.fr|access-date=24 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref> Sylvia Feucher is therefore in charge of the management of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feucher, Sylvia}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Saint Barth\u00e9lemy politicians]]\n[[Category:Saint Martin politicians]]\n[[Category:French civil servants]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{france-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylvie_Feucher"}
{"title_page": "Semanticity", "text_new": "'''Semanticity''' is one of [[Charles Hockett]]'s 16 [[design features of language]]. Semanticity refers to the use of arbitrary or nonarbitrary signals to transmit meaningful messages.<ref>Hockett, C. F. (1960) \"[http://www.columbia.edu/~rmk7/HC/HC_Readings/Hockett.pdf The origin of speech]\". ''Scientific American'', 203:2.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Hockett's design features]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Language acquisition]]\n[[Category:Semantics]]\n[[Category:Linguistic universals]]\n{{semantics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Semanticity''' is one of [[Charles Hockett]]'s 16 [[design features of language]]. Semanticity refers to the use of arbitrary or nonarbitrary signals to transmit meaningful messages.<ref>Hockett, C. F. (1960) \"[http://www.columbia.edu/~rmk7/HC/HC_Readings/Hockett.pdf The origin of speech]\". ''Scientific American'', 203:2.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Language acquisition]]\n[[Category:Semantics]]\n[[Category:Linguistic universals]]\n{{semantics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Travalleir", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semanticity"}
{"title_page": "Norbert Bl\u00fcm", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg \n| imagesize     = 250px\n| caption       = Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1988\n| office        = Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour\n| term_start    = 4 October 1982 \n| term_end      = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor   = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor     = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany]] \n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]] {{flagicon|Germany}}\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| relations     = Marita Bl\u00fcm\n| residence     = [[Bonn]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bonn]]\n| occupation    = \n| religion      = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 or 24 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=General Anzeiger |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] politician, serving as [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] (1987\u20131999), and [[Political minister|minister]] of labor and social affairs\u2014the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm trained locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]]. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts within the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]]. Later he studied German language and literature, history and philosophy.\n\n==Political positions==\nDuring his time in office, Bl\u00fcm famously held out and pushed back against demands  by fellow Christian Democratic Union politicians, to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> His popular quote \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated to: \"Pensions are untouchable\") is a misquotation. It was a slogan he wielded in 1986 (\"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\", \"One thing is untouchable: pensions\"). This misquotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference to be popularized by his opponents and critics for years to come. After almost three decades, Bl\u00fcm himself took part in it, by mocking said quote on the German TV show [[Neues aus der Anstalt]].\n\nEspecially during his political career, Bl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]]. As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.\n\n==Other activities==\n* Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne, Member of the Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member\n\n==Recognition (selection)==\n* 2000 \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] \n* 2005 \u2013 [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[:de:Norbert Bl\u00fcm|Norbert Bl\u00fcm]] in German Wikipedia\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=October 9, 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', June 9, 2001\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg \n| imagesize     = 250px\n| caption       = Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1988\n| office        = Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour\n| term_start    = 4 October 1982 \n| term_end      = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor   = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor     = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany]] \n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]] {{flagicon|Germany}}\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| relations     = Marita Bl\u00fcm\n| residence     = [[Bonn]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bonn]]\n| occupation    = \n| religion      = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 or 24 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=[[General Anzeiger]] |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] politician, serving as [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] (1987\u20131999), and [[Political minister|minister]] of labor and social affairs\u2014the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm trained locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]]. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts within the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]]. Later he studied German language and literature, history and philosophy.\n\n==Political positions==\nDuring his time in office, Bl\u00fcm famously held out and pushed back against demands  by fellow Christian Democratic Union politicians, to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> His popular quote \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated to: \"Pensions are untouchable\") is a misquotation. It was a slogan he wielded in 1986 (\"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\", \"One thing is untouchable: pensions\"). This misquotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference to be popularized by his opponents and critics for years to come. After almost three decades, Bl\u00fcm himself took part in it, by mocking said quote on the German TV show [[Neues aus der Anstalt]].\n\nEspecially during his political career, Bl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]]. As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.\n\n==Other activities==\n* Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne, Member of the Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member\n\n==Recognition (selection)==\n* 2000 \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] \n* 2005 \u2013 [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[:de:Norbert Bl\u00fcm|Norbert Bl\u00fcm]] in German Wikipedia\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=October 9, 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', June 9, 2001\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "dl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norbert_Bl%C3%BCm"}
{"title_page": "Natalie and Nadiya Anderson", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Natalie Anderson\n| image =\n| birth_name = Natalie Anderson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1986|04|11}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| home_town = [[Edgewater, New Jersey]], U.S.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Natalie And Nadiya|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/amazing_race/cast/183900/|website=CBS|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| occupation = TV personality, Crossfit coach, physical therapy student\n| television = ''{{nowrap|[[The Amazing Race 21]]}}''<br>''{{nowrap|[[The Amazing Race 24]]}}''<br>''{{nowrap|[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]}}'' (winner)<br>''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| alias = Twinnie <br> Nat\n}}\n\n'''Natalie Anderson and Nadiya Anderson''' (born April 11, 1986) are American television personalities and twins, most commonly known as ''The Twinnies''. They appeared on ''[[The Amazing Race (American TV series)|The Amazing Race]]'' and ''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''. Nadiya was the first contestant to be voted out, while Natalie was crowned Sole Survivor, winning the show's $1 million prize. Natalie also competed on ''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nThe Anderson twins were born in [[New York City]] to a [[Tamils|Tamil]] father and a [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] mother, but they moved to [[Sri Lanka]] when they were three and were there during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/TheAmazingRace/article/Natalie-and-Nadiya-embarrassed-to-be-eliminated-first-on-e28098Amazing-Racee28099-All-Stars|title=The Amazing Race - News - Natalie and Nadiya embarrassed to be eliminated first on 'Amazing Race' All-Stars - CTV|work=CTV.ca|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> They moved to [[West Hartford, Connecticut]] when they were thirteen years old, attending [[Hall High School (Connecticut)|Hall High School]], where both sisters ran track and Natalie was captain of the swim team, and [[Fordham University]]'s Gabelli School of Business, where Natalie played rugby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.fordham.edu/university-news/twins-travel-the-world-on-the-amazing-race/|title=Twins Travel the World on The Amazing Race|date=2012-11-08|website=Fordham Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/java/hc-west-hartford-twins-amazing-race-20150407-story.html|title=West Hartford 'Twinnies' Of 'Amazing Race,' 'Survivor' Fame Tell Of Winning & Losing|last=FILLO|first=MARYELLEN|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> Before participating in their first season on ''The Amazing Race'', both had moved to [[Edgewater, New Jersey]] where Natalie was studying [[physical therapy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/amazing_race/cast/183900/|title=The Amazing Race Cast: Natalie and Nadiya|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=CBS|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Television appearances==\n===''The Amazing Race''===\nNatalie and Nadiya first participated in the [[The Amazing Race 21|21st season of ''The Amazing Race'']], where they called each other \"Twinnie\". The Andersons won two legs during the season, but were eliminated in 4th place in the penultimate leg. They returned in the [[The Amazing Race 24|24th season ''All-Stars'' competition]], but were eliminated in the first leg of the season.<ref name=profile/>\n\n===''Survivor''===\nNatalie and Nadiya appeared as contestants on ''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''. The twins appeared on a season that used the Blood vs. Water theme, which pitted nine pairs of loved ones against each other. Natalie was placed on the Hunahpu tribe, while Nadiya was on the Coyopa tribe, as the season's theme was pairs of loved ones competing against each other on opposing tribes. Nadiya was the first contestant eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/151703_survivor_nadiya_talks_reality_show_curse/|title='Survivor' Nadiya Talks Reality Show Curse|work=Entertainment Tonight|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> Natalie remained in the game, making it into the merged Huyopa tribe, and won three reward challenges, one individual immunity, and was sent to Exile Island twice. Natalie ultimately made it into the Final Three and was voted by the jury in a 5\u20132\u20131 vote as the Sole Survivor, winning the season's $1,000,000 grand prize.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Survivor: San Juan Del Sur\" Names Winner|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2014/12/18/survivor-san-juan-del-sur-names-sole-survivor/|website=CBRDFS|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNatalie was slated to return for ''[[Survivor: Game Changers]]'' as a member of the Nuku tribe, but she suffered a concussion and was replaced by Sierra Dawn Thomas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://survivingtribal.com/2017/05/30/survivor-game-changers-players-game-changing-moments/12/|title=Survivor Game Changers: Each player\u2019s big game-changing moment|date=2017-05-30|website=Surviving Tribal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NatalieeAnd/status/990016551112896512|title=Totes|last=Anderson|first=Natalie|date=2018-04-27|website=@NatalieeAnd|language=ca|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nNatalie is competing in ''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''. She was the first person voted out, but is inhabiting the \u201cEdge of Extinction\u201d, where she has a chance to re-enter the main competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.cbs.com/shows/survivor/photos/1008880/who-s-in-the-cast-of-survivor-season-40-winners-at-war-/2/|title=Who\u2019s in the Cast of Survivor Season 40: Winners at War?|date=2019-12-18|website=CBS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> Her sister Nadiya came to visit her on episode 10.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title= Winner of ''[[Survivor (U.S. TV series)|Survivor]]'' | before=[[Tony Vlachos]]| years=''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''| after= [[Mike Holloway (Survivor contestant)|Mike Holloway]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{The Amazing Race contestants}}\n{{Survivor contestants}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:The Amazing Race contestants]]\n[[Category:American people of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Identical twin females]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Edgewater, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Survivor (American TV series) winners]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Natalie Anderson\n| image =\n| birth_name = Natalie Anderson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1986|04|11}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| home_town = [[Edgewater, New Jersey]], U.S.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Natalie And Nadiya|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/amazing_race/cast/183900/|website=CBS|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| occupation = TV personality, Crossfit coach, physical therapy student\n| television = ''{{nowrap|[[The Amazing Race 21]]}}''<br>''{{nowrap|[[The Amazing Race 24]]}}''<br>''{{nowrap|[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]}}'' (winner)<br>''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| alias = Twinnie <br> Nat\n}}\n\n'''Natalie Anderson and Nadiya Anderson''' (born April 11, 1986) are American television personalities and twins, most commonly known as ''The Twinnies''. They appeared on ''[[The Amazing Race (American TV series)|The Amazing Race]]'' and ''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''. Nadiya was the first contestant to be voted out, while Natalie was crowned Sole Survivor, winning the show's $1 million prize. Natalie also competed on ''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nThe Anderson twins were born in [[New York City]] to a [[Tamils|Tamil]] father and a [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] mother, but they moved to [[Sri Lanka]] when they were three and were there during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/TheAmazingRace/article/Natalie-and-Nadiya-embarrassed-to-be-eliminated-first-on-e28098Amazing-Racee28099-All-Stars|title=The Amazing Race - News - Natalie and Nadiya embarrassed to be eliminated first on 'Amazing Race' All-Stars - CTV|work=CTV.ca|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> They moved to [[West Hartford, Connecticut]] when they were thirteen years old, attending [[Hall High School (Connecticut)|Hall High School]], where both sisters ran track and Natalie was captain of the swim team, and [[Fordham University]]'s Gabelli School of Business, where Natalie played rugby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.fordham.edu/university-news/twins-travel-the-world-on-the-amazing-race/|title=Twins Travel the World on The Amazing Race|date=2012-11-08|website=Fordham Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/java/hc-west-hartford-twins-amazing-race-20150407-story.html|title=West Hartford 'Twinnies' Of 'Amazing Race,' 'Survivor' Fame Tell Of Winning & Losing|last=FILLO|first=MARYELLEN|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> Before participating in their first season on ''The Amazing Race'', both had moved to [[Edgewater, New Jersey]] where Natalie was studying [[physical therapy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/amazing_race/cast/183900/|title=The Amazing Race Cast: Natalie and Nadiya|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=CBS|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Television appearances==\n===''The Amazing Race''===\nNatalie and Nadiya first participated in the [[The Amazing Race 21|21st season of ''The Amazing Race'']], where they called each other \"Twinnie\". The Andersons won two legs during the season, but were eliminated in 4th place in the penultimate leg. They returned in the [[The Amazing Race 24|24th season ''All-Stars'' competition]], but were eliminated in the first leg of the season.<ref name=profile/>\n\n===''Survivor''===\nNatalie and Nadiya appeared as contestants on ''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''. The twins appeared on a season that used the Blood vs. Water theme, which pitted nine pairs of loved ones against each other. Natalie was placed on the Hunahpu tribe, while Nadiya was on the Coyopa tribe, as the season's theme was pairs of loved ones competing against each other on opposing tribes. Nadiya was the first contestant eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/151703_survivor_nadiya_talks_reality_show_curse/|title='Survivor' Nadiya Talks Reality Show Curse|work=Entertainment Tonight|accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> Natalie remained in the game, making it into the merged Huyopa tribe, and won three reward challenges, one individual immunity, and was sent to Exile Island twice. Natalie ultimately made it into the Final Three and was voted by the jury in a 5\u20132\u20131 vote as the Sole Survivor, winning the season's $1,000,000 grand prize.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Survivor: San Juan Del Sur\" Names Winner|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2014/12/18/survivor-san-juan-del-sur-names-sole-survivor/|website=CBRDFS|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNatalie was slated to return for ''[[Survivor: Game Changers]]'' as a member of the Nuku tribe, but she suffered a concussion and was replaced by Sierra Dawn Thomas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://survivingtribal.com/2017/05/30/survivor-game-changers-players-game-changing-moments/12/|title=Survivor Game Changers: Each player\u2019s big game-changing moment|date=2017-05-30|website=Surviving Tribal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NatalieeAnd/status/990016551112896512|title=Totes|last=Anderson|first=Natalie|date=2018-04-27|website=@NatalieeAnd|language=ca|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nNatalie is competing in ''[[Survivor: Winners at War]]''. She was the first person voted out, but is inhabiting the \u201cEdge of Extinction\u201d, where she has a chance to re-enter the main competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.cbs.com/shows/survivor/photos/1008880/who-s-in-the-cast-of-survivor-season-40-winners-at-war-/2/|title=Who\u2019s in the Cast of Survivor Season 40: Winners at War?|date=2019-12-18|website=CBS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title= Winner of ''[[Survivor (U.S. TV series)|Survivor]]'' | before=[[Tony Vlachos]]| years=''[[Survivor: San Juan del Sur]]''| after= [[Mike Holloway (Survivor contestant)|Mike Holloway]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{The Amazing Race contestants}}\n{{Survivor contestants}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:The Amazing Race contestants]]\n[[Category:American people of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Identical twin females]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Edgewater, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Survivor (American TV series) winners]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Eriru", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSurvivor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_and_Nadiya_Anderson"}
{"title_page": "History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya", "text_new": "{{short description|History of a Thai Buddhist temple}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n[[File:Dhammakaya cetiya night.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The Dhammakaya Cetiya]]\n[[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]] ({{lang-th|\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22}}) is a Buddhist temple in Thailand. It was founded in 1970 by the ''[[maechi]]'' (nun) [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]] and [[Luang Por Dhammajayo]]. The temple's founding has roots in the [[Dhammakaya tradition]] founded by [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro]] at [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]] in the early twentieth century.{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010|p=885}}{{sfn|Swearer|2010|p=114}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=52}} Wat Phra Dhammakaya is known for its modern dissemination methods and use of technology.\n\nThe temple was initially founded as a meditation center, after Maechi Chandra and the just ordained monk Luang Por Dhammajayo could no longer accommodate the rising number of participants in their activities at [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]], becoming an official temple in 1977. The temple experienced rapid growth during the 1980s, when the temple's programs became widely known among the urban middle class. Wat Phra Dhammakaya expanded its area quickly during this period and started building its iconic ''[[stupa]]'' (pagoda).\n\nDuring the period of the [[1997 Asian financial crisis]], however, the temple was subject to widespread criticism for its fundraising methods and teachings, Luang Por Dhammajayo was eventually charged with embezzlement and removed from his office as abbot. In 2006, the charges were withdrawn and he was restored as abbot. The temple grew further in the following years and became known for its many projects in education, promotion of ethics, and scholarship in Thai society. The temple's tradition developed an international scope, as of 2007, the temple's following was estimated at one million practitioners worldwide and thirty to fifty international centers outside of Thailand.\n\nUnder the [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|2014 military junta]], the abbot and the temple were put under scrutiny again and Luang Por Dhammajayo was accused of receiving stolen money of a supporter and money-laundering. This incident led to several standoffs between the temple and the junta, eventually leading to 23 day lock down of the temple in 2017 by the junta that made headlines worldwide. In the aftermath of the lock down the junta stated they will look for Luang Por Dhammajayo elsewhere but continued its scrutiny of the temple, giving the vice abbot, [[Luang Por Dattajivo]] several charges as well.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Founding years (1963\u20131978) ==\n\n=== First encounters ===\n\nWat Phra Dhammakaya started with the ''[[maechi]]'' (nun) [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]]. She was a notable student of Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro, when he was still alive.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998}}{{sfn|Scott|2006}} Although illiterate, she was widely respected for her experience in meditation, which is rare for a ''maechi''. She managed to attract many well-educated students, despite her rural background and illiteracy.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?isbn=1474280943|title=Freedom and Authority in Religions and Religious Education|last=Gombrich|first=R.|publisher=[[Cassell (publisher)|Cassell]]|year=1996|editor-last=Gates|editor-first=B.|location=London|page=11|chapter=Freedom and Authority in Buddhism|author-link=Richard Gombrich}}</ref> After Luang Pu Sodh died in 1959, Maechi Chandra transmitted the Dhammakaya tradition to a new generation at Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen.{{sfn|Heikkil\u00e4-Horn|1996|p=94}} She taught meditation; one of her pupils was a university student called Chaiyabun Sutthiphon. His parents were [[Lao Song]] and [[Thai-Chinese]], and separated when he was young. Chaiyabun was raised by his father, who was an engineer working for a government agency.{{sfn|Taylor|1989}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=33}} Chaiyabun developed a strong interest in reading, especially in books on Buddhist practice and biographies of leading people in the world, both religious and political,<ref name=\"Dokbia 991220\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=20 December 1999|work=Dokbia Thurakit|page=8|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e0a\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e32\u0e01\u0e25 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e01\u0e15\u0e33\u0e41\u0e19\u0e48\u0e07\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Suspicious: the case of the removal of Wat Phra Dhammakaya's abbot|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=15 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=33}} and read about Maechi Chandra in a magazine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2008/02/20/fea07.asp|title=Maha Dhammakaya Cetiya where millions congregate seeking inner peace|date=28 February 2008|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|publisher=Lake House|last1=Rajakaruna|first1=J.}}</ref> In 1963, while enrolled in [[Kasetsart University]], he started visiting [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]]. It was here that he first met Maechi Chandra and started to learn meditation with her.<ref name=\"McDaniel 2006\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/?id=CRCD96RNxfwC|title=Buddhism in World Cultures: Comparative Perspectives|last=McDaniel|first=Justin|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|year=2006|isbn=1-85109-787-2|editor-last=Berkwitz|editor-first=Stephen C.|location=Santa Barbara, California|chapter=Buddhism in Thailand: Negotiating the Modern Age}}</ref>\n\nChaiyabun encouraged his fellow university students to join the activities at Wat Paknam, and the community grew.<ref name=\"McDaniel 2006\" /> One of these students was Phadet Phongsawat. In Wat Phra Dhammakaya's biographies, it is told that Phadet often held public demonstrations of [[Khatha|black magic]] ({{lang-th|\u0e04\u0e32\u0e16\u0e32, \u0e44\u0e2a\u0e22\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c}}) to his fellow students in his years at Kasetsart University. However, every time Chaiyabun joined to watch one of Phadet's demonstrations, the magic would not work. Phadet therefore became curious, and learnt about [[Dhammakaya meditation]] from Chaiyabun. He felt inspired by Chaiyabun's sincerity in meditation and his adherence to the Buddhist [[five precepts]].{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=83}}<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZxOR950PgTk|series=Newsnight|network=Amarin TV|station=34|date=1 June 2016|time=1:38|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e17\u0e31\u0e15\u0e15\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e42\u0e27 \u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e09\u0e32\u0e01\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=Phra Dattajivo, standing behind Phra Dhammajayo|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== From Wat Paknam to Wat Phra Dhammakaya ===\n\n[[File:Wat Phra Dhammakaya aerial view May 2010.jpg|thumb|The compound of Wat Phra Dhammakaya: The Dining Hall of Khun yay Archaraya [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]] (lower left), The Memorial Hall of [[Phramongkolthepmuni]] (upper left) and The Great Sapha Dhammakaya Hall (upper right).]]In the beginning, the meditations and teachings were carried out in a small house called \"Ban Dhammaprasit\" in the compound of Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen. Chaiyabun had set up a group called \"Dhammaprasit\" and this group had financed the house together in which to organize meditations. Once Chaiyabun was ordained as a monk in 1969 and received the name [[Phra Dhammajayo]], he started teaching Dhammakaya meditation together with Maechi Chandra.{{sfn|Heikkil\u00e4-Horn|1996|p=94}} Because of the popularity of both teachers, the house soon became overcrowded with interested students and they considered it more appropriate to start a new meditation center by themselves.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998}} Although initially they intended to {{em|buy}} a plot of land in Pathum Thani, the landowner ''[[Khunying]]'' Prayat Suntharawet gave a plot four times the requested size to practice generosity at the occasion of her birthday. On 20 February 1970, Maechi Chandra, Phra Dhammajayo, Phra Dattajivo and their students moved to the 196-''[[Rai (area)|rai]]'' ({{cvt|313,600|m2|acre|adj=on|disp=or}}) plot of land to found a meditation center.{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010}} Phra Dhammajayo later became abbot of the temple and was called Luang Por Dhammajayo from then on, and Pongsawat was ordained with the name [[Luang Por Dattajivo]] and became deputy abbot.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007}}\n\nThe site, {{convert|16|km |spell=in}} north of [[Don Mueang International Airport]], was originally called \"Sun Phutthachak-patipattham\" ({{lang-th|\u0e28\u0e39\u0e19\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e0f\u0e34\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21}}). At the time Pathum Thani was well outside Bangkok's northern suburbs.{{sfn|Zehner|1990|p=408}} From acidic paddy fields, a woodland was created to be a park for meditation practitioners. The initial budget for construction was very low (3,200 [[Baht]]), but despite these economical constraints, the construction of the buildings on the land was able to continue.<ref name=\"Forbes 2015\" /> A book about the initiative was compiled, to inspire people to join in and help.{{sfn|Dhammakaya Foundation|2005|pp=102\u20133}} In the accounts of the temple, it is told that the construction happened with great attention for detail. For example, the outside of the wall of the ''[[Ubosot]]'' was made of gravel that was selected manually.{{sfn|Thammachay\u014d|Thattach\u012bw\u014d|Tawandhamma Foundation|2007|pp=46\u20139}} Because the land at first was very acidic, only [[Acacia|wattle]] could be planted. Later on, the soil improved.{{sfn|Dhammakaya Foundation|2005|p=108}} Though originally the intention was simply to build a center\u2014as a satellite meditation center of Wat Paknam\u2014eventually, this was changed to building a full-fledged temple, under pressure from the authorities who wanted the place to be properly registered.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=34}}{{sfn|Scott|2006|p=222}} The foundation stone for the ''Ubosot'' was laid by Princess [[Maha Chakri Sirindhorn]] on behalf of King [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] in December 1977. The following year it was officially recognized as a temple by the Thai government, as \"Wat Voranee Dhammakayaram\", named after the daughter of ''Khunying'' Prayat, Voranee. However, there was disagreement as to who should become the abbot of the temple, and how the temple should develop further: Voranee then stopped supporting the temple. In 1982, the temple therefore left out the daughter's name and renamed itself \"Wat Phra Dhammakaya\".<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PmIM_ZiFjRQ|series=The Dhammakaya Epic|network=[[Channel 8 (Thailand)]]|date=29 May 2016|number=3|time=1:52|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01 \"\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e17\u0e18\u0e34\u0e4c\" \u0e2a\u0e39\u0e48 \"\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e08\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e4c\"|trans-title=From Ban Thammaprasit to the Maha Dhammakaya Cetiya|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Matichon 1999\" />{{sfn|Swearer|1991|p=656}} The main concept of the temple from the start was to be \"a school for teaching ethics to society at large\", which the founders believed a temple should be.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://research.culture.go.th/index.php/research/item/58-2012-09-14-06-42-29.html|title=A study of the role of information technology in the Buddhist missionary activities of Wat Phra Dhammakaya|last2=Poungnoi|first2=Pa-ob|publisher=Office of the National Culture Commission, [[Ministry of Education (Thailand)|Ministry of Education]]|page=5|first1=Nataya|last1=Kaewsai|year=1999}}</ref>\n\n=== Start of ''Dhammadayada'' program ===\n\nIn 1972, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started a program called ''Dhammadayada'' ('heirs of the [[Dharma (Buddhism)|Dhamma]]'), a meditation training program focused on university students.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1993|p=157}} Wat Phra Dhammakaya emphasized youth and young adults in its orientation from its outset. The Buddhist societies of many of Thai universities and colleges were led by supporters of the temple, many coming from the ''Dhammadayada'' program,{{sfn|Sivaraksa|1987}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=84}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=44}} though in the mid-1990s this influence grew weaker.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=128}} In 1981, the temple also started organizing a contest called 'Path of Progress' ({{lang-th|\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e49\u0e32}}). In this program, schools all over Thailand competed in their knowledge of Buddhist ethics,{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=42\u20133}}<ref name=\"Matichon 990913\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=18 September 1999|work=Matichon|page=23|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e15\u0e23.\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e15\u0e39\u0e49 \u0e1b\u0e13.123 \u0e23\u0e27\u0e21\u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e39\u0e25\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Police starts PO Box for collecting information about Dhammakaya|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> which was designed to complement the national education system, which the temple believed had become too secularized.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=146}} Due to the large number of students joining the temple's activities, who in the 1970s tended to be leftist, for a brief period Wat Phra Dhammakaya was accused of supporting the [[Communist insurgency in Thailand]] and [[Thammasat University massacre|the student uprisings in the 1970s]].{{sfn|Taylor|1989}}{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2325}}{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=120}}\n\nSpokespeople of the temple describe the role of Maechi Chandra in the early period of the temple as a 'chief commander' ([[Thai language|Thai]]: ''jomthap''), whereas Luang Por Dhammajayo is depicted as a 'chief of staff' (Thai: ''senathikan'') developing proper plans, whereas Luang Por Dattaj\u012bvo is described as the practical manager.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=th:'\u0e17\u0e31\u0e15\u0e15\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e42\u0e27'\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e44\u0e1b\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19? |title=Thattachiwo hai pai nai |trans-title=Where is Dattaj\u012bvo? |url=https://www.komchadluek.net/news/scoop/229110 |work=[[Kom Chad Luek]] |date=7 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309164154/http://www.komchadluek.net/news/scoop/229110 |archivedate=9 March 2017 |language=TH}}</ref> During the years to follow, Maechi Chandra's role would gradually become less, as she grow older and withdrew more to the background of the temple's organization.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=41\u20133}}\n\n== Exponential growth (1979\u20131996) ==\n\n=== Further development of the ''Dhammadayada'' program ===\n\nAfter 1979, the ''Dhammadayada'' program began to include a temporary ordination.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=130}} In Thailand, it had been a tradition for men to ordain for the [[Vassa|monastic rains retreat (vassa)]] as a [[rite of passage]] before becoming adult.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2006|title=Buddhism|encyclopedia=Worldmark Encyclopedia of Religious Practices|publisher=[[Thomson Gale]]|location=Farmington Hills|url=https://www.politicalavenue.com/PDF/ENCYCLOPEDIAS/Encyclopedia%20of%20Religious%20Practices%20Vol1.pdf|volume=1|page=68|isbn=0-7876-6612-2|author=Kinnard, Jacob|editor=Riggs, Thomas|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302030021/http://www.politicalavenue.com/PDF/ENCYCLOPEDIAS/Encyclopedia%20of%20Religious%20Practices%20Vol1.pdf|archivedate=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seapa.org/scandal-in-the-temple/|title=Scandal in the Temple|date=11 May 2010|work=[[Southeast Asian Press Alliance]]|last1=Arpon|first1=Yasmin Lee G.|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> These ordinations were becoming shorter, and the temple was trying to reverse this trend.{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2324}} During such a training program at the temple, participants typically started off with rigorous physical training to prepare themselves for the program. When the training started, they kept the [[eight precepts]], slept under mosquito nets in the open air, and meditated for four to eight hours per day. After this preparatory training, they ordained for the remaining period of at least one month. Ordination ceremonies were held at [[Wat Benchamabophit]].{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=58\u201360}} The program initially focused on university students, starting with the network of friends of Luang Por Dhammajayo and Luang Por Dattajivo. During the period of the temple's construction, the ''Dhammadayada'' ordination plan gave training to hundreds of students, who swelled the number of residents in the temple community.{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=83\u20134}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=128\u201330}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1993|p=176}} For monks who stayed on for longer, ordaining for life was emphasized more than in other temples,{{sfn|Sivaraksa|1987}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=131}}{{sfn|Swearer|1991|p=659}} though considerable screening took place before someone could do so.<ref name=\"bun\">{{cite journal|date=1 January 2000|title=Thailand: Farewell to Old-Style Politics?|journal=Southeast Asian Affairs|publisher=[[ISEAS]], Yosuf Ishak Institute|pages=285\u201395|jstor=27912257|last1=Bunbongkarn|first1=Suchit}}</ref>{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=64}} For women, a parallel training program was held from 1986 onward, in which the eight precepts were kept, but the women did not receive full ordination in the manner of ''[[bhikkhuni]]s''.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=86}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=83\u20134}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=60}}\n\n=== Appeal ===\n[[File:Sign with regulations as issued by Mae chi Chan Khonokyoong.jpg|alt=Sign with rules set by Maechi Chandra Khonnokyoong|left|thumb|Maechi [[Chandra Khonnokyoong|Chandra]] set strict rules and regulations for the temple community, such as a prohibition on political lobbying and selling things in the temple.<ref name=\"Now 26\">{{cite news|url=http://www.now26.tv/view/100747|date=24 February 2017|work=Now 26|access-date=14 March 2017|publisher=Bangkok Business Broadcasting, [[The Nation Group]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e08\u0e32\u0e30\u0e42\u0e04\u0e23\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e2d\u0e33\u0e19\u0e32\u0e08\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e13\u0e32\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=The Dhammakaya world's structure in depth|time=1:40}}</ref>]]\n\nThe temple gained great popularity during the 1980s (during the Asian economic boom), especially among the growing well-educated and entrepreneurial middle class, mostly small-business owners and technocrats of [[Sino-Thai]] origin. Royalty and high-standing civil servants also started to visit the temple,<ref name=\"Falk 2007\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/?id=mQ2_t8TMcAoC|title=Making fields of merit: Buddhist female ascetics and gendered orders in Thailand|date=2007|publisher=[[Nordic Centre in Shanghai|NIAS Press]]|isbn=978-87-7694-019-5|location=Copenhagen|last1=Falk|first1=Monica Lindberg}}</ref>{{sfn|McDaniel|2010|pp=41, 662}}{{sfn|Bechert|1997|p=176}} including the generals [[Arthit Kamlang-ek]] and [[Chaovalit Yongchaiyuth]].<ref name=\"McDaniel 2006\" />{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=136}} During this period the temple experienced tremendous growth in terms of monks, lay workers and temple visitors. The temple therefore established a screening procedure for newcomer employees.{{sfn|Heikkil\u00e4-Horn|2015|p=62}}{{sfn|McDaniel|2010|pp=41, 662}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=43}} Maechi Chandra set rules and regulations for the community, including a prohibition on political lobbying and selling things in the temple.<ref name=\"Now 26\"/> Wat Phra Dhammakaya emphasized values of prosperity, modernity and personal development, which made it attractive for the middle class,{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=52}} especially during times of quick cultural and social changes.{{sfn|Swearer|1991|p=656}}{{sfn|Taylor|1989|p=126}} By the mid-1980s, the temple was attracting up to fifty thousand people for major ceremonies.{{sfn|Zehner|2013|p=191}} The ''Dhammadaya'' ordination program started out with sixty participants in 1979; by 1986, over a thousand participants joined.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=doCmVaOnh_wC|title=Fundamentalisms and the state: remaking polities, economies, and militance|date=1993|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=0-226-50884-6|series=[[The Fundamentalism Project]]|volume=3|location=Chicago|chapter=Buddhist Economics and Buddhist Fundamentalism in Burma and Thailand|last1=Keyes|first1=Charles F|editor1-last=Marty|editor1-first=Martin E.|editor1-link=Martin E. Marty|editor2-last=Appleby|editor2-first=R. Scott}}</ref> In 1990, the temple had 260 monks, 214 ''[[samanera]]s'' (novices that are minors) and 441 full-time employees.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=35}} In 1995, Wat Phra Dhammakaya caught the nation's attention when a ''[[Magha Puja]]'' celebration was broadcast live on television, with [[Vajiralongkorn|the then Crown Prince Vajiralongkorn]] as chairman of the ceremony.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=65}}\n[[File:Dhammakaya ordination ceremony 2.jpg|thumb|Ordination ceremony for new monks at Wat Phra Dhammakaya]]\n\n=== Other activities ===\n\nWat Phra Dhammakaya became known for its emphasis on meditation, especially ''[[samatha]]'' meditation (meditation aiming at tranquility of mind). Every Sunday morning, meditation was taught to the public. Every weekend a meditation retreat was held at the temple at no cost. For these weekends, the temple started using the word ''[[dhutanga]]'' ('ascetic practice'<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Dhutanga|encyclopedia=Buddhist dictionary: manual of Buddhist terms and doctrines|publisher=[[Buddhist Publication Society]]|location=Kandy, Sri Lanka|url=http://www.buddhanet.net/e-learning/e-books/palidictionary.zip|accessdate=19 September 2016|date=1980|edition=4|page=101|isbn=9552400198|last1=Nyanatiloka|author-link=Nyanatiloka}}</ref>) for accommodation in the open air, a word normally used for monastic practice.{{sfn|Snodgrass|2003}}{{sfn|Swearer|1991|p=661}} Seven-day retreats were held regularly at several locations, during which participants were required to keep the eight precepts.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2001|title=New Karma: Buddhist democracy and the rule of law in Thailand|url=http://search.proquest.com/openview/d01d97fbc1017961cd05eabc481849af/1|journal=American Asian Review|volume=19|issue=4|page=149|url-access=subscription|last1=Ambuel|first1=David}}</ref>{{sfn|Thammachay\u014d|Thattach\u012bw\u014d|Tawandhamma Foundation|2007|pp=64\u201370}} Also, special retreats were led by Luang Por Dhammajayo himself in [[Doi Suthep]].{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=34}} With regard to [[Three Trainings|the three Trainings]] (''{{lang-pi|tisikkha}}'') in Buddhist teaching, the temple was described as the temple that represents the meditation aspect (''{{lang-pi|samadhi}}''), whereas the [[Santi Asoke]] movement represents the discipline aspect (''{{lang-pi|[[\u015a\u012bla|sila]]}}'') and [[Buddhadasa|Luang Por Buddhadasa]] and his followers the wisdom aspect (''{{lang-pi|[[Praj\u00f1\u0101 (Buddhism)|pa\u00f1\u00f1a]]}}'').{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=192}}{{sfn|Vasi|1998|p=68}}\n\nOne of the core activities of the temple, since its inception, has been the ceremony of 'honoring the Buddhas by food' ({{lang-th|\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e27\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30}}), held every first Sunday of the month. This ceremony was so important to the temple's adherents that people from all over the country traveled by bus to join it, from urban and rural areas. It was usually led by the abbot himself, and, up until her death, by Maechi Chandra Khonnokyoong too. According to the temple's practitioners, in this ceremony food is offered to the Buddhas in meditation. The ceremony has been an important aspect of the temple's attractiveness to the public.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=95\u20137}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=46, 48, 98\u20139}}\n\nThe temple also started to develop a social dimension in its activities. For example, it started promoting blood donations. The temple organized training programs for both the private and public sector, emphasizing peace and stability in society by training government officers to be more reliable.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=143}} The temple also became active in promoting Buddhist scholarship and educational reform in the ''[[Sangha]]'' (monastic community), producing a CD with searchable texts of the [[Pali Canon]] in 1984, in cooperation with the [[Pali Text Society]], [[Mahidol University]] and the [[University of California in Berkeley]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2005|title=Pali Text Society|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion|publisher=[[Thomson-Gale]]|location=Farmington Hills|url=https://www.politicalavenue.com/PDF/ENCYCLOPEDIAS/The%20Gale%20Encyclopedia%20of%20Religion%202nd%20Ed%20Vol.%2010.pdf|edition=2|volume=10|page=6956|author=Burford, Grace G.|editor=Jones, Lindsay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302051005/http://www.politicalavenue.com/PDF/ENCYCLOPEDIAS/The%20Gale%20Encyclopedia%20of%20Religion%202nd%20Ed%20Vol.%2010.pdf|archivedate=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Digital input of Buddhist texts|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|publisher=[[Taylor and Francis]]|location=Hoboken|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ|date=2013|authorlink=Lewis Lancaster|editor-link=Damien Keown|page=289|isbn=978-1-136-98588-1|last1=Lancaster|first1=Lewis R.|editor1-last=Keown|editor1-first=Damien|editor2-last=Prebish|editor2-first=Charles S.}}</ref> In 1990, the temple also organized its first academic seminar ''Buddhism into the Year 2000'', with over a hundred international scholars joining.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/?id=5_BOAQAAIAAJ|title=Buddhism into the Year 2000: International conference proceedings|date=1994|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|location=Bangkok|last1=Dhammakaya Foundation}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=121}} On a more local level, the temple started to organize a yearly congratulation ceremony for Pali graduates at the highest level, and offered funds to temples that excelled at teaching Pali.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=147}}<ref name=\"Dokbia 1999\">{{cite news|date=1 March 1999|work=Dokbia Thurakit|page=1|language=th|script-title=th:29 \u0e1b\u0e35\u0e1a\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e17\u0e32\u0e03\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21|trans-title=29 years on the path of the Dhamma}}</ref> The temple was known to have wide support from the Thai ''Sangha'' and was tolerated by the government, though at times the government asked the temple to limit its mass assemblies.<ref name=\"Scupin\">{{cite journal|year=2001|title=Parallels Between Buddhist and Islamic Movements in Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/273456943|journal=Prajna Vihara|volume=2|issue=1|author=Scupin, Raymond}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1993|p=178}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=116\u20139}} In 1985, the Department of Religious Affairs, [[Ministry of Education (Thailand)|Ministry of Education]], prohibited the building of a meditation center in a rural area, citing as a reason that it was not accessible enough for people to visit.{{sfn|Taylor|1989|p=116}} Fuengfusakul concludes that during this period the government was afraid of the temple's ability to gather a large number of people.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1993|p=178}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=119}}\n\nIn 1986, the Dhammakaya Foundation became a United Nations-accredited non-governmental organization,{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010|p=886}} and started sending delegations to join workshops on youth and peace education. {{As of|2015|alt=As of 2015}}, the foundation was in consultative status with the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council|Economic and Social Council]].{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=137}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esango.un.org/civilsociety/consultativeStatusSummary.do?profileCode=2823|title=United Nations Civil Society Participation (iCSO)|website=Integrated Civil Society Organizations System|publisher=United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs, NGO Branch|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=E/CN.6/2016/NGO/82|title=United Nations Economic and Social Council-Commission on the Status of Women|date=17 November 2015|website=[[United Nations]]|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> In the 1980s, the foundation also became a member of the World Fellowship of Buddhist Youth and the [[World Fellowship of Buddhists]] networks, and later the chairman of the World Fellowship of Buddhist Youth. The foundation started to build up many relations with Buddhist organizations outside of Thailand, including [[Fo Guang Shan]] in Taiwan and the [[Ten Thousand Buddhas Monastery]] in Hong Kong,{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=122}}{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010|p=886}} with Wat Phra Dhammakaya and Fo Guang Shan officially declaring each other sister temples in 1994.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=145}}\n\nFrom 1992 onwards, the temple started to found its first branch centers, in the United States, Japan and Taiwan.<ref name=\"Forbes 2015\" />{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=123}}\n\n=== Construction ===\n\nThe ''Ubosot'' was completed in 1982, and the ceremony for allocating of the ''Ubosot's'' boundary was held three years later.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=73}} In 1984, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started expanding the temple's ground with two thousand ''rai'' (3.2&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>). Surrounding land was bought from a land owner, on the condition that the temple would deal with the sixty-one farmers who rented the land. The temple offered the renting farmers the option to end the contract early and obtain a compensation, or to stay until the contract ended and then leave. Seven farmers disagreed with both proposals, however, and the temple raised its offer, but to no avail. The resisting farmers then organized a protest, which was joined by a hundred land tenants from other places who felt unfairly treated by real estate firms.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=56\u20138}}\n[[File:Cetiya Gate Warning.JPG|left|thumb|The Dhammakaya Cetiya, Wat Phra Dhammakaya]]\nThe protest, which was featured in all major Thai newspapers,{{sfn|Taylor|1989}}{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2325}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=136}} ended with the tenants handing over a letter at a government office, asking for justice. The government investigated the temple's case, but concluded that the temple had acted lawfully. Outraged by the outcome, a number of protesters destroyed some parts of Wat Phra Dhammakaya's temple grounds, and the mob leader was arrested and imprisoned. The local municipality had to mediate and was able to persuade some of the farmers to accept the temple's proposal. Wat Phra Dhammakaya stated that they believed the protests were stirred up by investors who wanted the land for themselves.<ref>{{cite news|title=Detractor's testimony slams Dhammakaya|date=19 January 1999|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=56\u20138}}\n\nIn 1994, the temple began designing for the building of a huge ''[[stupa]]'' (a mound-like structure) which was later to become known as the Maha Dhammakaya Cetiya. The monument would be built to last for a thousand years, and would consist of a million Buddha images. An experienced architect and experienced engineers were employed, and the latest technology was used in the construction, to meet the demands of the project and to follow the [[Stupa#Construction|traditions of ''cetiyas'' and ''stupas'']]. Though traditionally ''stupas'' were often financed by kings, the Dhammakaya Cetiya was to be financed by people of all parts of society, all contributing their part. Attempts were made to involve the devotees of the temple through different stages of construction, through organizing meditations around the Cetiya, and holding ceremonies, in which people were given hammers to symbolically hit a foundation pile into the ground.{{sfn|Snodgrass|2003}}\n\n== First clash with government (1997\u20132000) ==\n\n=== The miracle controversy ===\n\nIn the late 1990s, Wat Phra Dhammakaya became known for its modern management and iconography,<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|year=1994|title=Thai Buddhism Today: Crisis?|encyclopedia=Buddhism into the Year 2000|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|location=Khlong Luang, Patumthani|url=https://books.google.com/books/?id=5_BOAQAAIAAJ|last=Na Songkhla|first=N.|pages=115\u20136|isbn=9748920933}}</ref> and became active in using modern media and public relations, to a scale which was until then unknown in Thailand.<ref name=\"Taylor 2008\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HiVoq_OHit4C|title=Buddhism and Postmodern Imaginings in Thailand: The Religiosity of Urban Space|date=2008|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]]|isbn=978-0-7546-6247-1|last1=Taylor|first1=Jim|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> The temple even received a prize for best marketing strategies from the Marketing Association of Thailand, despite its earlier prohibition on commercial practices in the temple.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.khamkoo.com/uploads/9/0/0/4/9004485/thailand_-_the_worldly_kingdom.pdf|title=Thailand: The worldly kingdom|last=Peleggi|first=Maurizio|publisher=[[Reaktion Books]]|year=2007|location=London|page=114}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1993|pp=160, 168}} In 1998, the temple first started to hold large-scale training programs, for laymen (13,824 participants) laywomen (140,000 participants){{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=44}}{{sfn|Snodgrass|2003}} and ''samaneras'' (13,842 participants).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=15 July 1998|work=Khao Sod|page=27|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e23\u0e1e\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e2d\u0e38\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e41\u0e01\u0e49\u0e27\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e36\u0e48\u0e07\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e04\u0e19 \u0e23\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e01\u0e38\u0e28\u0e25\u0e16\u0e27\u0e32\u0e22\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e35|trans-title=100,000 ''ratana-upasikas'' practice renunciation in honor of the Queen|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The temple received much financial support, including donations from real-estate firms.{{sfn|Satha-Anand|1990|p=401}}\n\nIn November 1998, after a ceremony held at the Cetiya of the temple, the temple reported in brochures and national newspapers that a miracle ({{lang-th|\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e28\u0e08\u0e23\u0e23\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e15\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e41\u0e01\u0e49\u0e27}}) had occurred at the Cetiya, which was witnessed by thousands of people. The miracle involved seeing an image of a Buddha or of [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro|Luang Pu Sodh]] imposed on the sun. Shortly afterwards, the Thai media responded very critically, leading to a nationwide, very intense debate about the state of [[Thai Buddhism]] in general, and Wat Phra Dhammakaya in particular, that lasted for an unusually long ten months. Critics believed that Wat Phra Dhammakaya, and Thai Buddhism in general, had become too much of a commercial enterprise ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e1e\u0e32\u0e19\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e22\u0e4c}}) and had grown corrupt; practitioners and temple devotees argued tradition was being followed.<ref name=\"Falk 2007\" />{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=2\u20133, 13, 124}}\n\nThe main criticism was that the temple was using fundraising methods that did not fit in with Buddhism. Examples that were pointed out were the fact that fundraising resembled [[direct sales]], the distribution of amulets to donors as complementary gifts and the use of modern technology.{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=124, 141}} Scholars in Buddhism, such as [[Prayudh Payutto|Luang Por Payutto]], social critic [[Sulak Sivaraksa]], as well as two monks who formerly lived at the temple, all argued against the temple's fundraising methods. Moreover, some teachings of the temple were criticized: the idea that large donations yield greater fruits or [[Merit (Buddhism)|merit]], and the idea that ''Nibbana'' was the [[Atman (Buddhism)|true self]].{{sfn|Scott|2009 |pp=129\u201330, 135, 137\u20138}} (See \u00a7\u2009[[Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Principles, practices and beliefs|Principles, practices and beliefs]]) Although many of these methods and teachings were not unique to Wat Phra Dhammakaya, the criticism came at a moment when the temple had become very noticeable due to its size, its high-profile supporters, and due to the project of building the Cetiya, which required a lot of funds.{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=391}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=132\u20134}} All of this was against the backdrop of the [[1997 Asian financial crisis|financial crisis]] that Thailand was going through.<ref name=\"Gearing\">{{cite news|url=http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/intelligence/9912/30/|title=Buddhist Scapegoat?: One Thai abbot is taken to task, but the whole system is to blame|last=Gearing|first=Julian|date=30 December 1999|work=[[Asiaweek]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625164034/http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/intelligence/9912/30/|archivedate=25 June 2009}}</ref>{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=132\u20134}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=55}}\n\nWat Phra Dhammakaya replied to the critics of the Cetiya building project that the building had begun before the crisis, when the economy was still booming; therefore, the timing was not wrong. The temple also raised examples of other important Thai building projects that had been realized during crises. Finally, the temple posed the question: if, despite the crisis, people were still buying alcohol and cigarettes and still going to the movies, then what was wrong with donating for a religious building?<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e48\u0e32\u0e07\u0e15\u0e30\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e14\u0e15\u0e39\u0e21\u0e15\u0e32\u0e21|date=28 November 1998|work=[[Khao Sod]]|pages=1, 12|language=th|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/THAILAND-BUDDHIST-SECT-ACCUSED-OF-PREYING-ON-THE-POOR/c8d88861c2c2d66d7be264028b606cb8|title=Thailand: Buddhist Sect Accused of Preying on the Poor|date=30 May 1999|work=[[Associated Press|AP Archive]]|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=127}} The temple also responded to its critics about the accusations of wealth, stating that the temple's wealth was used for the laypeople and Buddhist education, not for other purposes. Building large buildings benefited Buddhism as a whole, not just the temple, because it helped strengthen the religion. Apart from donating to hospitals or schools, financially supporting Buddhism should also be done, because it would help foster ethics in society.<ref name=\"Gearing 1999\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/magazine/99/0917/thai_intvu.html|title=Abbot Dhammachayo: 'I Will Never Be Disrobed'|date=17 September 1999|work=[[Asiaweek]]|agency=[[CNN]]|issue=25/37|last1=Gearing|first1=Julian|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PR 1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dhammakaya.or.th/thai/fact/html/fact_document_41-02.html|date=19 December 1998|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|location=Patumthani|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07\u0e09\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 2/2541-\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e20\u0e32\u0e27\u0e19\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e34\u0e4c\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e16\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19|trans-title=Announcement 2/2541-Phrarajbhavanavisudh and land ownership|author1=PR Department Team|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312140144/http://www.dhammakaya.or.th/thai/fact/html/fact_document_41-02.html|archivedate=12 March 2005}}</ref>{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=145}}\n\n=== Investigations and lawsuits ===\n\nUnder pressure of public outcry and critics, January 1999 the [[Sangha Supreme Council]] started an investigation in the accusations, led by {{ill|Luang Por \u00d1anavaro|th|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e42\u0e21\u0e25\u0e35 (\u0e27\u0e34\u0e25\u0e32\u0e28 \u0e0d\u0e32\u0e13\u0e27\u0e42\u0e23)}}, Chief of the \u0e3a[[Greater Bangkok]] Region.<ref name=\"Matichon 2006\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=23 August 2006|work=Matichon|page=16|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e22\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=Review of Dhammajayo's lawsuits|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{refn|Then known by the title \"Phraprommolee\".|group=note}} The Sangha Council declared that Wat Phra Dhammakaya had not broken any serious offenses against monastic discipline (''[[Vinaya]]'') that were cause for [[defrock]]ing (removal from monkhood), but four directives were given for the temple to improve itself: setting up an ''[[Abhidhamma]]'' school, more focus on ''[[vipassana]]'' meditation, and strict adherence to the rules of the ''Vinaya'' and regulations of the Sangha Council.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://opac.mbu.ac.th/Record/3070|title=\u0e27\u0e34\u0e40\u0e04\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e4c\u0e19\u0e34\u0e04\u0e2b\u0e01\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21 \u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|last=Udomsi|first=Sawaeng|year=2000|isbn=974-7078-11-2|location=Bangkok|pages=81\u20135|language=th|trans-title=Analysis of Disciplinary Transactions of Dhammakaya|chapter=\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e08\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e32\u0e14\u0e33\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e15\u0e32\u0e21\u0e21\u0e15\u0e34\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e40\u0e16\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e04\u0e21 \u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e53\u0e52/\u0e52\u0e55\u0e54\u0e51|trans-chapter=Report of Evaluation of the Treatment of the Case Wat Phra Dhammakaya-Verdict of the Supreme Sangha Council 32/2541 B.E.}}</ref> One of the accusations Luang Por \u00d1anavaro investigated was that Luang Por Dhammajayo had moved land donated to the temple to his own name.{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=129, 137, 143}}<ref name=\"Thai PBS 150722\" /> Wat Phra Dhammakaya denied this, stating that it was the intention of the donors to give the land to the abbot, and not the temple.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.dhammakaya.net/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, Luang Por \u00d1anavaro asked the {{ill|Religious Affairs Department|th|\u0e01\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32}} to assist Luang Por Dhammajayo in returning the land to the temple.<ref name=\"RAD 1999\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=7 March 1999|work=Matichon|page=2|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e38\u0e1b\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e21\u0e32\u0e40\u0e01\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e27\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e14\u0e33\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Overview of how the Case Dhammakaya was handled|via=Matichon E-library|author=Religious Affairs Department, [[Ministry of Education (Thailand)]]|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The abbot stated he was willing to transfer the land, but this required some time, because it required negotiation with the original donors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Dhammachayo for land transfer postponement|date=26 May 1999|work=[[The Nation]]|page=A6|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> When by May the temple had not moved all the land yet, a number of things happened.\n\nFirst, a letter was leaked to the press which was signed by the [[Supreme Patriarch]] (head of the Thai monastic community). This implied that Luang Por Dhammajayo had to disrobe because he had not transferred donated land back to the temple. A warning had preceded this letter, which government officials said had not yet been forwarded to the Sangha Council and Wat Phra Dhammakaya. The statement had a great impact.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/pxBoz8|date=18 December 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e06\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e52\u0e50|trans-title=The 20th Sangharaja|accessdate=18 December 2016|time=9:12}}</ref><ref name=\"Puengnet 1999\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=10 December 1999|work=\u0e3a Bangkok Biz News|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=2|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e25\u0e33\u0e14\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c 1 \u0e1b\u0e35\u0e41\u0e04\u0e48\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e01\u0e15\u0e33\u0e41\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e48\u0e07\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=Timeline of events: Sangha dealing with Sangha, after 1 year only suspension for Dhammajayo|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Puengnet|first1=Pakorn|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In response, the Religious Affairs Department pressed criminal charges of embezzlement against the abbot and a close aide.<ref name=\"Matichon 2006\" /><ref name=\"Puengnet 1999\" /> The temple stated that, being subject to a criminal lawsuit (as opposed to a {{ill|religious trial|th|\u0e2d\u0e18\u0e34\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e16\u0e30}}), the abbot would no longer transfer the land, because this might be interpreted as acceptance of guilt. Wat Phra Dhammakaya and the Sangha Council requested the department to wait until the monastic trials were finished first, but it continued the lawsuit.<ref name=\"RAD 1999\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Clarification sought over land transfer|date=6 June 1999|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|page=3|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Bunnag|first1=Sirikul|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Moreover, the department set up a public help-desk and post office box to receive complaints about the temple,<ref name=\"Matichon 990913\" />{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=51}} security officials of other departments stated they \"were closely monitoring Dhammachayo\",{{sfn|Streckfuss|Templeton|2002||page=76}} and Prince Vajiralongkorn personally showed an interest in the investigations.<ref>{{cite conference|last=Keyes|first=C.F.|date=July 1999|title=Buddhism fragmented: Thai Buddhism and political order since the 1970s|conference=Seventh International Thai Studies Conference, Amsterdam|conference-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030815202556/http://www2.fmg.uva.nl/seamain/icts7/index.html|url=https://www.academia.edu/download/45522452/Keyes_Buddhism_Fragmented.pdf|url-access=registration|page=27}}</ref> With the resulting witness accounts, more charges were laid against Luang Por Dhammajayo. In the process of these investigations, the main politicians responsible, that is the [[Ministry of Education (Thailand)|Minister and Deputy Minister of Education]], were both replaced, with the new Minister [[Somsak Prissanananthakul]] assuming a key role in the judicial processes against the abbot.<ref name=\"Puengnet 1999\" />\n[[File:The Dhammakaya Cetiya.jpg|thumb|The Dhammakaya Cetiya at night.]]\nIn June, the prosecutors started summoning Luang Por Dhammajayo, but he did not go to acknowledge the charges, citing bad health.<ref name=\"Voice 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://shows.voicetv.co.th/wakeupnews/369792.html|date=27 June 2016|work=VoiceTV|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:18 \u0e1b\u0e35\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e08\u0e1a\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e19\u0e35\u0e49?|trans-title=18 years of lawsuits against Phra Dhammajayo: will it end with this government?|accessdate=18 December 2016|time=4:12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221080839/http://shows.voicetv.co.th/wakeupnews/369792.html|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The temple cited the legal rights of monks under the constitution, pointing out that possessing personal property is common and legal in the Thai Sangha.<ref name=\"PR 1998\" />{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=138}} Spokespeople also questioned the authenticity of the letter of the Patriarch.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=143}}{{refn|The Supreme Patriarch had fallen ill, and could not easily be visited {{See below|{{section link||''Junta''<nowiki />'s reform council versus Sangha Council}}, below}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|url-access=subscription|via=Matichon E-library|work=Matichon|date=15 May 1999|access-date=13 February 2017|page=19|script-title=th:\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e19\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e43\u0e08\u0e44\u0e0a\u0e22\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c \u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e40\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e27\u0e04\u0e37\u0e19\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e48\u0e33\u0e02\u0e32\u0e14\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19|language=th|trans-title=Chuan believes Chaiyabul will return land, Dhammakaya is disorganized and lacks money}}</ref> Luang Por Dhammajayo then declared publicly that he would not disrobe under any circumstances, but \"would die in the [monk's] saffron robes\".{{sfn|Scott|2006|p=223}} When the Prime Minister himself pressured the abbot to acknowledge the charges, the temple asked for a guarantee that the abbot would not be imprisoned and consequently defrocked.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=53}}{{Refn|Disrobing effectively strips a Buddhist monk from his status and position within the monastic community, and is therefore considered by practitioners tantamount to execution.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007}}<ref name=\"Janruang 2017\">{{cite news|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2017/03/70346|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e30\u0e08\u0e1a\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e48\u0e32\u0e07\u0e44\u0e23|language=th|trans-title=How will the Dhammakaya case end?|first=Chamnan|last=Janruang|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=1 March 2017|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref>|group=note}} No such guarantee was given, an arrest warrant followed, and a standoff began between a police force of hundreds, and thousands of the temple's practitioners, in which the latter barricaded the temple's entrances. After two days, Luang Por Dhammajayo agreed to let the police take him when the requested guarantee was given, and a Sangha Council member threatened to defrock the abbot if he did not go with the police.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 150722\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/99/0514/feat8.html|title=Scandal over a monk's property|date=1999|work=[[Asiaweek]]|agency=[[CNN]]|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/26/world/world-briefing.html|title=Thailand: Monk ends standoff|date=26 August 1999|work=[[The New York Times]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|last1=Neilan|first1=Terence|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> The abbot was interrogated for three hours, but not defrocked. Then he was released on a bail of two million baht, still on the same day. The news made headlines worldwide. From November onward, Luang Por Dhammajayo started visiting the court for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=23 October 1999|work=Matichon|page=23|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e19\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e0d\u0e0a\u0e35 28 \u0e15.\u0e04.|trans-title=Dhammakaya's lawyer makes appointment on 28 October and clears up issue of closing bank account|via=Matichon E-library}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=19 November 1999|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|page=11|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1c\u0e27\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e36\u0e21\u0e0b\u0e49\u0e33 2 \u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e28\u0e34\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e15\u0e23\u0e36\u0e07\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e23|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry of Education also accused Luang Por Dhammajayo of having stated that the [[Tipitaka]] (Buddhist scriptures) was incomplete.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 161119\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fpUy7JsaKjI|date=25 January 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e06\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e52\u0e50|trans-title=The 20th Supreme Patriarch|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> This accusation was religious in nature, however, and would normally only be made by other monks in a monastic trial. Luang Por \u00d1anavaro and Wat Phra Dhammakaya therefore questioned the [[jurisdiction]] of laypeople in this matter.<ref name=\"Nation 1999\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Abbot's followers seek statute court's ruling|date=1 September 1999|work=[[The Nation]]|page=A2|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=53}} Indeed, despite certain powers that the ministry had about religious matters, in the 1990s, there was no law against \"heresy\" in Thailand. Nevertheless, religious and state officials continued to assert that the temple's teachings constituted criminal offenses.{{sfn|Streckfuss|Templeton|2002|pp=76\u20137}} Eventually it was decided that the charges could be pressed, as long as the accuser in the final trial was a monk. A period of investigation passed by, after which Luang Por \u00d1anavaro insisted that the Sangha Council's four-point advice had been sufficient.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=29 November 1999|work=Dokbia Thurakit|page=7|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e19\u0e34\u0e04\u0e2b\u0e01\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21 \u0e1a\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e08\u0e19\u0e4c\u0e20\u0e39\u0e21\u0e34\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e0d\u0e0d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e21\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22|trans-title=The Case Dhammakaya: a test of wisdom for Thai society|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Discussions arose in the media, questioning the authority of the Thai Sangha and government to deal with problems within the Thai Sangha,<ref name=\"bun\" />{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=139}} and Luang Por \u00d1anavaro was removed from the Sangha Council and replaced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=15 September 1999|work=Matichon|page=24|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07 \u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e18\u0e35 \u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e20\u0e32\u0e04 1 \u0e0a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e27\u0e04\u0e23\u0e32\u0e27|trans-title=Phrathepsutthi temporarily appointed as acting Head of Region 1|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Luang Por Dhammajayo was suspended as abbot, as the trials continued and Luang Por Dhammajayo's deputies continued to manage the temple.<ref name=\"AP 991007\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19991007&id=cOROAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fxQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6903,2508411|title=Thai monk to stand down from temple duties|date=7 October 1999|work=[[New Straits Times]]|agency=[[The Associated Press]]|issue=413/12/99|page=19|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=139}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=53\u20134}} The chief monk overseeing the local temples in the area had to be removed from office in the process, because he refused to suspend Luang Por Dhammajayo.<ref name=\"Puengnet 1999\" /> Luang Por Dhammajayo had fallen ill and was hospitalized with throat and lung infections.<ref name=\"Gearing\" /><ref name=\"AP 991007\" /> In the 2000s, the controversies gradually lost the interest of the public, as the news focused on other topics,{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=154}} although in 2002 a fifth charge against the abbot was added to the list.<ref name=\"Nation 2002\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/search/page.arcview.php?clid=2&id=59039&usrsess=|title=Controversial monk faces fresh charges|date=26 April 2002|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713160550/http://www.nationmultimedia.com/search/page.arcview.php?clid=2&id=59039&usrsess=|archivedate=13 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seapabkk.org/fellowships/2002/yasmin.html|title=Scandals Threaten Thai Monks' Future|last=Arpon|first=Yasmin Lee|date=11 July 2002|work=SEAPA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041013030503/http://www.seapabkk.org/fellowships/2002/yasmin.html|archive-date=13 October 2004}}</ref>{{refn|The five charges were: helping a civil servant to act unlawfully, two charges of embezzlement of land and two charges of embezzlement of money.<ref name=\"Puengnet 1999\" /><ref name=\"Naew Na 2006\" />|group=note}} The trials proceeded slowly, as the hearings were postponed because of evidence that was not ready, and because of the abbot's illness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=19 June 2003|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=3|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35 \u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e31\u0e01\u0e22\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14|trans-title=Hearing Dhammajayo embezzlement money temple postponed|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=\u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e1f\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e33\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07 \u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|date=26 August 2003|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=16|language=th|trans-title=Hearing verdict Dhammajayo postponed|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n=== The temple's response ===\n\nDuring the Supreme Sangha's investigations, the temple responded little to the accusations. But when the Ministry of Education decided to no longer wait on the Sangha Council's investigations, and pressed charges on Wat Phra Dhammakaya, the temple responded by suing for [[malicious prosecution]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2053923,00.html|title=Trouble in Nirvana|date=28 June 1999|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last2=Horn|first2=Robert|last1=Liebhold|first1=David|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Naew Na, 8 December 1999|p=7}} The temple accused several leading people in the Ministry of abusing their position, and petitioned the [[Constitutional Court of Thailand|Constitutional Court]], calling the religious charges a violation of [[Freedom of religion in Thailand|freedom of religion]].<ref name=\"Nation 1999\" /> Spokespeople and proponents of the temple described the response of the ministry and the media as \"stirring up controversy\", and politically motivated.<ref name=\"Nation 2002\" /><ref name=\"Phraputthasat 1999\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=14 June 1999|work=Dokbia Thurakit|pages=3\u20134|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e21\u0e25\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e34\u0e01\u0e24\u0e15\u0e34\u0e27\u0e07\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22+\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e21\u0e44\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e34|trans-title=Phra Phimontham's and Phra Dhammajayo's case studies: crisis in Thai Sangha and the mindlessness of society|via=Matichon E-library|author=Phraputthasat-mahabandit|accessdate=11 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nDuring this period, many news reporters used pejorative language in describing the Sangha Council, the Supreme Patriarch, or Wat Phra Dhammakaya. In May 1999, {{ill|monastic chiefs of regions|th|\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e20\u0e32\u0e04}} nationwide sent a letter to the Prime Minister to help protect Buddhism and pressure media to use more polite language and show more respect for judicial processes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 May 1999|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|page=14|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1b\u0e32\u0e01\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e04\u0e19\u0e1c\u0e34\u0e14|trans-title=The Patriarch of Wat Paknam is not favored to the guilty|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> News reporters would often use abusive or pejorative language describing the temple or Luang Por Dhammajayo, such as 'idiot with glasses' ({{lang-th|\u0e44\u0e2d\u0e49\u0e41\u0e27\u0e48\u0e19}})<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e1b\u0e17\u0e38\u0e21\u0e18\u0e32\u0e19\u0e35\u0e22\u0e31\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e14\u0e41\u0e19\u0e48 \u0e44\u0e2d\u0e49\u0e41\u0e27\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19|date=14 November 1999|work=[[Khao Sod]]|publisher=Matichon Publishing|page=1|language=th|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> or simply calling Luang Por Dhammajayo by his first name used as a layman, \"Chaiyabun\", as though he had already been defrocked. December 1999, Wat Phra Dhammakaya sued the newspapers [[Matichon]], [[Siam Rath]], [[Khao Sod]], [[Daily News (Thailand)|Daily News]] and the television station [[ITV (Thailand)|ITV]]. The temple laid civil and criminal charges for slander, accusing the media outlets for depicting the temple in a distorted way.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Dhammakaya to file suits against media|date=8 December 1999|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|page=7|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Naew Na, 8 December 1999|p=1}} In 2001 and 2003, ITV, Siam Rath,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhammakaya.net/blog/2001/10/03/\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22-2|last=Naphaket|first=Sakda|date=3 October 2001|work=Siam Rath Sapdavichan|access-date=6 December 2016|publisher=Siam Rath|issue=52/17691|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e01\u0e32\u0e28|trans-title=Announcement|via=dhammakaya.net}}</ref> and Matichon<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|last=Srisuwan|first=Suchat|date=19 July 2003|work=Matichon|page=10|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e33\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07|trans-title=Announcement|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pochanalawan|first1=Pinyapan|script-title=th:'\u0e17\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e24\u0e17\u0e18\u0e34\u0e4c...\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e40\u0e08\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e4c' \u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e14\u0e49\u0e27\u0e22\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e08\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e4c|trans-title='Fully dedicated to finish the Cetiya': About the saga of the Mahadhammakaya Cetiya|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2009/04/20960|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=22 April 2009|language=th}}</ref> were found guilty of slander and forced by verdict to issue a public apology in their newspapers,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dmc.tv/images/annoucement/Media-ask-for-forgiveness/440621-Bangkokbusiness.jpg|last=Chairat|first=Krisana|date=21 June 2001|work=Bangkok Biz News|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|issue=4655|volume=14|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e01\u0e32\u0e28|trans-title=Announcement|via=[[Dhammakaya Media Channel]]|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dmc.tv/images/annoucement/Media-ask-for-forgiveness/440624-Bangkokbusiness.jpg|last=Chairat|first=Krisana|date=24 June 2001|work=Bangkok Biz News|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|volume=14|page=11|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e01\u0e32\u0e28|trans-title=Announcement|via=[[Dhammakaya Media Channel]]|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref>{{refn|ITV doing so through Bangkok Biz News, also owned by [[The Nation Group]].|group=note}} admitting to publishing distorted information about Luang Por Dhammajayo trading in stock, transferring money to mistresses, and other accusations. Siam Rath was also found guilty of violating the authority of the court, by publishing incorrect information on a verdict.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhammakaya.net/blog/2001/09/16/\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22-1|date=16 September 2001|work=Siam Rath|access-date=1 May 2016|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e01\u0e32\u0e28|trans-title=Announcement|via=dhammakaya.net}}</ref> The charges laid against Daily News were dismissed, however, because of being laid too late.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=14 November 2000|work=[[Daily News (Thailand)]]|publisher=Si Phrayakarn|page=2|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Charges Dhammakaya not accepted|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the period of intense media attention of 1999\u20132000 had disastrous effects on the temple, the temple still continued to organize projects, ceremonies and other events. The temple persuaded supporters nationwide to open their homes or workplaces as ''[[kalyanamitta]]'' homes ('houses of good Dhamma friends'), for establishing a culture of shared meditation practice and wisdom.<ref name=\"Matichon 1999\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=|last=|first=|date=28 June 1999|work=Matichon|access-date=1 November 2016|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e14\u0e34\u0e49\u0e19\u0e14\u0e39\u0e14\u0e25\u0e39\u0e01\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32 \u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e07\u0e27\u0e31\u0e25\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e48\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e01\u0e01\u0e31\u0e25\u0e22\u0e32\u0e13\u0e21\u0e34\u0e15\u0e23|trans-title=Dhammakaya struggles and attracts customers, announces prize for finding more ''kalyanamitta'' members|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2000, during a celebration of the new millennium at the newly built Dhammakaya Cetiya, 300,000 people joined. Many monks from different temples of Thailand joined as well, and temples and NGOs from outside of Thailand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 April 2000|work=Naewna|page=5|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e19\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e1e\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e21\u0e32\u0e01\u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32 3 \u0e41\u0e2a\u0e19 \u0e41\u0e2b\u0e48\u0e09\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e22\u0e34\u0e48\u0e07\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e48|trans-title=Going against the tide of Phra Dhammajayo's lawsuits: 300,000 people show their strength in a grand procession|via=Matichon e-library|author=Special event team of Naewna|url-access=subscription}}</ref> This period also brought [[Boonchai Bencharongkul]] to the temple, then CEO of the telecommunications company [[DTAC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2015/06/24/artistic-expression/|title=From Mobile to Art: Boonchai of Thailand Opens Private Museum|website=[[Forbes Asia]]|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In 1999, the temple had thirteen centers outside of Thailand.{{sfn|Matichon, 10 January 1999|p=4}}\n\nWhen in 2000 the Thai Maharat Party was founded, it was suspected the temple had a hand in it. Founder Kanin Boonsuwan denied the temple's influence in the founding, although he admitted some of its members were Dhammakaya practitioners.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Kanin dismisses cult role in setting up Thai Maharat|date=24 October 2000|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|page=3|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=15 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=125}}\n\nIn 2000, Maechi Chandra Konnokyoong died. The temple announced it would give people the time to pay their respects for several months, after which Maechi Chandra's remains would be cremated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=18 September 2000|work=Matichon|page=19|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e27\u0e01\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e28\u0e1e\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e14\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e16\u0e36\u0e07\u0e21.\u0e04.\u0e1b\u0e35\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e49\u0e32|trans-title=Dhammakaya's disciples commemorate Chi Chandra, chanting until January next year {{bracket|before cremating}}|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n== Nationwide activities (2001\u20132006) ==\n\nThe period of 2001 to 2006 was the period that [[Thaksin Shinawatra]] came into power. It was a period of increased democratization and diversification of [[civil society]] in Thailand, as the Thai parliament withdrew itself from religious affairs. The temple thrived on this, though the temple did work on similar objectives as the government in terms of education, health care and even national security. The temple was no longer at the margins of the religious landscape in Thailand, but started to integrate itself within the [[Maha Nikaya]] fraternity.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|pp=116\u20137, 120, 125, 156}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1999|title=The politics of Buddhism in Southeast Asia|encyclopedia=Religion, globalization and the political culture in the Third World|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|location=Basingstoke|url=https://books.google.com/?id=g0C_DAAAQBAJ|last=McCargo|first=Duncan|editor-last=Haynes|editor-first=Jeff|page=219|isbn=978-1-349-27038-5}}</ref> It was the period the temple cremated their teacher Maechi Chandra, and it was a period that the temple started to expand its activities to a national scale.\n\n=== Cremation of Maechi Chandra Khonnokyoong ===\n\nOn 3 February 2002, Maechi Chandra's remains were cremated, and abbots of 30,000 temples were invited to join the cremation, to give the lay people the chance to make merit in gratitude to Maechi Chandra. During the cremation, there was merit-making and meditation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=21 January 2002|work=Matichon|page=5|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e19\u0e37\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e4c\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30 3 \u0e2b\u0e21\u0e37\u0e48\u0e19 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e41\u0e21\u0e48\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c|trans-title=Dhammakaya invites 30,000 monks to cremate Maechi Chandra|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=5 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> 100,000 monks and another 100,000 laypeople joined the cremation. Many high-standing guests joined, including the [[Supreme Patriarch of Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=17 February 2002|work=Naew Na|pages=1\u20132|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e38\u0e14\u0e44\u0e1f\u0e41\u0e01\u0e49\u0e27\u0e2a\u0e25\u0e32\u0e22\u0e23\u0e48\u0e32\u0e07\u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e22\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e19\u0e19\u0e01\u0e22\u0e39\u0e07|trans-title=Igniting the Crystal Fire cremating Khun Yay Chandra Konnokyoong|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=5 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2002/02/02/fea04.html|title=Upasika Khun Yai, the founder of Dhammakaya|date=1 February 2002|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|publisher=Lake House|last1=Nemsiri|first1=Mutukumara|accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> Maechi Chandra's remains were burnt in a grand ceremony, using glass to ignite the fire by sun light. Her ashes were kept in a small ''stupa''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=200,000 {{bracket| people say}} farewell {{bracket|to}} sect founder|date=4 February 2002|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|page=1|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Somsin|first1=Benjawan|accessdate=5 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 January 2002|work=Dokbia Thurakit|page=1|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e25\u0e39\u0e01\u0e28\u0e34\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e22\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e23\u0e27\u0e21\u0e08\u0e34\u0e15\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e36\u0e48\u0e07 \u0e17\u0e33\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d 3 \u0e2b\u0e21\u0e37\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14|trans-title=Students of Khun Yay Chandra make merit for 30,000 temples in unity|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> Critics said the cremation was too grand for a nun, but the Religious Affairs Department said it was the temple's right to organize the event at this scale.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=2 February 2002|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|pages=1, 16|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2e\u0e36\u0e01\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e34\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e28\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e32\u0e22\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e34\u0e48\u0e07\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e48\u0e40\u0e01\u0e34\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38|trans-title=Dhammakaya arrogantly cremates remains Maechi Yay in too grand way|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=5 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=5 February 2002|work=Matichon|page=15|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e23\u0e21\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e1c\u0e34\u0e14|trans-title=RAD announced that there is nothing wrong with Dhammakaya cremating Maechi Chandra|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=5 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Scott cites Maechi Chandra's cremation as evidence that some female religious leaders have had a great impact on Thai society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scott|first=Rachelle M.|date=2010|title=Buddhism, miraculous powers, and gender: Rethinking the stories of Therav\u0101da nuns|url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/viewFile/9291/3152|journal=Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies|volume=33|issue=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaigns against drinking and smoking ===\n\nIn the 2000s, the temple began to focus more on promoting an ethical lifestyle, using the five and [[Eight Precepts|eight precepts]] as a foundation.<ref name=\"Scupin\" />{{sfn|Zehner|1990|p=424}} Nationwide people were encouraged to quit drinking and smoking through a campaign called ''The Lao Phao Buri'' ({{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e17\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e35\u0e48}}, literally: 'throw away alcohol and burn cigarettes'), cooperating with other religious traditions. This project led the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) to present a [[World No Tobacco Day]] award to Luang Por Dhammajayo on 31 May 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/tobacco/communications/events/wntd/2004/awards/en/index5.html|title=List of World No Tobacco Day awardees-2004|date=17 September 2011|website=[[World Health Organization]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=71}}{{sfn|Seeger|2006|p=7}} Over two hundred ''The Lao Phao Buri'' ceremonies were held, involving literally the pouring away of alcoholic beverages and the burning of cigarettes.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=153}} The ceremonies were later to become a regular practice in schools and government institutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://breakingnews.nationtv.tv/home/read.php?newsid=764743|date=29 July 2015|work=Nation TV|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e01\u0e25\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23\u0e40\u0e17\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32 \u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e07\u0e14\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e23\u0e29\u0e32|trans-title=Sakon Nakhon's soldiers throw away their alcohol and cigarettes at start of Rains Retreat|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psl.ac.th/wpweb/?p=1239|date=2 June 2016|work=Paliang Padungsit School|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e34\u0e08\u0e01\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e40\u0e17\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e1b\u0e35 2559|trans-title=The Lao Phao Buri activities in 2016|accessdate=28 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129155750/http://www.psl.ac.th/wpweb/?p=1239|archivedate=29 November 2016}}</ref> The temple's campaign became more widely known when in 2005 the beverage company [[Thai Beverages|Thai Beverage]] announced its intention to list in the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]], which would be the biggest listing in Thai history.<ref name=\"Hills 2005\">{{cite news|url=http://csr-asia.com/csr-asia-weekly-news-detail.php?id=3547|title=CSR and the alcohol industry: a case study from Thailand|date=5 April 2005|work=CSR Asia|last1=Hills|first1=Jonathan|accessdate=29 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129153130/http://csr-asia.com/csr-asia-weekly-news-detail.php?id=3547|archivedate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/224f3bd6-981d-11d9-912c-00000e2511c8.html|title=Buddhist monks protest against IPO plan|date=19 March 2005|work=[[The Financial Times]]|last1=Kazmin|first1=Amy|accessdate=29 November 2016|url-access=limited|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831120536/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/224f3bd6-981d-11d9-912c-00000e2511c8.html|archive-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> Despite attempts by the [[National Office of Buddhism]] (a government agency) to prohibit monks from protesting, two thousand monks of the temple organized a chanting of Buddhist texts in front of the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand|Stock Exchange]] to pressure them to decline Thai Beverage's [[initial public offering]].<ref name=\"Inbaraj 2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2005/03/thailand-beer-and-buddhism-a-definite-no-cry-conservatives/|title=Thailand: Beer and Buddhism, a Definite No, Cry Conservatives|date=20 March 2005|work=[[Inter Press Service]]|last1=Inbaraj|first1=Sonny|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Weekend 2005\" />{{refn|The temple used the project name \"Thai Buddhist Monks National Coordination Center\".<ref name=\"Weekend 2005\" />|group=note}} In an unprecedented cooperative effort, the temple was soon followed suit by former [[Black May (1992)|Black May]] revolt leader [[Chamlong Srimuang]] and the [[Santi Asoke]] movement. Subsequently, another 122 religious and social organizations joined, belonging to several religions and reaching numbers of 10,000 protesters. The organizations asked Prime Minister Thaksin to stop the company, in what some of the protest leaders described as \"a grave threat to the health and culture\" of Thai society.<ref name=\"Inbaraj 2005\" /><ref name=\"Weekend 2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationweekend.com/weekend/20050304/web01.shtml|date=4 March 2005|work=Nation Weekend|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e02\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e15\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e40\u0e21\u0e32 \u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e1b\u0e1c\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01 \u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e19\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e43\u0e04\u0e23?|trans-title=Resistance against alcohol: a hundred flowers bloom fully, and for who do a hundred institutions compete?|accessdate=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201235248/http://www.nationweekend.com/weekend/20050304/web01.shtml|archive-date=1 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Buddhists protest beer company's launch on stock exchange|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/bac9ced135a9b2a99d9d55e13bd91590|accessdate=9 July 2017|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=20 July 2005}}</ref> While the Stock Exchange pointed out the economical benefits of this first local listing, opponents referred to rising alcohol abuse in Thai society, ranking fifth in alcohol consumption according to the [[UN Food and Agriculture Organization]]. Ultimately, the protests led to an indefinite postponement of the listing by the Stock Exchange.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/4374889.stm|title=Protests 'halt' Thai beer listing|date=23 March 2005|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=52,1462,0,0,1,0#.WDzZmdUrK72|title=5,000 Buddhists protest against listing breweries on Thai exchange|date=20 July 2005|work=[[Today Online]]|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|via=The Buddhist Channel|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> Thai Beverage chose to list in Singapore instead, as the Stock Exchange chief resigned as a result.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/2ff6dd00-7d3e-11da-875c-0000779e2340|title=Thai brewer creates stir with Singapore plan|date=4 January 2006|work=[[The Financial Times]]|last1=Kazmin|first1=Amy|accessdate=29 November 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2006/05/25/thai-bourse-chief-quits-after-losing-ipo-to-rival/|title=Thai Bourse Chief Quits After Losing I.P.O. to a Rival|date=25 May 2006|work=[[Financial Times]]|via=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== International meditation and the tsunami memorials ===\n\nThe temple broadened its activities to a more national scope. The temple started its own satellite channel called [[Dhammakaya Media Channel]] (DMC),{{sfn|Heikkil\u00e4-Horn|2015|p=63}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=85}} and a university that supports [[distance learning]].<ref name=\"Forbes 2015\" /> The temple started to use this satellite channel to broadcast live events to branch centers, such as guided meditations.{{sfn|Snodgrass|2003}} Wat Phra Dhammakaya started to develop a more international approach to its teachings, teaching meditation in not-Buddhist countries as a religiously neutral technique suitable for those of all faiths, or none.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=48, 63, 71}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=242}} An international ''Dhammadayada'' program was also started, held in Chinese and English, and the temple started to organize retreats in English language in Thailand and abroad. Later on, guided meditations were also held online, in different languages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2005/08/03/fea10.htm|title=In Thailand, British monk brings Buddhism to Westerners|date=3 August 2005|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|publisher=Lake House|last1=Mathes|first1=Michael|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=11 July 2016|title=Thai Meditation Lineages Abroad: Creating Networks of Exchange|journal=Contemporary Buddhism|volume=17|issue=2|pages=2\u20135|doi=10.1080/14639947.2016.1205767|last1=Schedneck|first1=Brooke}}</ref><ref name=\"Schedneck 2015\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=o5lhCQAAQBAJ|title=Thailand's International Meditation Centers: Tourism and the Global Commodification of Religious Practices|date=15 May 2015|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-317-44938-6|chapter=The Field of international Engagement with Thai Meditation Centers|last1=Schedneck|first1=Brooke}}</ref> The temple was the first new religious organization in Thailand to effectively use Internet technology in disseminating their teachings.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Taylor|first=Jim|year=2003|title=New Buddhism, urban space, and virtual civil society|encyclopedia=International readings on theory, history and philosophy of culture|url=http://www.spbric.org/PDF/ttr15.pdf|volume=15|publisher=Eidos|editor-first=Liubava|editor-last=Moreva|page=239}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Wat Phra Dhammakaya made headlines when it offered aid to victims of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 tsunami disaster]] in Thailand, through charity and by organizing inter-faith memorial services for the victims in [[Phang Nga Province|Phang Nga]] and [[Phuket Province|Phuket]].{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=391}}{{sfn|Seeger|2006|p=7}} The temple acted as an intermediary in the coordination between the government and NGOs.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|pp=148\u20139}}\n\nThe Path of Progress contest started to expand (as of 2006, 19,839 schools, according to the temple{{sfn|Thammachay\u014d|Thattach\u012bw\u014d|Tawandhamma Foundation|2007|pp=94\u2013103}}) and a number of schools in other countries started to compete in their knowledge of Buddhist ethics as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/11/25/news60.asp|title=Quick Look\u2013Examination on World Peace|date=25 November 2009|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|publisher=Lake House|accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Novices meditating.jpg|alt=Novices meditating|thumb|As of 2006, the community living at Wat Phra Dhammakaya numbered more than a thousand monks and ''samaneras''.<ref name=\"Taylor 2008\" />{{sfn|Zehner|2013|p=191}}]]\n\n=== Charges withdrawn ===\n\nIn 2006, the running lawsuits ended when the {{ill|Attorney-General of Thailand|th|\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e22\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14 (\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22)}} withdrew the charges against Luang Por Dhammajayo. He stated that Luang Por Dhammajayo had moved all the land to the name of the temple, that he had corrected his teachings according to the Tipitaka, and that continuing the case might create division in society,{{Refn|In 2006, there were rising political conflicts.<ref name=\"Voice 2016\" />|group=note}} and would not be conducive to public benefit. Furthermore, Luang Por Dhammajayo had assisted the Sangha, the government and the private sector significantly in organizing religious activities. Luang Por Dhammajayo's position as an abbot was subsequently restored.<ref name=\"Naew Na 2006\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=23 August 2006|work=Naew Na|page=1|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e22\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e04\u0e37\u0e19\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e22\u0e31\u0e01\u0e22\u0e2d\u0e01 950 \u0e25.|trans-title=Prosecutor withdraws charges Dhammajayo, Dhammajayo agrees to return embezzled 950 M.|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=52,3073,0,0,1,0#.VyYxl_l9670|title=Thai court spares founder of Dhammakaya|date=23 August 2006|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|via=The Buddhist Channel|accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> Critics questioned whether the charges were withdrawn because of the political influence of Prime Minister Thaksin.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 160616\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a266s83xt-c|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|script-title=th:\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e32\u0e04\u0e15\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e2d\u0e19\u0e32\u0e04\u0e15\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e1b\u0e44\u0e15\u0e22|trans-title=The future of Dhammakaya, the future of democracy|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Dubus 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-06-22-derriere-la-controverse-autour-du-temple-bouddhique-dhammakaya-un-bras-de-fer-religieux-et-politique|title=Controverse autour du temple bouddhique Dhammakaya: un bras de fer religieux et politique|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=22 June 2016|work=\u00c9glises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=Controversy regarding the Dhammakaya Buddhist temple: A religious and political standoff|access-date=16 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123040416/http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-06-22-derriere-la-controverse-autour-du-temple-bouddhique-dhammakaya-un-bras-de-fer-religieux-et-politique|archive-date=23 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhen PM Thaksin was in power, the temple was often accused of having close ties to him, influencing his policies.{{sfn|Swearer|2010|p=141}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=155\u20136}} The temple has denied this, saying that all political parties are welcome in the temple.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36545637|title=Thailand: Devotees block arrest of Dhammakaya temple abbot|date=16 June 2016|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> In 2006, before the charges were withdrawn, Wat Phra Dhammakaya hosted a meeting of 78,540 local administrators, led by PM Thaksin, themed ''Every religion working together for local development''. The meeting was held as a form of [[inter-faith dialogue]] between Buddhists, Christians and Muslims, in which speakers of each religion explained their views on local economical and social development.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=136}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e02\u0e22\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e15\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e23\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07 \u0e21\u0e17.\u0e42\u0e15\u0e49\u0e40\u0e01\u0e13\u0e11\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e19|date=11 July 2006|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=14|language=th|trans-title=Army spreads warning message through cars, Ministry Internal Affairs replies to {{bracket|accusations of}} political lobbying|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=7 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=19 July 2006|work=Bangkok Biz News|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=8|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e34\u0e13\u0e22\u0e36\u0e14\u0e40\u0e27\u0e17\u0e35\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e14\u0e01\u0e25\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21\u0e15\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e15\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19|trans-title=Thaksin takes over the Dhammakaya stage to speak out against resistance groups|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=7 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Critics argued this was a political rally, but the government and the temple stated that the temple simply offered a venue which was hard to find elsewhere, and the temple did not take part in the actual event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=12 July 2006|work=Matichon|page=11|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e22\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 \u0e41\u0e1c\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a-\u0e23\u0e38\u0e01 \u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e18\u0e21\u0e34\u0e15\u0e23|trans-title=Thai Rak Thai's strategies revealed: attack and defense against PAD|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=7 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Temple gathering not political, govt. says|date=18 July 2006|work=[[The Nation]]|page=4|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=7 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the temple did have similar methods as Thaksin to build a mass support base, and raise funds, the political connection with the Red Shirts was not so self-evident.<ref name=\"BBC 2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39263793|title=The curious case of a hidden abbot and a besieged temple|last=Head|first=Jonathan|date=22 March 2017|work=[[BBC]]|location=Bangkok|accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref> Some major supporters of the temple were publicly known as members of the [[People's Alliance for Democracy|Yellow Shirts]] political pressure group, which was strongly opposed to PM Thaksin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news/182603|date=21 June 2016|work=Matichon|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e13\u0e35\u0e15 \u0e2d\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e27 \u0e17\u0e33\u0e44\u0e21 \u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e1a\u0e0d\u0e08\u0e23\u0e07\u0e04\u0e01\u0e38\u0e25 \u0e1a\u0e32\u0e17\u0e01\u0e49\u0e32\u0e27 \u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Refined and fast: Why does Boonchai Benjarongkul step in for Dhammakaya?|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Yee 161116\" /><ref name=\"Pravit 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2016/06/12/yellow-red-seen-orange-folds-dhammakaya-scandal/|title=Yellow & Red Seen in Orange Folds of Dhammakaya Scandal|date=12 June 2016|work=[[Khaosod]]|last1=Rojanaphruk|first1=Pravit|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> At least one Red Shirt leader has later come out to state that there is no link between Wat Phra Dhammakaya and the Red Shirt pressure group.<ref name=\"Reuters 170224\" /> Anthropologist Jim Taylor believes the temple's involvement in political agendas was most intensive in the early period, but after that had become less, and in 2017 described the temple as \"stoically politically neutral, aloof\".<ref name=\"BBC 2017\" /><ref name=\"Mandala 2017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newmandala.org/perplexing-case-wat-dhammakaya/|title=The perplexing case of Wat Dhammakaya|last=Taylor|first=Jim|date=6 March 2017|work=New Mandala|access-date=9 March 2017}}</ref> A [[Prachatai]] columnist argued that there may be some relation between Dhammakaya, Thaksin and [[Pheu Thai Party|his party]], but to equate Thaksin with Dhammakaya and Somdet Chuang, or to equate devotees of Dhammakaya with Red Shirts, would be going too far.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bai Tong Haeng|script-title=th:\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e19\u0e30\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e43\u0e15\u0e49 \u0e21.44|trans-title=Religious disaster under Section 44|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2017/02/70320|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=28 February 2017|language=th}}</ref> As for the temple's spokespeople, in a widely cited survey of political opinion among Thai monastics, the temple stated they did not choose any political side. They did disagree with the coup d'\u00e9tat as a political solution as opposed to a peaceful solution.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thaweesak|first1=Surapot|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e1a\u0e37\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e27\u0e34\u0e08\u0e31\u0e22\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e1d\u0e48\u0e32\u0e22 '\u0e41\u0e14\u0e07-\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07-\u0e01\u0e25\u0e32\u0e07'|trans-title=A closer look at study about role Sangha in selecting Yellow, Red or neutral side|url=https://prachatai.com/node/33210/talk|accessdate=31 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=20 February 2011|language=th}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, the community living at Wat Phra Dhammakaya numbered over a thousand monks and ''samaneras'', and hundreds of laypeople. The temple also had two thousand volunteers for help in ceremonies.{{sfn|Seeger|2006|p=1}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Adjustments needed to end religious controversy|date=30 January 1999|work=[[The Nation]]|publisher=The Nation Group|page=A1|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Osthanon|first1=Prapasri|url-access=subscription|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> Although, like most Thai temples, the temple had no formal sense of membership,<ref name=\"Taylor 2008\" />{{sfn|Zehner|2013|p=191}} congregations on Sundays and major religious holidays, such as ''[[Kathina]]'' or ''Magha Puja'', were estimated at over a hundred thousand people.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=52}}{{sfn|Heikkil\u00e4-Horn|2015|p=63}}{{sfn|Seeger|2006|p=1}} Worldwide, the temple's following was estimated at one million practitioners.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=9}}\n\n== Wider public engagement (2007\u20132013) ==\n\n=== Educational and scholarly programs ===\nIn April 2007, while a government-appointed council was working on drafting a new constitution, a march of two thousand monks and lay people was held to press the council to include in the new constitution that Buddhism become the [[state religion]] of Thailand. Wat Phra Dhammakaya supported the march. Prime Minister [[Surayud Chulanont]] stated, however, that such a clause was not feasible, as it would lead to rejection of the draft.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=26 April 2007|work=Bangkok Biz News|access-date=8 December 2016|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=15|script-title=th:\u0e21\u0e47\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e20\u0e32\u0e04\u0e43\u0e15\u0e49\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e1c\u0e48\u0e32\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Protest of southern monks organized by Wat Phra Dhammakaya|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Religion protests worry Surayud|last=Srivalo|first=Piyanart|date=26 April 2007|work=[[The Nation]]|access-date=8 December 2016|last2=Butrsripoom|first2=Atthayuth|pages=1A, 4A|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e21\u0e47\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e21\u0e19\u0e38\u0e21\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e48 \u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a \u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e23\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e38\u0e19|trans-title=Large gathering of Buddhists, {{bracket|organizer}} admits that Dhammakaya helps support|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2007/04/12493|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=26 April 2007|language=th}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2008 onward, the temple extended its youth activities to include a training course in Buddhist practice known as {{dfn|''V-star''}}, and a yearly national day of Buddhist activities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-21016612|title='One million children' join Buddhist meditation event|date=15 January 2013|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|last1=Bansong|first1=Aggarat|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In the V-star course, children were encouraged to observe ten daily practices, among which paying respect to their parents, and chanting Buddhist texts before sleeping.<ref name=\"Channel 8 2015\" /> Students were also encouraged to lead Kathina ceremonies in local temples.{{Refn|There had been a problem with temples not being able to organize Kathina ceremonies due to lack of supporters or funds.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e10\u0e34\u0e19\u0e22\u0e38\u0e04\u0e17\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e34\u0e13\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e01\u0e23\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e22 \u0e28\u0e23\u0e31\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32\u0e2b\u0e14 \u0e40\u0e28\u0e23\u0e29\u0e10\u0e01\u0e34\u0e08\u0e1f\u0e38\u0e1a|trans-title=A quiet Kathina in the Thaksin period: faith and economy are breaking down|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|accessdate=5 December 2016|work=Dokbia Thurakit|date=10 November 2003|page=11|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription|language=th}}</ref>|group=note}} The point of these practices was to create good habits, fostered through a cooperation between parents, teachers and monks ({{lang-th|\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14 \u0e42\u0e23\u0e07\u0e40\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e19}}, shortened as \u0e1a\u0e27\u0e23). On a yearly V-star day the children normally meditated and chanted, but also listened to Buddhist teachings, watched an exhibition and solved problems about those teachings. They confirmed their Buddhist faith through a [[Up\u0101saka and Up\u0101sik\u0101#Theravada traditions|refuge ceremony]]. The day closed by watching a 3D movie with a Buddhist theme. {{As of|2014}}, five thousand schools joined the program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=20 December 2014|work=Matichon|page=5|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e23\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e01\u0e25\u0e2f \u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e23\u0e27\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e01\u0e14\u0e35\u0e27\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e04\u0e15\u0e32\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 9|trans-title=International Buddhist Society organizes a 9th V-star Day for good children to join hands|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=135}}\n\nTogether these programs were called the 'World Morality Revival' ({{lang-th|\u0e1f\u0e37\u0e49\u0e19\u0e1d\u0e39\u0e48\u0e28\u0e34\u0e25\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01}}) project, using the slogan \"knowledge combined with virtue\". The project became noticeable quite soon, when former PM Thaksin Shinawatra and Deputy PM [[Somchai Wongsawat]] were guest speakers on the 2008 V-Star Day.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=135}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=2123|date=26 May 2008|work=Matichon|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e40\u0e1a\u0e37\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07 \u0e19\u0e23.2 \u0e41\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e41\u0e2b\u0e48\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a|trans-title=Behind the 200,000 schools lining up to receive {{bracket|funds}}|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220033317/http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=2123|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=23 May 2008|work=Matichon|page=13|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e34\u0e13\u0e42\u0e1c\u0e25\u0e48\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e19.\u0e23.\u0e19\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e16\u0e39\u0e01\u0e14\u0e36\u0e07\u0e23\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e33\u0e1d\u0e19\u0e23\u0e2d|trans-title=Thaksin appears at event Wat Phra Dhammakaya, hundred thousand students waiting, exposed to rain|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> To promote these programs further, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started cooperating extensively with the Ministry of Education, the temple's education department signing an MoU ([[Memorandum Of Understanding]]) with the [[Office of the Basic Education Commission]] (OBEC) in 2010. Shortly after signing the {{abbr|MoU|Memorandum of Understanding}}, however, the Minister of Education asked a commission to review the programs mentioned in it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/82367|date=11 May 2010|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e23\u0e48\u0e07\u0e15\u0e23\u0e27\u0e08\u0e2a\u0e2d\u0e1a \u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Pressing investigations into the case of Dhammakaya|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/local/37120/chinnaworn-halts-moral-conduct-plan|title=Chinnaworn halts moral conduct plan|date=11 May 2010|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|accessdate=16 June 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref> The ministry was criticized by a network of scholars, led by Sulak Sivaraksa, for being too personally involved with the temple. The contents of the proposed programs were also questioned. The minister issued a press release, stating the involvement was merely professional, but he would be careful as the project would become more concrete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1273678198|date=12 May 2010|language=th|script-title=th:\"\u0e21\u0e32\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e04\"\u0e08\u0e35\u0e49\u0e28\u0e18.\u0e40\u0e23\u0e48\u0e07\u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e47\u0e21\u0e42\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e39\"\u0e2a\u0e1e\u0e10.-\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\" \u0e40\u0e25\u0e02\u0e32\u0e2f\u0e01\u0e1e\u0e10.\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e14\u0e43\u0e0a\u0e49\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e18\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e1b\u0e39\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07|trans-title=Minister of Education urges his ministry to explain the MoU between OBEC and Dhammakaya, secr. OBEC denies personal involvement having been start|work=Matichon}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=PM urged to halt huge temple plan|date=10 May 2010|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|page=16|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> As the plans evolved, it became clear the temple wanted to offer training programs to millions of youth through the entire country. Essential to the project was the idea that teachers would work more together to promote good morals in education. Criticism did not stop, however, and the program was brought to a halt, only to be revived by [[Yingluck cabinet|Yingluck Shinawatra's government]]. Three nationwide training programs were held in the period of 2010 to 2013. Programs involved meditation, Buddhist teaching and keeping eight precepts. The {{abbr|OBEC|Office of the Basic Education Commission}} often defended the project, saying that nationwide many temples were involved in the project, not just Wat Phra Dhammakaya, as well as many organizations promoting Buddhist education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=9 September 2013|work=Lok Wannee|pages=2\u20133|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e33\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e17\u0e33\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e1b|trans-title=Merit or demerit?|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Kritthaphat|accessdate=24 November 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Pariyattithum School.jpg|thumb|The Pariyattithum School at [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]], where [[Pali]] language and [[Buddhist studies|Buddhist Studies]] are taught.]]\nAlso, in this period, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started to invest more resources in its own education and scholarship. In 2009, Wat Phra Dhammakaya had the highest number of [[Pali]] (language of the Theravada Buddhist canon) graduates in the central area of Thailand. The temple was continuously ranked as one of the five highest in the country in Pali studies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/17276|date=4 July 2009|work=Thai Rath|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\"\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e42\u0e21\u0e25\u0e35-\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22-\u0e15\u0e32\u0e01\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32-\u0e42\u0e2a\u0e18\u0e23\" \u0e04\u0e27\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e14\u0e35\u0e40\u0e14\u0e48\u0e19|trans-title=Wat Moli, Dhammakaya, Tak Fa and Sothorn obtain awards for excellent Pali|accessdate=22 November 2016|author=Education News Team|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201312/http://www.thairath.co.th/content/17276|archivedate=23 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/69087|date=6 March 2010|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:43 \u0e2b\u0e31\u0e27\u0e01\u0e30\u0e17\u0e34\u0e20\u0e34\u0e01\u0e29\u0e38-\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e21\u0e40\u0e13\u0e23 \u0e1c\u0e48\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e42\u0e22\u0e04 9 \u0e1b\u0e35 53|trans-title=43 top monks and novices obtain a ninth-level degree in 2010}}</ref> In 2010, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started the ''Dhammachai Tipitaka Project'', providing facilities for scholars worldwide to work together collecting ancient manuscripts, mostly from Myanmar, Sri Lanka and Thailand, to make a [[critical edition]] of the Pali Canon, the Theravada Buddhist scriptures. This edition was to provide the technology and comparative data for scholars to come to a reconstruction of the Tipitaka texts as they were known in the fifth century CE, when they were first written down. There were over a hundred staff members working on the project worldwide, divided in manuscript reading teams. The work was reviewed by an international advisory board of scholars, including [[Rupert Gethin]], [[Richard Gombrich]] and [[Oskar von Hin\u00fcber]]. A digital version of the Tipitaka was expected to be completed by 2028, but the first part was published in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ocbs.org/the-ur-text-of-the-pali-tipi%E1%B9%ADaka-some-reflections-based-on-new-research-into-the-manuscript-tradition/|title=The ur-text of the Pali Tipi\u1e6daka: Some reflections based on new research into the manuscript tradition|publisher=[[Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies]]|last1=Wynne|first1=Alexander|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocbs.org/news-ocbsmain-88/270-ocbs-news-march-2013?start=2|title=OCBS News March 2013 \u2013 Tipitaka|date=6 September 2015|website=[[Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies]]|location=Oxford|last1=Gombrich|first1=Richard|author-link=Richard Gombrich|accessdate=19 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906033244/http://www.ocbs.org/news-ocbsmain-88/270-ocbs-news-march-2013?start=2|archivedate=6 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wynne|first=Alexander|year=2013|title=A Preliminary Report on the Critical Edition of the P\u0101li Canon being prepared at Wat Phra Dhammak\u0101ya|journal=Thai International Journal of Buddhist Studies|volume=IV|pages=167, 142\u20133|issn=2286-8348}}</ref> The project backfired, however, when Matichon and other Thai newspapers interpreted the project as an actual {{em|correcting}} or 'purification of the Tipitaka' ({{lang-th|\u0e0a\u0e33\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e44\u0e15\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e0e\u0e01}}), as this was done in the historical [[Buddhist Councils]]. Wat Phra Dhammakaya denied this in a press statement, however. They said it was not their intention to rewrite the Pali Canon, and considered it unlikely that in the present day anyone could do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/158282|date=24 March 2011|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e42\u0e21\u0e25\u0e35 \u0e25\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e32\u0e21\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e17\u0e33\u0e44\u0e15\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e0e\u0e01\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e19|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1300796317|date=23 March 2011|work=Matichon|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e21\u0e21\u0e23.\u0e41\u0e09\"\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\"\u0e40\u0e23\u0e48\u0e07\u0e0a\u0e33\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e44\u0e15\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e0e\u0e01 \u0e41\u0e01\u0e49 \u2032\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e31\u0e15\u0e15\u0e32\u2032\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u2032\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e15\u0e15\u0e32\u2032 \u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e17\u0e33\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Mahamakut Buddhist University exposes Wat Phra Dhammakaya quickly reviewing the Tipitaka, replacing 'anatta' with 'atta', shaking up and destroying Buddhism|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> Wat Phra Dhammakaya set up another research institute, located in Australia, called DIRI (Dhammachai International Research Institute). This institute promoted research on manuscripts of [[early Buddhism]], and offered fellowships to that end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asian.washington.edu/news/2014/08/01/72nd-dhammachai-fellowship-announcement|title=72nd Dhammachai Fellowship Announcement|date=1 August 2014|website=Asian Languages & Literature|publisher=[[University of Washington]]|last1=Dye|first1=Curtis A.|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ocbs.org/ocbs-news-june-2015/|title=OCBS News|date=1 June 2015|publisher=[[Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:City pilgrimage organized by Wat Phra Dhammakaya.jpg|alt=City pilgrimage organized by Wat Phra Dhammakaya|thumb|In 2011, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started to organize [[pilgrimages]] passing important places in the life of [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro]].]]\n\n=== Teaching in the city ===\nThe temple also started to organize huge [[Alms#Buddhism|alms giving]] events around the country, including at important sites in Bangkok, some of which were joined by thousands of monks. The alms giving events were held to help bring monks and lay people together, to revive the custom of alms giving, and as a dedication of merit to the victims of the [[Insurgency in South Thailand|insurgency in the Southern provinces]].<ref name=\"Channel 8 2015\" />{{sfn|Kom Chad Luek, 24 February 2010|p=32}}<ref name=\"Banmuang 2014\" /> The profits from the alms giving events were used to support the temples and teachers in the South with aid and supplies.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=148}}<ref name=\"Banmuang 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=1 January 2014|work=Banmuang|page=13|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e16\u0e27\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e06\u0e17\u0e32\u0e19 323 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14 \u0e21\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e38\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e22\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e23\u0e39\u0e43\u0e15\u0e49|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya offers funds to aid teachers and 323 temples in South|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The events were the first mass gatherings which the [[Junta (governing body)|junta]] had allowed since the [[2006 coup d'etat in Thailand|2006 coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\"Henton 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/inpictures/2014/11/pictures-10000-marching-monks-20141124101848464934.html|title=In Pictures: 10,000 marching monks in Bangkok|date=26 November 2014|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|last1=Henton|first1=George|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In 2012, the alms events became more prominent when then Prime Minister [[Yingluck Shinawatra]] joined an event in person, as well as comedian [[Udom Taepanich]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1332058169|date=18 March 2012|work=Matichon|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e20\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e14 \"\u0e22\u0e34\u0e48\u0e07\u0e25\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e13\u0e4c WHOLESALE -\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\" \u0e17\u0e33\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d\u0e15\u0e31\u0e01\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e23\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c 22,600 \u0e23\u0e39\u0e1b \u0e09\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e0a\u0e22\u0e31\u0e19\u0e15\u0e35 2,600 \u0e1b\u0e35|trans-title=Let's look at Yingluck giving alms to a Sangha of 22,600 monks, celebrating Buddhajayanti 2,600 years, this is wholesale for Dhammakaya|accessdate=2 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203060806/http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1332058169|archivedate=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/34040.html|date=18 March 2012|work=VoiceTV|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e2f \u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e32\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e01\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e23\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c 22,600 \u0e23\u0e39\u0e1b|trans-title=PM is chairman in alms giving to 22,600 monks|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1333727835|date=6 April 2012|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e17\u0e33\u0e08\u0e23\u0e32\u0e08\u0e23\u0e15\u0e34\u0e14\u0e02\u0e31\u0e14 \u0e40\u0e1c\u0e22 \"\u0e42\u0e19\u0e49\u0e2a\" \u0e1c\u0e39\u0e01\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e32\u0e27\u0e19\u0e32\u0e19\u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32 10 \u0e1b\u0e35|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya makes statement about ''Dhutanga'' and traffic jams, reveals that Udom is fond of temple for over 10 years|via=Matichon|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220032311/http://www.matichon.co.th/news_detail.php?newsid=1333727835|archivedate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[2011 Thailand floods|in Thailand's worst flooding for more than half-a-century]], a great deal of Bangkok and its outskirts were inundated, including Patumthani, the area where Wat Phra Dhammakaya is located.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Thailand-Floods-4/d70eeaba87425443ada42e9129905ff8|title=Thailand Floods 4|date=17 October 2011|work=[[The Associated Press]]|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> Working together with the government, the temple deployed monastic and lay volunteers to bring a halt to the floods in the area, who had to work day and night to build walls using sandbags and pump out the water.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/213896|title=|last=|first=|date=3 November 2011|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:7\u0e2d.\u0e1b\u0e17\u0e38\u0e21\u0e2f\u0e27\u0e34\u0e01\u0e24\u0e15\u0e34 \u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e07\u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e323\u0e21. '\u0e25\u0e33\u0e25\u0e39\u0e01\u0e01\u0e32'\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e44\u0e14\u0e49\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e22\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d|trans-title=Crisis in 7 municipalities in Patumthani: water higher than 3&nbsp;m, Lamlukka has not received help|via=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=|last=|first=|date=31 October 2011|work=Naew Na|page=17|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e34\u0e01\u0e24\u0e15\u0e34\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e17\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya and the flood crisis|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=2 December 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> At the same time, the temple offered shelter to evacuated workers from local factories,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/24/asia/gallery/floods-bangkok/index.html|title=Flooding threatens Bangkok|last=|first=|date=24 October 2011|work=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|at=Image 2|via=|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/277987/Bangkok-flood-barriers-hold-firm|title=Bangkok flood barriers hold firm|date=17 October 2011|work=[[Daily Express|Express]]|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> food, drinking water, transport and sandbags to local villagers, other affected temples and temples that also offered shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/217713|title=|last=|first=|date=19 November 2011|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e17\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e17\u0e38\u0e21\u0e18\u0e32\u0e19\u0e35\u0e40\u0e23\u0e48\u0e34\u0e21\u0e25\u0e14 \u0e04\u0e32\u0e14\u0e2d\u0e35\u0e012\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e1b\u0e14\u0e32\u0e2b\u0e4c\u0e08\u0e30\u0e01\u0e25\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e48\u0e1b\u0e01\u0e15\u0e34|trans-title=Flood levels in Pathumthani are falling, within 2 weeks back to normal|via=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Chaos reigns as strong torrents breach the dyke in Nava Nakorn|last=|first=|date=18 October 2011|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)|The Nation]]|page=14|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=2 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2009 onwards, Wat Phra Dhammakaya expanded its temporary ordination program by making it nationwide. In this program, the participants were trained in thousands of temples spread over Thailand, but ordained simultaneously at Wat Phra Dhammakaya. Held in cooperation with the [[House of Representatives (Thailand)|House of Representatives]], the concept of the program was to reverse the trend of the number of monks in Thailand decreasing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=|last=|first=|date=8 February 2012|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|page=15|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e30\u0e01\u0e34\u0e14\u0e08\u0e34\u0e15\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e19\u0e36\u0e01 \u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e38\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32|trans-title=Raising awareness: government supporting Buddhism|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=2 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The program was held twice a year, and the participants who decided to stay in the monkhood were encouraged to revive abandoned temples. In 2010, 10,685 monks joined the program.<ref name=\"Channel 8 2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nzWS-Nfi5S0|date=26 February 2015|work=[[Channel 8 (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e15\u0e25\u0e32\u0e14\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Dhammakaya's marketing|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Kom Chad Luek, 24 February 2010|p=31}} As part of the ordination programs, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started to organize pilgrimages passing important places in the life of Luang Pu Sodh.<ref name=\"Swatman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/charity/2015/11/buddhist-monks-complete-longest-journey-walking-on-flower-petals-across-thailand-404749|title=Buddhist monks complete longest journey walking on flower petals across Thailand|date=4 November 2015|website=Guinness World Records|last1=Swatman|first1=Rachel|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6x39ld6ZW?url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/charity/2015/11/buddhist-monks-complete-longest-journey-walking-on-flower-petals-across-thailand-404749|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This was done through a procession by over a thousand monks through the areas of Central Thailand that were flooded before, while life-size images of Luang Pu Sodh were ceremonially brought to install in pilgrimage places.<ref name=\"Forbes 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.forbesthailand.com/commentaries-detail.php?did=304|date=3 February 2015|work=[[Forbes]] Thailand|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e23\u0e39\u0e49\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01 \"\u0e40\u0e04\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e22\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\"|trans-title=Getting to know the Dhammakaya network|last1=Banchanon|first1=Phongphiphat|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Khao 3 Miti 2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0vkgc57yrNU|date=2 March 2015|work=[[Channel 3 (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22, \u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e19\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19|trans-title=The Dhammachai Dhutanga, Wat Phra Dhammakaya, and other news today|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> During the breaks between the walks, the monks spent their time meditating, chanting and making good wishes to those affected by the floods.<ref name=\":0\" />[[File:Signs at roadside inviting people to chant the Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta.jpg|alt=Signs in the shape of a wheel and a deer|left|thumb|284x284px|Signs at the roadside inviting people to recite the [[Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta]] at [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]].]]The pilgrimages were held with analogy to [[Vesali#Visits of the Buddha to Vai\u015b\u0101l\u012b|the traditional story of the Buddha ridding Vesali of illness and drought]]. On the way to Vesali, the Buddha's entire route had been decorated with flowers by [[King Bimbisara]]. As a re-enactment of this story, throughout the walks, laypeople spread self-picked flowers to pave a path for the monk-pilgrims.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/227577|date=2 January 2012|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e1e\u0e37\u0e49\u0e19\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 6 \u0e08\u0e27.\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e17\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21 \u0e1b\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e48\u0e32\u0e1c\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e20\u0e31\u0e22-\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e48\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e41\u0e1c\u0e48\u0e19\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19|trans-title=Dhammachai Dhutanga in the 6 flooded provinces: ridding the land of dangers, doing a great merit for the country|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref> Controversially, the temple used the word ''dhutanga'' for the walks, as it did before with its retreats. Responses were varied. On the one hand, the pilgrimage caused many people to participate with enthusiasm in the activities organized. For example, managers of some companies let the entire workforce take leave to join the flower-spreading.<ref name=\"Khao 3 Miti 2015\" /><ref name=\"Nukaew 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=|date=27 January 2014|work=Pim Thai|page=7|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e27\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e15\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e28\u0e23\u0e31\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49\u0e21\u0e41\u0e02\u0e47\u0e07|trans-title=City dwellers respond to the Dhammachai Dhutanga: inspiring faith to strengthen Buddhism|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Nukaew|first1=N.|accessdate=24 November 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Critics, however, said the ''dhutanga'' walks were causing traffic jams, and were not in accordance with traditional interpretations of ''dhutanga'' practice. The temple then defended the walks by stating that the monks joining actually took ''dhutanga'' vows, and by pointing out the spiritual benefits for the laypeople joining. A senator asked the National Office of Buddhism to investigate the matter further.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KD3oQ4K4bgM|date=4 February 2015|work=[[Channel 3 (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:2 \u0e21\u0e38\u0e21\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e07 \u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=2 perspectives on the Dhammachai Dhutanga|last1=Suthassanachinda|first1=Sorayuth|authorlink1=Sorayuth Suthassanachinda|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Monks march through city to welcome gold statue of Buddha|date=5 April 2012|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|page=15|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"Bangkok Post 2012\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Monks' city walk on right side of the Lord|date=5 April 2012|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|page=3|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Initially, the National Office of Buddhism approved of the city pilgrimage, saying that it agreed with Buddhist ideas and helped the economy.<ref name=\"Bangkok Post 2012\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/250451|date=3 April 2012|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e28.-\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e01\u0e25\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07 \u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e1c\u0e34\u0e14\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e01\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32|trans-title=ONB and Dhammakaya state that city ''dhutanga'' is not violating Buddhist principles|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, some news analysts speculated that the pilgrimages were meant to express loyalty to Somdet Chuang, the Supreme Patriarch to be. The appointment of the Supreme Patriarch was subject to rising disagreement, which fed the protesters' resentment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i4IOqafQp-w|date=24 December 2015|work=[[Spring News]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e23\u0e2b\u0e31\u0e2a\u0e02\u0e36\u0e49\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e49\u0e32\u0e22\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19 \"\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\" \u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e22\u0e32\u0e15\u0e23\u0e32|trans-title=Unraveling the riddle of the signs protesting Dhammakaya's Dhutanga Dhamma Journey|last1=Ekmahasawat|first1=Danai|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> Later, in 2015, the walk over spread flowers was approved as a [[Guinness world record]] in the category \"Longest journey walking on flower petals\".<ref name=\"Swatman\" /> Still in 2015 the National Office of Buddhism told Wat Phra Dhammakaya to stop organizing the pilgrimage walks in Bangkok, and only organize them outside of Bangkok, citing the problem of the traffic jams.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tnamcot.com/content/109000|date=31 December 2015|work=Thai News Agency|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e35\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e49\u0e32 \u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e43\u0e19\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e2f|trans-title=Next year, Dhammakaya not allowed to walk ''dhutanga'' in Bangkok|last1=Society News Department|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> At the end of the year, when the criticism did not tone down, Wat Phra Dhammakaya announced they would postpone organizing the pilgrimages indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lvKuzpGE5UQ|date=1 January 2016|work=[[Nation TV (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e22\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Retracing the Dhammachai Dhutanga|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> Religious Studies scholar Surapot Thaweesak argues that the debate about the pilgrimages is really a discussion about whether a religious organization can use [[public space]] and to what extent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thaweesak|first1=Surapot|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e35\u0e20\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e01\u0e25\u0e31\u0e49\u0e19 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Liberty and tolerance: the case of the Dhammakaya Dhutanga|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2015/02/57720|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=3 February 2015|language=th}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, during the [[Red Shirts (Thailand)|Red Shirt]] protests, in an attempt to keep control of any initiatives opposing the junta, a number of monastic and academic organizations and people, including Luang Por Dhammajayo, were put on a surveillance list by the Thai military. [[Duncan McCargo]] speculates that this information may have been deliberately leaked to the press as a form of threat to these organizations and people.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2014-11-11-pour-approfondir-bouddhisme-et-politique-en-thailande/|title=Pour approfondir-Bouddhisme et politique en Tha\u00eflande|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=11 November 2014|work=\u00c9glises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=In depth-Buddhism and politics in Thailand}}</ref>{{sfn|McCargo|2012|pp=631\u20132, 641}} Wat Phra Dhammakaya did not openly join any Red Shirt activities, but some leading members of pro-Thaksin parties were connected to the temple.{{sfn|McCargo|2012|p=641}}\n\nIn 2012, the temple broadcast a talk of Luang Por Dhammajayo about what happened to [[Steve Jobs]] after his death.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiasentinel.com/society/the-crisis-in-thai-buddhism/|title=The Crisis in Thai Buddhism|date=1 February 2013|work=[[Asia Sentinel]]|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> The talk came as a response to a software engineer of [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] who had sent a letter with questions to the abbot. Luang Por Dhammajayo described what Steve Jobs looked like in heaven.<ref name=\"Sify 2012\" /><ref name=\"TNA 2016\" /> He said that Jobs had been reborn as a ''[[Deva (Buddhism)|deva]]'' living close to his former offices, as a result of the [[Karma (Buddhism)|karma]] of having given knowledge to people.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/284972|date=20 July 2012|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e09\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01\u0e2d\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e44\u0e25\u0e19\u0e4c \u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e22'\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e35\u0e1f \u0e08\u0e47\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e4c'\u0e15\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e25\u0e49\u0e27\u0e44\u0e1b\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19|trans-title=Circulating through the online world: Dhammakaya reveals where Steve Jobs went after his death|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=27 August 2012|work=Lok Wannee|page=2|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e21 \u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d \u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e28\u0e23\u0e31\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32|trans-title=Society, beliefs and faith|via=Matichon E-library|last1=Chantarasiri|first1=Ruangyot|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The talk was much criticized, and the abbot was accused of pretending to have attained an advanced meditative state and of attempting to outshine other temples. The temple stated that the talk was meant to illustrate the law of karma, not to defame Jobs, nor to fake an advanced state.<ref name=\"Sify 2012\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sify.com/news/steve-jobs-now-an-angel-living-in-parallel-universe-news-international-miyk4jggedasi.html|title=Steve Jobs now an angel living in parallel universe|date=24 August 2012|work=[[Sify]]|agency=[[Asian News International]]|location=New Delhi|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TNA 2016\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indonesiarealtime/2012/08/31/thai-group-says-steve-jobs-reincarnated-as-warrior-philosopher/|title=Thai Group Says Steve Jobs Reincarnated as Warrior-Philosopher|date=31 August 2012|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|agency=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|last1=Hookway|first1=James|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2010}}, Wat Phra Dhammakaya was the fastest growing temple of Thailand.{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010|p=886}}{{sfn|Swearer|2010|p=138}} {{As of|2015}}, the temple had twenty-eight centers in Thailand, and eighty centers outside of Thailand,<ref name=\"Forbes 2015\" /> in all continents, except for South-America.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=145}} The ceremonies of the temple were often led by monks from the Supreme Sangha Council or other leading monks,<ref name=\"Prachachat 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 April 2014|work=Prachachat Thurakit|page=11|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c 30,000 \u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e17\u0e31\u0e48\u0e27\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e23\u0e34\u0e0d\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e4c|trans-title=30,000 temples nationwide chant Buddhist texts|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=24 April 2013|work=Pim Thai|page=7|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e2f \u0e23\u0e48\u0e27\u0e21\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e30\u0e04\u0e38\u0e49\u0e21\u0e04\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01|trans-title=Two high-standing monks joined the Dhamma Earth Day|via=Matichon E-library|accessdate=3 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and joined by high-ranking people from Thailand and other Buddhist countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/02/13/sec04.asp|title=LTTE preventing civilians leaving war zone, Prime Minister tells Thai counterpart|date=13 February 2009|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|publisher=Lake House|last1=de Silva|first1=Neville|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref> For major festivals, the number of practitioners reached 300,000 people.{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010|p=886}}\n\n== Standoff with junta (2014\u2013present) ==\n\n=== ''Junta''<nowiki />'s reform council versus Sangha Council ===\n\nAfter the [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|2014 coup d'\u00e9tat]], several initiatives were started to bring change to Thai society, which the junta stated was necessary before elections could be held. Among these measures, a National Reform Council was founded and the religious committee of this council was led by {{ill|Paiboon Nititawan|th|\u0e44\u0e1e\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c \u0e19\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e15\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19}}, a former senator who had played a crucial role in the coup. Backed by the bureaucracy, military and Royal Palace, Paiboon sought to deal with any shortcomings in the leading Thai Sangha through judicial means. He was joined by then monk {{ill|Phra Suwit Dhiradhammo|th|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e4c \u0e18\u0e35\u0e23\u0e18\u0e21\u0e3a\u0e42\u0e21}} (known under the activist name Phra Buddha Issara), a former infantryman who had assumed a main role in the coup as well. Finally, [[Mano Laohavanich]], a former monk of Wat Phra Dhammakaya, also a member of the reform council, joined the investigations.<ref name=\"Dubus 2016\" /><ref name=\"TNA 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tnamcot.com/content/482809|date=3 June 2016|work=Thai News Agency|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e08\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e21\u0e20\u0e31\u0e22\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32|trans-title=Dhammakaya responds to issues that threaten {{bracket|Buddhist}} religion|accessdate=15 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318153419/http://www.tnamcot.com/content/482809|archivedate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/tense-times-for-thai-junta-buddhist-clergy|title=Tense times for Thai junta, Buddhist clergy|date=25 February 2016|work=[[The Straits Times]]|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|author=Tan Hui Yee|accessdate=16 November 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nTo start with, Phra Suwit requested the [[Department of Special Investigation]] (DSI), a department modeled on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]],<ref name=\"Wechsler 2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Law enforcement agency tries to shake off shackles|last=Wechsler|first=Maxmilian|date=10 May 2009|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|page=6|via=Matichon e-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> to start an investigation in the assets of the Sangha Council's members. This included Somdet Chuang Varapu\u00f1\u00f1o, who was Luang Por Dhammajayo's preceptor (the person who ordained him), who had been nominated by the council to become the next [[Supreme Patriarch of Thailand|Supreme Patriarch]] per 5 January 2016. Phra Suwit objected to this nomination, and successfully held a petition to stop it.<ref name=\"Dubus 2016\" /><ref name=\"Dubus 20160118\">{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-01-18-la-thailande-se-dechire-a-propos-de-la-nomination-du-chef-des-bouddhistes/|title=La Tha\u00eflande se d\u00e9chire \u00e0 propos de la nomination du chef des bouddhistes|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=18 January 2016|work=\u00c9glises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=Thailand is torn about the appointment of a Buddhist leader|access-date=16 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123040131/http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-01-18-la-thailande-se-dechire-a-propos-de-la-nomination-du-chef-des-bouddhistes/|archive-date=23 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the meantime, in February 2015, Paiboon Nititawan tried to reopen the 1999 case of Luang Por Dhammajayo's alleged embezzlement of land.<ref name=\"Dubus 2016\" /><ref name=\"Piyanuch 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/thai-abbot-be-probed-over-massive-donations|title=Thai abbot to be probed over massive donations|last=Thamnukasetchai|first=Piyanuch|date=28 February 2015|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|agency=[[Asia News Network]]|via=Asia One}}</ref> Somdet Chuang and the rest of the Sangha Council were also involved in this, as they were accused of being negligent in not defrocking Luang Por Dhammajayo.<ref name=\"Dubus 20160118\" /> First, the Sangha Council reconsidered the embezzlement and fraud charges, but concluded that Luang Por Dhammajayo had not intended to commit fraud or embezzlement, and had already returned the land concerned;{{Refn|In the same period, Narong Nuchuea, a leading journalist on religious affairs, came out to state that the statement of the Supreme Patriarch was fake, because \"politics got involved\". He said that the then Supreme Patriarch would never leak such a letter to the press. Several Thai journalists and scholars have stated that the letter was suspicious for several reasons, including its layout, and the timing it was issued, and was therefore never taken in consideration by the Sangha Council.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 150723\">{{cite news| first=Jirachata|last=Iamrasmi|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/moBgUU|work=[[Thai PBS]]|date=23 July 2015|title=\u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c \"\u0e04\u0e33\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\u0e34\u0e08\u0e09\u0e31\u0e22\" \u0e1b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e01 \"\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\"|language=th|trans-title=Clearing up the analysis of an offense leading to disrobing|number=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Jomquan|last=Laopet|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e07(\u0e06\u0e4c)\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c?|trans-title=Is the Sangha in doubt about the Sangha?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hu0EdHf47eI|accessdate=23 February 2017|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|date=23 February 2015|time=18:37|language=th}}</ref> The Sangha Council itself stated that the Supreme Patriarch's letter was not an unconditional order: it said that Luang Por Dhammajayo should disrobe {{em|if}} (and only if) he did not return the land on his name to the temple.<ref name=\"Matichon 2015\">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|url-access=subscription|via=Matichon E-library|work=Matichon|date=23 February 2015|page=12|script-title=th:\u0e09\u0e38\u0e19\u0e21\u0e15\u0e34\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e40\u0e16\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e04\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e38\u0e49\u0e21\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e30\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e30\u0e22\u0e01\u0e02\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e36\u0e1a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e32\u0e01\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33|language=th|trans-title=Angered about decision SSC protecting Dhammakaya, Buddha Issara suddenly moves procession to Wat Paknam}}</ref>|group=note}} after that, Phra Suwit enlisted the help of the [[Ombudsman]], who asked the General-Attorney and the National Office of Buddhism to reconsider the criminal law case of embezzlement.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 150722\">{{cite news|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/JUTeqF|last=Chinmani|first=Vorawit|date=22 July 2015|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c \"\u0e04\u0e33\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\u0e34\u0e08\u0e09\u0e31\u0e22\" \u0e1b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e01|trans-title=Clearing up the analysis of an offense leading to disrobing|number=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/aec/30279019|title=Investigation of Phra Dhammachayo continues|date=11 February 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]}}</ref>{{Refn|The Ombudsman pointed out that the returning of land could not in itself be cause for withdrawing the charges: it would only make the charges less severe. Moreover, although recognizing that he had no jurisdiction with regard to ecclesiastical law, he did point out some inconsistencies which he believed indicated that the Sangha Council had not taken the letter of the Supreme Patriarch very seriously.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 150722\" />|group=note}}\n\n[[File:Alms giving to several thousand monks, next to Central World in Bangkok on the morning of Sunday 18th March 2012.png|left|thumb|The temple also started to organize huge [[Alms#Buddhism|alms giving]] events around the country, including at important sites in Bangkok.]]\n\nThese investigations did not go without response. In February 2016, on ''Magha Puja'', a protest was held by over a thousand Thai monks in the [[Phutthamonthon]] Park, as a response to this involvement by the [[National Council for Peace and Order|junta]].<ref name=\"Constant 2016\" /> The protest was organized by the Buddhist Protection Center of Thailand, a Red Shirt-oriented network.{{sfn|McCargo|2012|p=635}} The protesters demanded that the Thai junta not interfere with the Sangha's affairs, in particular the appointment of the next Supreme Patriarch.<ref name=\"Constant 2016\" /> After the junta responded by sending soldiers to control the site, the protest ended, but the monks announced they would repeat their protests if their demands were not met.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/thai-monks-protest/2516896.html|title=Thai monks protest against state interference in Buddhist governance|date=5 February 2016|work=[[Channel News Asia]]|agency=[[Mediacorp]]|last1=Wongcha-um|first1=Panu|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> Wat Phra Dhammakays's involvement was implied by the media. The temple denied organizing the protests, but did not disagree with them.<ref name=\"Constant 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/world/controversial-thai-temple-denies-involvement-in-politics/528142|title=Controversial Thai temple denies involvement in politics|date=27 February 2016|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|location=Bangkok|last1=Constant|first1=Max|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> At this point, the charges laid by Paiboon and Phra Suwit against the temple were by many interpreted as a way to discredit Somdet Chuang. Somdet Chuang had been abbot of Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen and preceptor (''{{lang-pi|upajjhaya}}''; person who ordained him) of Luang Por Dhammajayo during the latter's first years at Wat Paknam.<ref name=\"Dubus 2016\" /><ref name=\"Voice 2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gH8K1hZwVJw|date=23 March 2015|work=[[Voice TV]]|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e0f\u0e34\u0e23\u0e39\u0e1b\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e44\u0e25\u0e48\u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Reforming religion or hunting down Dhammakaya?|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Lok 2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lokwannee.com/web2013/?p=259415|last=Yimprasert|first=Sutchchai|date=27 February 2017|work=Lok Wan Nee|access-date=13 March 2017|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e43\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c|trans-title=The history of Dhammakaya}}</ref> Moreover, several Thai intellectuals and news analysts stated that Paiboon, Phra Suwit and Mano were abusing the ''Vinaya'' (monastic discipline) for political ends, and did not really aim to \"purify\" Buddhism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/378129.html|title=|last=Phaka|first=Kham|date=16 June 2016|work=Voice TV|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e0d\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e30\u0e17\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e08\u0e33\u0e01\u0e31\u0e14\u0e2d\u0e33\u0e19\u0e32\u0e08\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e23\u0e27\u0e21\u0e28\u0e39\u0e19\u0e22\u0e4c|trans-title=Problems with Dhammakaya reflect limitations in the government's centralizing efforts|via=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Tawisak 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.posttoday.com/analysis/interview/436236|date=8 June 2016|work=Post Today|publisher=The Post Publishing|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e34\u0e1e\u0e32\u0e01\u0e29\u0e4c \"\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e01\u0e0e\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e42\u0e04\u0e48\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\" \u0e2a\u0e38\u0e23\u0e1e\u0e28 \u0e17\u0e27\u0e35\u0e28\u0e31\u0e01\u0e14\u0e34\u0e4c|trans-title=Surapot Tawisak: commenting on the fall of Dhammakaya|last1=Panichkul|first1=Intarachai|accessdate=3 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205182815/http://www.posttoday.com/analysis/interview/436236|archive-date=5 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=4 June 2015|work=Matichon|access-date=25 January 2017|page=12|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e22\u0e37\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e2a\u0e2a.\u0e23\u0e37\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=Submitting to Attorney-General to revive lawsuit Dhammajayo|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe investigations were widely reported in the press, but eventually junta leader [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]] intervened: the embezzlement case had already been closed in 2006 by the then Attorney-General and that was the end of it. Prayut was afraid of the rising conflicts. He then dissolved the religious committee of the reform council. However, Paiboon, Phra Suwit and Mano continued to address shortcomings of leading members of the Sangha Council through judicial means.<ref name=\"Dubus 2016\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=8 June 2015|work=Matichon|access-date=25 January 2017|pages=8\u20139|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e22\u0e38\u0e1a\u0e41\u0e25\u0e49\u0e27 \u0e01\u0e01.\u0e1b\u0e0f\u0e34\u0e23\u0e39\u0e1b\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32 \u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e08\u0e47\u0e2d\u0e1a|trans-title=Reform committee dissolved, task is finished|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In the meantime, the DSI investigated further, and it was discovered that a used [[vintage car]] in Wat Paknam's museum had not been properly registered, allegedly to evade taxes. Somdet Chuang was charged with tax evasion by the DSI,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/dsi-bares-illegal-import-of-somdet-chuang-mercedes/869624|title=DSI bares illegal import of Somdet Chuang's Mercedes|date=19 February 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|accessdate=10 November 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and the accusations were reason enough for the government to further postpone the appointment.<ref name=\"Holmes 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/29/top-thai-buddhist-monk-somdet-chuang-investigated-over-vintage-mercedes-benz|title=Top Thai Buddhist monk investigated over vintage Mercedes-Benz|date=29 March 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|last1=Holmes|first1=Oliver|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/aec/30290322|title=Prayut refuses to submit nomination of Somdet Chuang as Supreme Patriarch|date=12 July 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|last2=Samerp|first2=Sakda|last1=Deechuay|first1=Anapat|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> Fear of Phra Suwit Dhiradhammo and his ties to the army may have played a role in this stalling.<ref name=\"Dubus 20160118\" /> In December 2016, the [[National Legislative Assembly of Thailand (2014)|National Legislative Assembly]] amended the {{ill|2005 Monastic Act|th|\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e40\u0e16\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e04\u0e21#%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%8A%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%8D%E0%B8%8D%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%93%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%86%E0%B9%8C_%E0%B8%9E.%E0%B8%A8._2505_%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%81%E0%B9%89%E0%B9%84%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%B4%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%A1%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%A1%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%94%E0%B8%A2_%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%8A%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%8D%E0%B8%8D%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%93%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%86%E0%B9%8C_(%E0%B8%89%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%B5%E0%B9%88_2)_%E0%B8%9E.%E0%B8%A8._2535}} to allow other monks than Somdet Chuang to be appointed Supreme Patriarch.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dubus|first1=Arnaud|title=La junte amende la loi monastique pour \u00e9carter Somdet Chuang de la direction de l'Eglise bouddhique|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2017-01-02-la-junte-amende-la-loi-monastique-pour-ecarter-somdet-chuang-de-la-direction-de-l2019eglise-bouddhique/|accessdate=18 March 2017|work=Eglises d'Asie|publisher=Paris Foreign Missions Information Agency|date=2 January 2017|language=fr|trans-title=The junta amends the monastic law to remove Somdet Chuang from the leadership of the Buddhist religion}}</ref> Finally in February 2017, {{ill|Somdet Amborn|th|\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e34\u0e22\u0e27\u0e07\u0e28\u0e32\u0e04\u0e15\u0e0d\u0e32\u0e13 \u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e06\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a (\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e23 \u0e2d\u0e21\u0e3a\u0e1e\u0e42\u0e23)}} was appointed by King Vajiralongkorn to serve as the next Supreme Patriarch.<ref name=\"Nation 2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/breakingnews/30305856|work=[[The Nation]]|title=Somdet Phra Maha Muneewong appointed new supreme patriarch|url-access=limited|date=7 February 2017|access-date=8 February 2017}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|In November 2016, the prosecutors decided not to charge Somdet Chuang, but to charge his attendant Luang Phi Pae instead, and another six people who had taken part in importing the vintage car.<ref name=\"Kom 2016\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.komchadluek.net/news/regional/250165|title=|date=25 November 2016|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e41\u0e23\u0e01 \u0e23\u0e16\u0e42\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e32\u0e13\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e07|trans-title=First hearing vintage car Somdet Chuang postponed|access-date=25 December 2016|via=}}</ref> On 12 January 2017, however, the prosecutor issued a non-prosecution order against Luang Phi Pae, since the Department of Special Investigation had found no evidence of conspiring to evade taxes. The order indicated innocence on the part of Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen, the temple of Somdet Chuang.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e27\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e48\u0e41\u0e1b\u0e4a\u0e30\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e23\u0e16\u0e42\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e32\u0e13\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e39\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e07 \u0e0a\u0e35\u0e49\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e21\u0e35\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e01\u0e10\u0e32\u0e19\u0e23\u0e39\u0e49\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e20\u0e32\u0e29\u0e35\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e16\u0e39\u0e01\u0e15\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07|trans-title=Issuing non-prosecution order for Luang Phi Pae in lawsuit vintage car Somdet Chuang, no evidence of awareness of private company paying taxes incorrectly|url=https://news.thaipbs.or.th/content/259470|work=[[Thai PBS]]|date=12 January 2017|language=th}}</ref> Paiboon responded to the outcome by giving several other reasons why he believed Somdet Chuang could not be Supreme Patriarch.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e44\u0e1e\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e22\u0e01 3 \u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d \u0e2a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e21\u0e41\u0e04\u0e25\u0e07\u0e43\u0e08 \u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e27\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e21\u0e0b\u0e38\u0e01\u0e23\u0e16\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e39|language=th|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/content/837040|accessdate=3 February 2017|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|date=16 January 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Klongchan controversy ===\n\nOn 29 October 2015, the DSI stated that Supachai Srisuppa-aksorn, then chairman of the Klongchan Credit Union Cooperative (KCUC), had fraudulently authorized 878 cheques worth 11.37 billion baht, in which a portion totaling more than a billion baht was traced to Wat Phra Dhammakaya via donations. The problem had begun in April 2013, when it turned out that Supachai had borrowed too much money from the [[credit union]] for it to manage, and it had to freeze fifty thousand accounts, as well as postpone the payments to seventy-four creditors. The angered members held many protests and the credit union sued Supachai. The temple was implicated as well. In defense, spokespeople of Wat Phra Dhammakaya said that Luang Por Dhammajayo was not aware that the donations were illegally obtained because the temple lacked the means to check for illegally obtained money.<ref name=\"Yee 161116\">{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/politics-and-religion-coming-worryingly-together-in-temple-scandal|title=Politics and religion coming worryingly together in temple scandal|date=23 June 2016|work=[[The Straits Times]]|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|author=Tan Hui Yee|accessdate=16 November 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"Thai PBS 160502\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2016/07/66829|work=[[Prachatai]]|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e04\u0e23\u0e14\u0e34\u0e15\u0e22\u0e39\u0e40\u0e19\u0e35\u0e22\u0e19|language=th|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya and the credit union|first=Suthachai|last=Yimprasert|access-date=26 December 2017|date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, in a written agreement with the credit union, supporters of the temple had raised 684 million baht linked to Wat Phra Dhammakaya to donate to the {{abbr|KCUC|Klongchan Credit Union Cooperative}} to compensate their members. The money was donated under the condition that the credit union would withdraw the charges, and the money would be returned to the temple if Supachai's donations to the temple were later proven legal.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 160502\" />\n\nIn the meantime, Supachai was convicted and jailed, but more charges of embezzlement and fraud were still under investigation. Another 370 million baht linked to the temple was discovered as the [[Anti-Money Laundering Office (Thailand)|Anti-Money Laundering Office]] and DSI investigated further. Donors of the temple donated the remaining 370 million baht to the credit union as well,{{Refn|The sum of the two amounts donated to the credit union did not exactly match the total amount of money that was traced to Wat Phra Dhammakaya, because it was argued by the temple's lawyers that twenty cheques had not actually reached Luang Por Dhammajayo.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e04\u0e37\u0e19\u0e1c\u0e39\u0e49\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e2b\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e14\u0e08\u0e23\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48|trans-title=Did Dhammakaya really return all the credit union money to those affected?|number=2|time=3:12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hC6vWyiQivI|accessdate=17 November 2016|work=Bright TV|date=6 May 2016|language=th}}</ref>|group=note}} but apart from the problem of compensation to the credit union, the DSI suspected Luang Por Dhammajayo of having conspired in the embezzlement of Supachai. The department then investigated two charges: conspiring to launder money and receiving stolen goods. The charges were laid by an affected client of the credit union, who felt the money the temple returned had too many strings attached.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 160502\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/thai-abbot-be-probed-over-massive-donations|title=Thai abbot to be probed over massive donations|date=10 May 2009|work=[[AsiaOne]]|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> The temple denied the charges of the department, stating that donations were received in the open in public, and that Supachai had only donated cheques, no cash. They further explained that the temple had a department for financial matters, in which Supachai had no part,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.dhammakaya.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/FINALPressReleaseFactsRegardingDSIBidtoArrestDhammakayaAbbot-1.pdf|title=Press Release|last=Dantamano|first=Phra Pasura|date=3 May 2016|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.dhammakaya.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/2016-12-09-PetitiontoHMKingEnglish.pdf|title=Petition to HM The King from devotees of Wat Phra Dhammakaya|date=9 December 2016|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|author=Devotees of Wat Phra Dhammakaya|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> and accused the DSI of violating [[double jeopardy]] principles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.dhammakaya.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/PressRelease14June2016.pdf|title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya Press Release|date=14 June 2016|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|last1=Wuttiwangso|first1=Phra Sanitwong|translator-first=Phra Pasura|translator-last=Dantamano|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> The DSI stated that Supachai was likely to have been a financial assistant of the abbot, because he had admitted in court that the abbot was on friendly, informal terms with him.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e22\u0e01\u0e04\u0e33\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=Request to withdraw arrest warrant Dhammajayo denied|url=http://www.komchadluek.net/news/crime/228262|accessdate=16 December 2017|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|date=24 May 2015|language=th}}</ref>\n\nLuang Por Dhammajayo was summoned to acknowledge the charges of ill-gotten gains and conspiring to money-laundering at the offices of the DSI. Spokespeople of the temple asked for postponement three times: the first time citing a busy schedule due to training programs, and after that the abbot's [[deep vein thrombosis]].<ref name=\"Thai PBS 160502\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s72K_zUt5T0|title=|last=|first=|date=2 May 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|publisher=|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e29\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e08\u0e32\u0e04\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19|trans-title=Poisonous donations of a billion baht|lay-url=http://www.dhammakayauncovered.com/editorial/2016/4/21/a-perspective-on-the-klongchan-credit-union-cooperative-case|lay-source=Dhammakaya Uncovered|lay-date=21 April 2016|via=|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Thailand-Temple/f1de88b4d2b46d648fcc53eeaec5a425|title=Police raid Thai temple in search of wanted monk|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|via=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Constant 161115\">{{cite news|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/thai-police-blocked-from-arresting-controversial-abbot/590527|title=Thai police blocked from arresting controversial abbot|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|last2=Constant|first2=Max|location=Bangkok|last1=Thana|first1=CS|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> According to spokespeople, to travel to the DSI could mean a risk to Luang Por Dhammajayo's life. The temple requested the DSI to let him acknowledge his charges at the temple, a request the DSI refused.<ref name=\"Yee 161111\">{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/thai-abbot-defies-orders-to-appear-at-fraud-probe|title=Thai abbot defies orders to appear at fraud probe|date=28 May 2016|work=[[The Straits Times]]|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|via=|last1=Yee|first1=Tan Hui|accessdate=11 November 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"Spring 161118\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9ML53YfJqQ|date=6 May 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 (\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48) \u0e1c\u0e34\u0e14?|trans-title=Is Dhammajayo at fault?|number=1|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> The DSI was skeptical of the temple's cited reasons and asked for a certificate from a physician, which the temple gave, but just as in 1999, discussions arose regarding the way the certification should be properly done.<ref name=\"Danai 161118\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N3xacb7X4Ow|date=5 June 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22...\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e14\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a \u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e16\u0e19\u0e32 (\u0e14\u0e35) DSI?|trans-title=Does Dhammakaya deny DSI's (good) intentions?|last1=Ekmahasawat|first1=Danai|accessdate=18 November 2016|time=5:50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/correspondents/content/2016/s4475743.htm|title=Thailand standoff: a monk's refusal to explain police questions about money laundering|date=4 June 2016|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|last1=Cochrane|first1=Liam|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> Moreover, the DSI concluded that Luang Por Dhammajayo was a flight risk and asked for an arrest warrant to take the abbot into custody.<ref name=\"Thai PBS 160502\" /> In the period the DSI issued an arrest warrant for the abbot, the temple was organizing a training program for women with thousands participants. Accused of organizing a [[human shield]] to prevent the DSI from entering, a spokesperson of the temple said that the only thing the temple would do to resist is \"chanting and meditation\".<ref name=\"Yee 161111\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=enjZZRCXBW8|date=16 May 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e01\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e49\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e43\u0e08 \u0e1a\u0e34\u0e14\u0e40\u0e1a\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e19...?|trans-title=The end of Phra Dhammajayo's lawsuit: Clearing up the question whether {{bracket|teachings are}} distorted|last1=Chimmani|first1=Worawit|number=1|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pN97nryLNMM|date=25 May 2016|work=Amarin|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e15\u0e32\u0e22...\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27|trans-title=Dhammajayo at the finish line... surrendering|last1=Aphiwan|first1=Phuttha|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>[[File:Police squadron prepare to enter Wat Phra Dhammakaya.jpg|thumb|Police squadron prepares to enter Wat Phra Dhammakaya in a raid|left]]In the meantime, news analysts, lawyers, current and former government officials of the Thai justice system, such as [[Seripisut Temiyavet]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zCQIWfqtc48|date=24 June 2016|script-title=th:\u0e17\u0e38\u0e08\u0e23\u0e34\u0e15 \u0e2d\u0e1c\u0e28.\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=The illegal practices of the War Veterans Organization of Thailand and Phra Dhammajayo's case|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mHNW2nKJWOc|title=\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e28\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e4c\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e21\u0e20\u0e32\u0e29\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35 \u0e42\u0e08 \u0e14\u0e48\u0e32\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e21\u0e31\u0e0d_\u0e06\u0e32\u0e15\u0e01\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21 \u0e09\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e21 32 \u0e19\u0e32\u0e17\u0e35|date=24 June 2016|website=Seree Voice|trans-title=Seripisut has an interview about Cho Danchang's lawsuit, the problem of legal killing |time=26:42|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> came out to state that the DSI was not handling the investigation of the temple with proper legal procedure. It was questioned why the DSI would not let the abbot acknowledge the charges at the temple, which many considered legitimate under criminal law.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2x6ovTnf0nQ|title=|last=|first=|date=27 May 2016|work=[[TNN24]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e22\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07 \u0e2a\u0e19\u0e07.\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e0d\u0e32\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e22 DSI \u0e08\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e48\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e28\u0e32\u0e25\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e44\u0e14\u0e49\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e01\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e21\u0e35\u0e21\u0e39\u0e25|trans-title=Review: Office of Criminal Law states DSI cannot charge Phra Dhammajayo if lawsuit is baseless|via=Bright TV|accessdate=9 August 2016}} subtitled [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wd-oHil2MFU here]</ref><ref name=\"Chatmontri\">{{cite journal|date=23 May 2016|title=|script-title=th:\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e14\u0e35\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e2a\u0e44\u0e2d|trans-title=Arrest warrant of Phra Dhammajayo and DSI's justice|url=http://www.prachatai.com/journal/2016/05/65923|journal=[[Prachatai]]|last1=Chatmontri|first1=Winyat|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pptvthailand.com/programs/%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7/%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B7%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%87-%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7/64589|title=|last=Wiriyaphanphongsa|first=Satian|date=30 May 2016|work=[[PPTV (Thailand)]]|publisher=Bangkok Media and Broadcasting|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e19\u0e28\u0e23\u0e31\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32 \"\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\"|trans-title=Arrest warrants and faith: Phra Dhammajayo}}</ref> The DSI replied that they did not want to visit the abbot at the temple at this stage, because the temple was crowded with people, which could lead to conflict.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pptvthailand.com/news/%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B0%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%94%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%99/27513|date=18 November 2016|work=[[PPTV (Thailand)]]|publisher=Bangkok Media and Broadcasting|last2=Khumthamphinit|first2=Parinda|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a \u201c\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\u201d \u0e1a\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e08\u0e19\u0e4c \u0e01\u0e0e\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u2013\u0e28\u0e23\u0e31\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32|trans-title=Arrest warrant Dhammajayo: law versus faith put to the test|first1=Chanchai|last1=Kayasit}}</ref> A spokesperson of the temple also questioned why the DSI did not pursue lawsuits that were still running against Paiboon and Phra Suwit. Was the DSI biased because they received orders from someone not disclosed?<ref name=\"Anan 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/aec/30288864|title=Phra Dhammachayo's disciples accuse DSI of double standards|date=23 June 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|last2=Th|first2=Piyanuch|first1=Anan|last1=Wijitpracha}}</ref> The DSI had seen its independence questioned before, even by leading people within the department itself.<ref name=\"Wechsler 2009\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-07/12/c_13396249.htm|title=Thai special investigation team must politically {{bracket|be}} freed: Senior official {{bracket|says}}|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Xinhua]]|author=Deng, Shasha|accessdate=1 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103233906/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-07/12/c_13396249.htm|archivedate=3 November 2016}}</ref> In short, the temple's practitioners and spokespeople felt the charges were politically motivated, and had no confidence in the justice system under the junta. Moreover, they felt that if the former abbot would turn himself in, this would set a precedent for more baseless persecutions of other monks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r3AiAkBF5ao|date=16 December 2016|work=Amarin|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32(\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48)\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e43\u0e19\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e34\u0e4c \u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e27\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|trans-title=We are (not) confident about Luang Por Dhammajayo's innocence|last1=Apiwan|first1=Puttha|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFFqSO2T2i8|last=Laopet|first=Jomquan|date=16 December 2016|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e43\u0e08\u0e28\u0e34\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya's students speak from their heart|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rojanaphruk 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/news/2016/12/18/look-inside-dhammakayas-besieged-temple/|title=A Look Inside the Besieged Wat Dhammakaya|date=18 December 2016|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|publisher=Matichon Publishing|last1=Rojanaphruk|first1=Pravit|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the DSI entered the temple to take Luang Por Dhammajayo in custody. However, a number of laypeople sitting silently in rows barred the DSI from continuing their search. The DSI, avoiding a confrontation, withdrew.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/thai-police-prepare-to/2877174.html|title=Meditating devotees shield scandal-hit abbot from Thai police|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Channel News Asia]]|publisher=[[Mediacorp]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617141309/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/thai-police-prepare-to/2877174.html|archivedate=17 June 2016}}</ref> A temple official was seen giving a press statement that the abbot would surrender himself \"as soon as the state has become a democracy\", enabling a fair judicial process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aWeOPRvHNZE|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|last2=Mahitthiruk|first2=Omonrat|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14! 5 \u0e41\u0e01\u0e19\u0e19\u0e33 \"\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\"|trans-title=The 5 leaders of Dhammakaya revealed|last1=Ekmahasawat|first1=Danai|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> Even though the statement was later downplayed by temple's spokespeople as not representing the temple's official opinion,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DKp5tkHgSWM|date=27 June 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e28\u0e34\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \"\u0e40\u0e04\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e4c\" \u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e23\u0e2b\u0e32 \"\u0e2a\u0e2b\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e2f \u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e08\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19-\u0e01\u0e33\u0e41\u0e1e\u0e07\u0e21\u0e19\u0e38\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\"|trans-title=Dhammakaya's followers clear up the accusations about the Klongchan Credit Union and the human shield|last1=Chimmani|first1=Worawit|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> former senator Paiboon pointed out it reflected the temple's autonomy from the state.<ref name=\"BBC 2017\" /> In reflection, news analysts concluded that the DSI did not really have the intention to arrest Luang Por Dhammajayo, but was simply surveying the temple grounds, or \"playing political theatre\" ([[Otago Daily Times]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hnBrbMNMY1s|date=16 June 2016|work=Amarin|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e01\u0e0f\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e22\u0e38\u0e15\u0e34\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e42\u0e25\u0e48\u0e21\u0e19\u0e38\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c|trans-title=A perspective on the ending of the arrest of Dhammajayo, because of a row of people|last1=Aphiwan|first1=Phuttha|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/world/thai-police-prepare-raid-scandal-hit-temple|title=Thai police prepare to raid scandal-hit temple|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Otago Daily Times]]|publisher=[[Allied Press]]|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k0Esql34ckQ|date=16 June 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e02\u0e35\u0e14\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e43\u0e15\u0e49\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22: \u0e27\u0e34\u0e40\u0e04\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e4c\u0e1b\u0e0f\u0e34\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e01\u0e1a\u0e34\u0e25 59|trans-title=Underlining Thailand: analysis of the \u0e3aBill 59 Mission|last1=Klikrajai|first1=Suphap|accessdate=18 November 2016|time=3:55}}</ref>\n\nAfter the standoff had taken place, tensions in social media rose, and the attorney-general stated that DSI should complete its investigations first, before further action could be taken.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30299408|title=Public prosecutors to delay Dhammachayo indictment decision again to Nov 30|date=8 November 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|last2=Tamnukasetchai|first2=Piyanuch|last1=Taengkhieo|first1=Kesinee|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/crime/1129184/oag-puts-off-decision-on-one-of-dhammajayo-cases|title=OAG puts off decision on one of Dhammajayo's cases|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|url-access=limited}}</ref> In the meantime, Luang Por Dhammajayo was ordered by a senior monk to step down as abbot temporarily, after Phra Suwit Dhiradhammo filed a request for suspension, citing Luang Por Dhammajayo's illness.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PDTaZXXCVYY|date=31 May 2016|work=NOW 26|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e16\u0e25\u0e07 \u0e2d\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e31\u0e0a\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e2f\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21|trans-title=Dhammakaya announces to ask the Theravada Buddhist Sangha Council to insist the Prime Minister acts fairly|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Aqf_82imsXY|date=31 May 2016|work=New TV|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e14 \u0e1a\u0e23\u0e23\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e28\u0e2a\u0e14\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Live: The atmosphere at Wat Phra Dhammakaya|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref> It turned out, however, that Luang Por Dhammajayo had stepped down since 2011, but this was not widely known. It was then announced in the media that Luang Por Dattajivo was the acting abbot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YfqVK9_HSQo|date=9 July 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Acting abbot Dhammakaya appointed|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/387648.html|last=Kanha|first=Wiranan|date=11 July 2016|work=[[Voice TV]]|access-date=9 February 2017|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e43\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e41\u0e23\u0e01! \u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e41\u0e17\u0e19\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Not the first time! Acting abbot Wat Phra Dhammakaya appointed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821002935/https://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/387648.html|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December, however, Phravitetbhavanacharn was appointed instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.posttoday.com/social/general/469373|date=9 December 2016|work=Post Today|publisher=The Post Publishing|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e14'\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22'\u0e1e\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Phra Dhammajayo removed from position abbot Wat Phra Dhammakaya|accessdate=10 December 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Junta''<nowiki />'s lockdown ===\n\n<!--\"Luang Por Dattajivo\" links here.-->[[File:Dhammakaya Standoff.jpg|thumb|The ''junta''<nowiki />'s lockdown.]]\nWhen it turned out that the prosecutors were slow to continue the Klongchan lawsuit with regard to Luang Por Dhammajayo, the DSI and several other police departments started to press charges against other people related to the temple.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/monks-summoned-for-questioning-in-dhammajayo-case/1029061|title=Monks summoned for questioning in Dhammajayo's case|date=6 July 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30293565|title=Dhammakaya lawyer, M-home board members hear charges|date=23 August 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|last1=Tamnukasetchai|first1=Piyanuch|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> To further pressurize Luang Por Dhammajayo, the DSI also expanded its focus to branch centers of Wat Phra Dhammakaya. Branch centers in [[Nakhon Ratchasima]], [[Chiangmai]], [[Kanchanaburi]], [[Loei]], and [[Tak Province|Tak]] were investigated and charged with encroaching on [[nature reserve]]s.<ref name=\"Danai 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gOOlzfExmb4|date=28 June 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e27\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e0d\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 + \u0e40\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e28\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e4c \"\u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e14\u0e31\u0e1a\"|trans-title=Bunchai and Seripisut: the Dhammakaya battle is taken to a new level|last1=Ekmahasawat|first1=Danai|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.thaipbs.or.th/content/254149|date=18 July 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e15\u0e23\u0e27\u0e08\u0e2a\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e02\u0e32\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e21\u0e32\u0e15\u0e23\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e14\u0e14\u0e31\u0e19 \"\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\"|trans-title=Checking Wat Phra Dhammakaya's branches: A judicial way to pressurize Phra Dhammajayo}}</ref> On 21 November, this finally led to another two arrest warrants, totaling three, and plans were made by the Thai police and the DSI to take Luang Por Dhammajayo into custody, through force if required.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fWpuwJgdY0w|work=[[Spring News]]|last2=Mahitthiruk|first2=Amonrat|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14 3 \u0e2b\u0e21\u0e32\u0e22\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a \"\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\"|trans-title=3 arrest warrants for Dhammajayo explained|last1=Ekmahasawat|first1=Danai|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.banmuang.co.th/news/crime/69568|date=3 December 2016|work=Banmuang|language=th|script-title=th:\u201c\u0e28\u0e23\u0e35\u0e27\u0e23\u0e32\u0e2b\u0e4c\u201d\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e17\u0e31\u0e1e \u0e1a\u0e38\u0e01\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e15\u0e32\u0e2210\u0e18\u0e31\u0e19\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27|trans-title=Sirawa organizes police force to enter Dhammakaya, 10 December deadline to surrender|accessdate=4 December 2016|archiveurl=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:http://www.banmuang.co.th/news/crime/69568|archivedate=3 December 2016}}</ref>[[File:Gates of Wat Phra Dhammakaya during Article 44.jpg|thumb|Crowd of people at Wat Phra Dhammakaya gates as police and soldiers surround the temple|left]]A deal was proposed that if Luang Por Dhammajayo surrendered he would not be incarcerated and subsequently defrocked. Although the DSI agreed with such a guarantee at first, they later stated they could not give it because it was the jurisdiction of the court to decide on this.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pattayamail.com/thailandnews/dhammachayo-agrees-surrender-provided-granted-bail-157280|title=Dhammachayo agrees to surrender provided he is granted bail|date=3 December 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|via=Pattaya Mail|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1151025/dsi-says-its-powerless-to-meet-abbots-bail-demand|title=DSI says it's powerless to meet abbot's bail demand|date=4 December 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|last1=Wongyala|first1=Pongpat|accessdate=4 December 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"Wongyala 2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1162845/police-demand-cooperation-from-abbot|title=Police demand cooperation from abbot|date=19 December 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|last1=Wongyala|first1=Pongpat|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> News analysts speculated that Thai law enforcement had not been able to arrest the abbot successfully, because of the complexity of the temple's terrain, the large number of practitioners, who continually adjusted their methods, and the imminent danger of a violent clash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rfsPaFrQQaE|date=14 December 2016|work=[[PPTV]]|publisher=Bangkok Media and Broadcasting|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e1c\u0e31\u0e07\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e49\u0e32\u0e22\u0e21\u0e27\u0e25\u0e0a\u0e19 \u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e15\u0e23\u0e27\u0e08\u0e04\u0e49\u0e19|time=11:42|trans-title=Analyzing a map of Wat Phra Dhammakaya: moving people, preparing for searches|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1162921|title=Temple drama a tale of ineptness|date=19 December 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|last1=Prateepchaikul|first1=Veera|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> Another reason brought up by news analysts was the Thai ''junta''<nowiki />'s concern for potential international backlash that could be generated from Wat Phra Dhammakaya's numerous international centers. In fact, international followers had already petitioned the [[White House]] and met with US Congressmen regarding the case.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/Thai-junta-in-showdown-at-Buddhist-temple-gates|title=Thai junta in showdown at Buddhist temple gates|last=Macan-Markar|first=Marwaan|date=25 January 2017|work=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|access-date=29 January 2017|via=}}</ref> During the standoff, temple officials still affirmed that they were willing to cooperate with law enforcement, their only request being that the DSI give Luang Por Dhammajayo his charges at the temple due to his health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/-thai-temple-says-not-resisting-legal-process-of-abbot/723413|title=Thai temple says not resisting legal process of abbot|access-date=29 January 2017|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]}}</ref> However, the police applied the method of \"trimming the tree\" by issuing hundreds of fines about gates, bridges, and other parts of the temple, to gradually get more control over the temple.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30302275|title=Dhammachayo arrest on hold as warrant expires; temple faces more than 100 complaints|date=17 December 2016|work=[[The Nation]]|accessdate=20 December 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pptvthailand.com/programs/%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7/%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B7%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%87-%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7/67086|date=16 December 2016|work=[[PPTV]]|publisher=Bangkok Media and Broadcasting|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e15\u0e31\u0e14\u0e41\u0e02\u0e19\u0e02\u0e32\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Removing Wat Phra Dhammakaya's limbs|last1=Wiriyapongsa|first1=Satian|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> As of March 2017, the Thai junta had laid 340 different charges against the temple and the foundation, including alleged forest encroachment and allegedly building the ''Ubosot'' illegally in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/massed-police-surround-bangkok-buddhist-temple-in-standoff-with-monks-20161227-gtidu4.html|title=Police delay raid on Thailand's largest temple after stand-off with monks|last=Murdoch|first=Lindsay|date=27 December 2016|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=8 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30306679|title=308 criminal cases filed against Dhammakaya Temple|access-date=25 February 2017|newspaper=[[The Nation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Prachatai 2017\" /> While law enforcement was under growing pressure to get the job done, criticism against the operation grew as well, news reporters comparing the temple with [[Falun Gong]] in China or the [[Gulen Movement]] from Turkey.<ref name=\"Reuters 170224\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism-power-idUSKBN163037|title=The power struggle behind Thailand's temple row|date=24 February 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|last2=Satrusayang|first2=Cod|last3=Thempgumpanat|first3=Panarat|last1=Tostevin|first1=Matthew|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Rojanaphruk 2016\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://shows.voicetv.co.th/inherview/463542.html|date=20 February 2017|work=[[Voice TV]]|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32: \u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e43\u0e0a\u0e48\u0e40\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e0a\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e15\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e30\u0e40\u0e25\u0e32\u0e30\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19|trans-title=Buddhism, choose your preference and don't fight about it|last1=Paka|first1=Kham|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Wat Phra Dhammakaya monks meet soldiers.jpg|thumb|Monks at Wat Phra Dhammakaya prepare to meet incoming unit of military during the ''junta''<nowiki />'s lockdown]]\nMeanwhile, the temple started a project to encourage people to chant the [[Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta]], traditionally regarded as the first teaching of the Buddha.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pptvthailand.com/programs/%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7/%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%82%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A7%E0%B8%84%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B3/65408|date=19 July 2016|work=[[PPTV (Thailand)]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e14\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1b\u0e1b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e15\u0e23 1 \u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e08\u0e1a|trans-title=Wat Phra Dhammakaya chants the Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta one million times|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2004|title=Life of the Buddha|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|publisher=[[Thomson-Gale]]|location=Farmington Hills|url=http://www.ahandfulofleaves.org/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Buddhism_2%20Vols_%20Buswell.pdf|editor-last=Buswell|editor-first=Robert E. Jr.|volume=1|page=84|isbn=0-02-865719-5|author=Bechert, Heinz}}</ref> The activities at the temple were interpreted as methods to block law-enforcing officers from entering the terrain. On 9 December 2016, the television channel of the temple was therefore closed down to prevent the temple from further mobilizing supporters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/439647.html|work=VoiceTV|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e17\u0e35\u0e27\u0e35\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e0a\u0e19\u0e27\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38\u0e23\u0e30\u0e14\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e25|trans-title=Closing down channel Dhammakaya, reason used for mobilizing|last1=Chotsiripornrit|first1=Natchapan|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1154077/regulator-takes-temple-tv-off-air|title=Regulator takes temple TV off air|date=8 December 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=8 December 2016|publisher=The Post Publishing|url-access=limited}}</ref> In February 2017, four days after the appointment of the new Supreme Patriarch with no connections to the temple, junta leader Prayuth announced a special decree following the controversial [[Prayut Chan-o-cha#Article 44|Section 44]] of the [[2014 interim constitution of Thailand|interim constitution]].<ref name=\"Reuters 170224\" /> The section gave a carte blanche to law-enforcing authorities to get Luang Por Dhammajayo into custody through a wide range of means.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/news/crimecourtscalamity/2017/02/16/dhammakaya-says-govt-siege-not-buddhist-way/|title=Dhammakaya Says Govt Siege Not \"Buddhist Way\"|date=16 February 2017|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|publisher=Matichon Publishing|last1=Rojanaphruk|first1=Pravit|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/crime/1199117/assault-on-dhammakaya-temple-imminent|title=Assault on Dhammakaya temple 'imminent'|date=16 February 2017|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=Post Publishing|last1=Laohong|first1=King-oua|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> The decree included heavy penalties against any person obstructing the arrest, and declaring the temple a restricted zone, which no-one could access or leave without the authorities' permission. A 4200-man combined [[task force]] of the DSI, police and army surrounded the temple and started to search every corner of the terrains. The temple showed little resistance.<ref name=\"Prachatai 2017\">{{cite news|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2017/03/70611|work=[[Prachatai]]|script-title=th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01: \u0e2a\u0e23\u0e38\u0e1b\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e43\u0e0a\u0e49 \u0e21.44 \u0e01\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e25\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|language=th|trans-title=A monk that is hard to find: summary of situation after using section 44, before and after lockdown|date=16 March 2017|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1199557|title=Police enter temple, search for Phra Dhammajayo begins|date=16 February 2017|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/special-investigation-department-summons-top-temple-monks|title=Special investigation department summons top temple monks|date=20 February 2017|work=Asia One|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|agency=[[Asia News Network]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> After two days, the task force reached the residence where the former abbot stayed, only to find it empty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.phillytrib.com/thai-police-empty-handed-so-far-in-search-for-prominent/article_9b9849cd-4572-5d84-b576-7797d38ea3a3.html|title=Thai police empty-handed so far in search for prominent monk|date=17 February 2017|work=[[The Philadelphia Tribune]]|last1=Kaewjinda|first1=Dow|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Despite having searched every room and building in the temple,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/thousands-thais-obstruct-search-wanted-monk-170219123011943.html|title=Thousands of Thais obstruct search for wanted monk|date=19 February 2017|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref> the authorities did not withdraw and ordered all non-residents of the temple to leave. Tensions increased, and though the temple staff was unarmed, they managed to use large crowds to push through the task force and a deal was brokered to allow lay people to come in the temple. On 22 February, an official negotiation followed, the DSI still pushing to remove all non-residents from the temple.<ref name=\"Asia 1 2017\">{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/special-investigation-department-summons-top-temple-monks|title=Special investigation department summons top temple monks|work=Asia One|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|agency=[[Asia News Network]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2017/02/19/dhammakaya-supporters-defy-order-leave-dsi-withdraw-forces/|title=Dhammakaya Supporters Defy Order to Leave; DSI to Withdraw Forces|date=19 February 2017|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|publisher=Matichon Publishing|last1=Charuvastra|first1=Teeranai|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> The temple stated they had been sufficiently cooperative and pointed out that the task force had completed their search, resulting in a standoff and a siege of the temple by thousands of military personnel.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|title=Thailand's Dhammakaya Temple Under Scrutiny|url=https://www.wsj.com/video/thailand-dhammakaya-temple-under-scrutiny/6B0C0B21-4AE6-4EFD-A40C-21968D021BF2.html|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/thousands-thais-obstruct-search-wanted-monk-170219123011943.html|title=Thousands of Thais obstruct search for wanted monk|date=19 February 2017|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/dhammakaya-temple-monks-see-help-un|title=Dhammakaya temple monks to see help from UN|work=Asia One|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|agency=[[Asia News Network]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> In the meantime, the junta government stated they were not only looking for Luang Por Dhammajayo, but were also intending to reform the temple.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationtv.tv/main/content/politics/378535779/|date=22 February 2017|work=The Nation TV|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e27\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e18\u0e38\u0e4c \u0e22\u0e31\u0e19\u0e04\u0e49\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e21\u0e35\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e15\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e08\u0e30\u0e17\u0e33\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e01\u0e15\u0e34\u0e17\u0e31\u0e48\u0e27\u0e44\u0e1b|trans-title=Suwapan confirms to set no deadline for search Dhammakaya, will change Dhammakaya into a normal temple|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichon.co.th/news/466412|date=17 February 2017|work=Matichon Online|language=th|script-title=th:9.00 INDEX \u0e21\u0e32\u0e15\u0e23\u0e32 44 \u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e14\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e44\u0e1b\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23|trans-title=Level 9 on the Section 44 Index in the Dhammakaya situation: from politics to military action|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> This raised questions, and a lively national debate started as to what a \"real temple\" and \"real Buddhism\" should look like.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://shows.voicetv.co.th/wakeupnews/464541.html|date=February 2017|work=[[Voice TV]]|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e41\u0e17\u0e49 \u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e41\u0e19\u0e48\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e08\u0e30\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e41\u0e17\u0e49\u0e08\u0e23\u0e34\u0e07|trans-title=If someone establishes himself as a true Buddhist, he may not always be one|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://prachatai.com/journal/2017/03/70408|script-title=th:\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e41\u0e17\u0e49-\u0e40\u0e17\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e21\u0e35\u0e08\u0e23\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d?|language=th|trans-title=Does true or false religion exist? |last=Supawathanakul|first=Krisada|date=5 March 2017|access-date=24 December 2017|work=[[Prachatai]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newmandala.org/can-thailand-tolerate-one-form-buddhism/|title=Can Thailand tolerate more than one form of Buddhism?|date=1 December 2016|access-date=25 February 2017|newspaper=New Mandala}}</ref>\n[[File:Wat Phra Dhammakaya street during article 44.jpg|left|thumb|Monks at Wat Phra Dhammakaya during article 44 lockdown with soldiers surrounding the temple in the distance]]\nThe junta further increased its control on the temple by having the mobile signal in the temple area shut off,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/a-gruelling-surreal-and-potentially-sinister-stand-off|title=A gruelling, surreal and potentially sinister stand-off|last=Yee|first=Tan Hui|date=28 February 2017|work=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thairath.co.th/clip/104580|date=24 February 2017|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Wacharapol|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e14\u0e35\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e2a\u0e44\u0e2d\u0e15\u0e31\u0e14\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e0d\u0e0d\u0e32\u0e13\u0e42\u0e17\u0e23\u0e28\u0e31\u0e1e\u0e17\u0e4c\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=DSI cuts off Wat Phra Dhammakaya's telephone signal|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> by barring reporters from entering the temple<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/10/thailand-authorities-seek-disrobe-scandal-hit-buddhist-abbot|title=Thai authorities seek to defrock scandal-hit Buddhist abbot|last=Holmes|first=Oliver|date=10 March 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=11 March 2017}}</ref> and by censoring and blocking a broadcast about the lockdown from [[Al Jazeera]] in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2017/03/04/al-jazeeras-report-dhammakaya-chopped-truevisions-video/|title=Al Jazeera's Report on Dhammakaya Chopped by TrueVisions|last=Rojanaphruk|first=Pravit|date=4 March 2017|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|access-date=6 March 2017|publisher=Matichon Publishing}}</ref> Criticism of the operation further increased when one man committed suicide and one asthma patient died during the operation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/breakingnews/30307627|title=Dhammakaya follower dies of asthma after ambulance stopped by troops: monk spokesman|work=[[The Nation]]|access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2017/02/25/protester-commits-suicide-outside-wat-dhammakaya/|title=Protester Commits Suicide Outside Wat Dhammakaya|date=25 February 2017|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|publisher=Matichon Publishing|last1=Mokkhasen|first1=Sasiwan|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> On 10 March 2017, a deal was made allowing authorities to search the temple once again on the condition that representatives of the [[National Human Rights Commission (Thailand)|Thai Human Rights Commission]] and news reporters were allowed to witness the search.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1212333/search-resumes-at-wat-phra-dhammakaya|title=Search resumes at Wat Phra Dhammakaya|date=10 March 2017|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=11 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing|url-access=limited}}</ref> Once again, authorities were not able to find the abbot, resulting in the junta ending the three-week occupation of the temple. However, section 44 still remained in effect, allowing the authorities to resume action against the temple at any time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1212430/temple-search-ends-with-no-signs-of-phra-dhammajayo|title=Temple search ends with no signs of Phra Dhammajayo|date=|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=11 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism-idUSKBN16H18Q|title=Thai police end search of temple without finding monk|date=10 March 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=11 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe lockdown resulted in a heated debate about section 44. The section was raised as an example of the ''junta''<nowiki />'s illegitimacy and unjust means, by the temple and many other critics.<ref name=\"Asia 1 2017\" /><ref name=\"Nation 170223\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30306970|title=DSI prepares for \"full scale\" raid after talks break down|date=23 February 2017|work=[[The Nation]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nBBng5KH4CI|date=20 February 2017|work=Peace TV|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e23\u0e38\u0e21\u0e08\u0e27\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e40\u0e1c\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e04\u0e2a\u0e0a.\u0e40\u0e01\u0e34\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e15\u0e38 \u0e21.44 \u0e01\u0e27\u0e32\u0e14\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|trans-title=Many criticizing junta, NCPO too authoritarian, using Section 44 to eradicate Wat Phra Dhammakaya|via=Freedom Thailand|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> While proponents pointed out that all would be finished if Luang Por Dhammajayo only gave himself over to acknowledge the charges,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1034250.shtml|title=Thai PM not to revoke order over controversial temple until ex-abbot surrenders|date=22 February 2017|work=[[Xinhua]]|via=[[Global Times]]|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> critics pointed out that Luang Por Dhammajayo would be imprisoned and defrocked if brought into custody.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lokwannee.com/web2013/?p=254731|date=25 February 2017|work=Lok Wannee|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e07\u0e06\u0e4c\u0e22\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e39\u0e48\u0e20\u0e32\u0e22\u0e43\u0e15\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e33\u0e19\u0e32\u0e08\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10|trans-title=The Sangha is still under the state's control|last1=Praiwan|first1=Phra Maha|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=luK6CTybJog|date=24 February 2017|work=Jom Voice|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e33\u0e08\u0e31\u0e14\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e17\u0e33\u0e25\u0e32\u0e22\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32 \u0e2b\u0e19\u0e17\u0e32\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e2d\u0e33\u0e19\u0e32\u0e08\u0e04\u0e27\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e38\u0e21\u0e04\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22|trans-title=Removing Dhammakaya and destroying Buddhism: the path to gaining power to control Thai people|last1=Petchpradap|first1=Jom|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> News reporters compared the temple's resistance with the Burmese [[Saffron Revolution]] in 2007, some reporters expecting defeat soon,<ref name=\"Economist 2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21717412-dragnet-orders-headquarters-fails-snare-fugitive-abbot-thailands-junta-feuds|title=Thailand's junta feuds with an influential Buddhist sect|date=23 February 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|location=Patumthani|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> others a new opposition movement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2017/02/dhammakaya-temple-thailand-saffron-resistance-170222110000775.html|title=Dhammakaya temple and Thailand's saffron resistance|date=22 February 2017|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|last1=Hay|first1=Wayne|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theworldweekly.com/reader/view/magazine/2017-02-23/monks-stand-off-against-thai-military-junta/9746|title=Monks in standoff with Thai military junta|date=23 February 2017|work=The World Weekly|last1=McCready|first1=Alastair|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Many reporters also questioned the practicality of using section 44 and so much resources to arrest one person for acknowledging a charge of a non-violent crime. It has been pointed out that it is more viable to try Luang Por Dhammajayo ''[[in absentia]]'' to determine guilt first.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/thai-authorities-contine-standoff-at-buddhist-temple/3743269.html|title=Thai Authorities Continue Standoff at Buddhist Temple|last=Corben|first=Ron|work=[[VOA]]|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1199953/misguided-section-44-use|title=Misguided Section 44 use|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=1 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1208953/dhammakaya-sagas-cost-is-too-high|title=Dhammakaya saga's cost is too high|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=6 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing}}</ref>\n[[File:Lone monk at Wat Phra Dhammakaya during article 44.jpg|thumb|A Wat Phra Dhammakaya monk stands at the edge of a barbed wire barricade of the temple set up by the junta.]]\nA few days before the lockdown was brought to a halt, it was announced in the [[Royal Thai Government Gazette]] that Luang Por Dhammajayo had his honorific title Phrathepyanmahamuni removed, because of the accusations he was charged with.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/politics/2017/03/05/hm-king-strips-dhammachayo-royal-title/|title=HM King strips dhammajayo of monk title|last=Charuvastra|first=Teeranai|work=[[Khao Sod]] English|publisher=Matichon Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/thai-king-strips-monastic-title-from-wanted-buddhist-abbot/415476884/|title=Thai king strips monastic title from wanted Buddhist abbot|date=6 March 2017|work=[[Star Tribune]]|access-date=13 March 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314063238/http://www.startribune.com/thai-king-strips-monastic-title-from-wanted-buddhist-abbot/415476884/|archivedate=14 March 2017}}</ref> The junta stated that after this announcement, they could and would immediately defrock Luang Por Dhammajayo if they were to find him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/thai/thailand-39176807|date=6 March 2017|work=[[BBC]] Thai|access-date=13 March 2017|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e2d\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e44\u0e23\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2a\u0e36\u0e01\u0e17\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e35|trans-title=Thai government reveals they will immediately defrock Phra Dhammajayo if they find him}}</ref>\n\nIn the middle of the lockdown of the temple, news reporting and social media activity about the event was very intensive. Writing for the liberal outlet Lok Wannee, a regular columnist argued that the response of government was similar to the aggressive anti-communist sentiment preceding the [[Thammasat University massacre]] on 6 October 1976.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ruang Jak Pok|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e32\u0e25\u0e40\u0e27\u0e25\u0e32\u0e1c\u0e31\u0e19\u0e1c\u0e48\u0e32\u0e19 '\u0e2d\u0e20\u0e34\u0e19\u0e34\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23' \u0e21\u0e34\u0e40\u0e04\u0e22\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e19|trans-title=After many years, the fairy tales are still the same|url=http://www.lokwannee.com/web2013/?p=262868|accessdate=7 January 2018|work=[[Lok Wannee]]|date=27 March 2017}}</ref> Kornkritch Somjittranukit from Prachatai expressed concern with the extent conservative news outlets such as [[Tnews]] and [[Manager Daily]] demonized the temple. He argued that this had a detrimental effect on society, raising as an example how the suicide of a devotee during the lockdown led many people on social media to express satisfaction.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Somjittranukit|first1=Kornkritch|title=Media efforts to justify junta's harassment of Dhammakaya|url=https://prachatai.com/english/node/6975|accessdate=7 January 2018|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Aftermath and revival ===\n\nFollowing the end of the lockdown of the temple, the junta stated authorities will look for Luang Por Dhammajayo elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/thailand-ends-hunt-for-fugitive-monk-at-temple-but-continues-search-elsewhere|title=Thailand ends hunt for fugitive monk at temple, but continues search elsewhere|last=Arpon|first=Yasmin Lee|date=10 March 2017|work=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref> However, investigations against the temple continued. Just days after the end of the lockdown, additional charges were filed against people of Wat Phra Dhammakaya, this time also against the deputy abbot, [[Luang Por Dattajivo]], for allegedly using the Klongchan Credit Union money to buy stocks and illegal land,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30309353|title=Temple money \"invested in shares\"|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)|The Nation]]|access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref> something the temple dubbed \"fake news\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism-idUSKBN16U0NU|title=Thailand seeks new abbot for scandal-hit Buddhist temple|date=23 March 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=24 March 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6wzQlSYJW?url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism/thailand-seeks-new-abbot-for-scandal-hit-buddhist-temple-idUSKBN16U0NU|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Khao Sod]] columnist became critical of the new charges, stating that weeks after the accusations were made neither the justice system nor DSI had produced any form of evidence supporting the allegations, describing the accusations as \"a new invention\" and improbable, because the temple would have no need for such money.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.khaosod.co.th/hot-topics/news_267078 |title=\u0e17\u0e33\u0e44\u0e21\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e2b\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\"\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\"\u0e08\u0e36\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e25\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e44\u0e1b |date=23 March 2017 |work=\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2a\u0e14 (Khao Sod) |access-date=28 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328033346/https://www.khaosod.co.th/hot-topics/news_267078 |archive-date=28 March 2017 |url-status=dead |language=th-TH }}</ref> As of March 2017, the junta had summoned 317 people involved with the temple to report or acknowledge charges.<ref name=\"Prachatai 2017\" />[[File:Monks from other temples protest Dhammakaya lockdown.jpg|left|thumb|Monks from various temples in Thailand chant in protest of the ''junta''<nowiki />'s lockdown of Wat Phra Dhammakaya]]\nWith both Wat Phra Dhammakaya's honorary and deputy abbot under investigation, the junta has pushed for a replacement abbot for the temple, with the junta-appointed director of the National Office of Buddhism calling for an outsider to be appointed the temple's abbot.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/thailand-buddhism-idINKBN1640EX|title=Thai junta replaces director of Buddhism department with policeman|work=[[Reuters India]]|access-date=24 March 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6wzPqSGw7?url=https://in.reuters.com/article/thailand-buddhism/thai-junta-replaces-director-of-buddhism-department-with-policeman-idINKBN1640EX|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This attempt was unsuccessful however, because the Thai Sangha considered this the responsibility of the temple.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/new-abbot-sought-to-replace-dhammajayo/1219965|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180204224359/https://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/new-abbot-sought-to-replace-dhammajayo/1219965|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live|title=New abbot sought to replace Dhammajayo|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=30 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Buddhism Office proposes appointment of new abbot of Dhammakaya temple|url=http://englishnews.thaipbs.or.th/buddhism-office-proposes-appointment-new-abbot-dhammakaya-temple/|accessdate=4 February 2018|work=[[Thai PBS]]|date=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072140/http://englishnews.thaipbs.or.th/buddhism-office-proposes-appointment-new-abbot-dhammakaya-temple/|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, news outlets described a \"revival\" of the temple, as the temple unexpectedly assigned a new person as abbot. This was an assistant-abbot who until thus far had been unknown to the press: Phrakhru Sangharak Rangsarit. At the same time, the temple announced it would organize a new city pilgrimage in March 2018, though it would be less publicly visible than the previous ones.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?&v=VSQ14hAOHpI|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|script-title=th:\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e04\u0e37\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e1e!|language=th|trans-title=Dhammakaya is revived!|date=14 December 2017|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?&v=mTVfbqI5XBs|script-title=th:\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e04\u0e34\u0e14\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e25\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e21\u0e32\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e18\u0e38\u0e14\u0e07\u0e04\u0e4c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22|language=th|trans-title=People's opinions about the revival of the Dhammachai Dhutanga of Wat Phra Dhammakaya|work=[[Amarin (Thailand)|Amarin]]|date=29 November 2017|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile the temple was planning a comeback, on 20 December the DSI did an unannounced search at night to find the former abbot still missing. Three buildings were searched, but no traces were found.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g-lZwaDEzF4|script-title=th:\u0e14\u0e35\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e2a\u0e44\u0e2d \u0e41\u0e17\u0e47\u0e01\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21 \u0e1e\u0e28. \u0e1a\u0e38\u0e01\u0e40\u0e07\u0e35\u0e22\u0e1a\u0e01\u0e25\u0e32\u0e07\u0e14\u0e36\u0e01\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e44\u0e23\u0e49\u0e40\u0e07\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e31\u0e21\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e42\u0e22|language=th|trans-title=DSI quietly enters Wat Dhammakaya at night, no traces of Phra Dhammajayo can be found|work=[[Spring News]]|date=22 December 2017|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Charuvastra|first1=Teeranai|title=Fugitive Abbot Not Found in New Dhammakaya Raid|url=http://www.khaosodenglish.com/news/crimecourtscalamity/2017/12/22/fugitive-abbot-not-found-new-dhammakaya-raid/|accessdate=4 February 2018|work=[[Khaosod English]]|date=22 December 2017}}</ref> Regardless, the Klongchan lawsuits continued, and on 2 February 2018, the attorney requested the court to seize four bank accounts of the temple's two foundations. The KCUC objected to this, however, and finally the court ordered that the money on the accounts, 58 million baht, be given to the credit union instead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Temple told to pay KCUC B58 million|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/crime/1405854/temple-told-to-pay-kcuc-b58-million|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180204223944/https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/crime/1405854/temple-told-to-pay-kcuc-b58-million|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=4 February 2018|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|date=2 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=th:\u0e28\u0e32\u0e25\u0e41\u0e1e\u0e48\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07 \u201c\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u201d \u0e04\u0e37\u0e19\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19 4 \u0e1a\u0e31\u0e0d\u0e0a\u0e35 \u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32 58 \u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19 \u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e2a\u0e2b\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e08\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19|trans-title=Civil court orders Wat Dhammakaya to return 58 M from 4 accounts to Klongchan Union|url=https://www.posttoday.com/social/general/538513|accessdate=4 February 2018|work=[[Post Today]]|date=1 February 2018|language=th}}</ref> In June 2018, the junta seized a 1.46 billion baht building at Wat Phra Dhammakaya, alleging that it was built using Klongchan Credit Union money.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1494662/ex-senior-monks-b135m-dhammakayas-building-frozen|title=Ex-senior monks' B135m, Dhammakaya's building frozen|last=Limited|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|date=|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-09-02}}</ref> In November 2018, the DSI filed additional charges once again of alleged money laundering, this time against a lay supporter who is the chair of the Dhammakaya Foundation. They proposed seizing most of the temple's properties and assets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/detail/national/30359547|title=DSI calls for dissolution of Dhammakaya-related foundation|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)|The Nation]]|date=30 November 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190211043904/http://www.nationmultimedia.com/detail/national/30359547|archive-date=11 February 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> In response, hundreds of thousands of the temple's followers returned over 3 million donation receipts to the temple to submit as evidence that the temple's properties were obtained through legal donations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.banmuang.co.th/news/education/141434 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210184056/http://www.banmuang.co.th/news/education/141434 |archive-date=10 February 2019 |url-status=live |work=Banmuang |language=th |script-title=th:\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e49\u0e04\u0e14\u0e35\u0e22\u0e36\u0e14\u0e17\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e4c!!!\u0e28\u0e34\u0e29\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e01\u0e32\u0e22\u0e17\u0e31\u0e48\u0e27\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01\u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e22\u0e37\u0e48\u0e19\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e38\u0e42\u0e21\u0e17\u0e19\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e15\u0e23 3 \u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e43\u0e1a |trans-title=Fighting the charges: Wat Phra Dhammakaya's pupils worldwide submit 3 million donation receipts |date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Dhammakaya tradition]]\n* [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]]\n* [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]]\n* [[Suppression of monasteries]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em|group=note}}\n\n== Citations ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Citation|last=Bechert|first=Heinz|title=Der moderne Theravada-Buddhismus in Sri Lanka und S\u00fcdostasien|url=https://www.buddhismuskunde.uni-hamburg.de/pdf/4-publikationen/buddhismus-in-geschichte-und-gegenwart/bd2-k08bechert.pdf|year=1997|volume=2|publisher=Asia-Africa Institute, ([[University of Hamburg]])|editor1-last=Mathes|editor2-last=Freese|editor1-first=Klaus-Dieter|editor2-first=Harald|language=de|trans-title=Modern Theravada Buddhism in Sri Lanka and Southeast Asia|encyclopedia=Buddhism in the Past and Present}}\n* {{Citation|title=Second to None: The Biography of Khun Yay Maharatana Upasika Chandra Khonnokyoong|url=http://en.dhammakayapost.org/download/book/04-Second-to-None.pdf|year=2005|author=Dhammakaya Foundation|location=Bangkok|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819002003/http://en.dhammakayapost.org/download/book/04-Second-to-None.pdf|archivedate=19 August 2016}}\n* {{Citation|title=Empire of Crystal and Utopian Commune: Two Types of Contemporary Theravada Reform in Thailand|date=1 January 1993|last1=Fuengfusakul|first1=Apinya|journal=[[Sojourn (journal)|Sojourn: Journal of Social Issues in Southeast Asia]]|volume=8|issue=1|pages=153\u2013183|jstor=41035731|doi=10.1355/SJ8-1G}}\n* {{Citation|url=http://www.cubs.chula.ac.th/images/research/58_2/Dhammakaya_Full.pdf|year=1998|last1=Fuengfusakul|first1=Apinya|publisher=Buddhist Studies Center, [[Chulalongkorn University]]|language=th|script-title=th:\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e17\u0e31\u0e28\u0e19\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e31\u0e22\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48: \u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e